vboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{SPFA Players' Player of the Year}}\n{{Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{West Ham United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Goal of the Season}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Swindon Town F.C. managers}}\n{{Sunderland A.F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Canio, Paolo}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rome]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:S.S. Lazio players]]\n[[Category:Ternana Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Napoli players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Atletico Roma F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Italy under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Pro Licence holders]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian neo-fascists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                = Paolo Di Canio\n | image               = Paolo Di Canio Upton Park 11 September 2010.jpg \n | image_size          = 200\n | caption             = Di Canio at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]], September 2010\n | fullname            = Paolo Di Canio<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{cite web |title=Paolo Di Canio |url=http://hugmansfootballers.com/player/5108 |work=Barry Hugman's Footballers |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n | birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1968|7|9|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n | birth_place         = [[Rome]], Italy<ref name=\"Hugman\"/>\n | height              = {{convert|1.78|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/l/l93618.html |title=Di Canio: Paolo Di Canio: Manager |publisher=BDFutbol |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n | position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n | currentclub         = \n | youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1   = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n | years1   = 1985\u20131990 | clubs1   = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] | caps1   = 54 | goals1   = 4\n | years2   = 1986\u20131987 | clubs2   = \u2192 [[Ternana Calcio|Ternana]] (loan) | caps2   = 27 | goals2   = 2\n | years3   = 1990\u20131993 | clubs3   = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] | caps3   = 78 | goals3   = 6\n | years4   = 1993\u20131994 | clubs4   = [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] | caps4   = 26 | goals4   = 5\n | years5   = 1994\u20131996 | clubs5   = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] | caps5   = 37 | goals5   = 6\n | years6   = 1996\u20131997 | clubs6   = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] | caps6   = 26 | goals6   = 12\n | years7   = 1997\u20131999 | clubs7   = [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] | caps7   = 41 | goals7   = 15\n | years8   = 1999\u20132003 | clubs8   = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | caps8   = 118 | goals8   = 47\n | years9   = 2003\u20132004 | clubs9   = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] | caps9   = 31 | goals9   = 4\n | years10  = 2004\u20132006 | clubs10  = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] | caps10  = 50 | goals10  = 11\n | years11  = 2006\u20132008 | clubs11  = [[Atletico Roma F.C.|Cisco Roma]] | caps11  = 46 | goals11  = 14\n | totalcaps = 534 | totalgoals = 126\n| nationalyears1       = 1988\u20131990\n| nationalteam1        = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U-21]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 9\n| nationalgoals1       = 2\n| nationalyears2       = 1989\n| nationalteam2        = [[Italy national football B team|Italy B]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-b-intres-det.html |title=England - International Results B-Team - Details |publisher=RSSSF |first=Barrie |last=Courtney |date=22 May 2014 |accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n| nationalcaps2        = 1\n| nationalgoals2       = 0\n | manageryears1 = 2011\u20132013 | managerclubs1 = [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n | manageryears2 = 2013      | managerclubs2 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n}}\n'''Paolo Di Canio''' (born 9 July 1968) is an Italian [[Association football|football]] manager and former professional footballer. During his playing career he made over 500 league appearances and scored over one hundred goals appearing primarily as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|deep-lying]] [[Forward (association football)|forward]] but could also play as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], or as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]]. A talented yet controversial player, Di Canio was known for his creativity, eye for goal, technical ability, and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills, as well as his temperamental character, tenacity and aggression on the pitch.<ref name=\"Di Canio, Paolo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Di_Canio_Paolo|title=Di Canio, Paolo|website=tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Paolo Di Canio\">{{cite web|url=http://ilpalloneracconta.blogspot.ca/2007/07/paolo-di-canio.html|title=Paolo Di Canio|publisher=Il Pallone Racconta|language=Italian|date=10 July 2014|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Paolo di Canio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magliarossonera.it/protagonisti/Gioc-Dicanio.html|title=Paolo di Canio|website=magliarossonera.it|language=Italian|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=tuttojuve.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-paolo-di-canio-196426|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Paolo DI CANIO|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author1=Stefano Bedeschi|date=10 July 2014|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/731574-epl-ranking-60-of-the-best-overseas-players-in-english-premier-league-history#slide15 |title=English Premier League: Ranking 60 of the Best Overseas Players in EPL History |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Thorpe |first1=Lee |date=14 June 2011 |accessdate=26 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\nDi Canio began his career in the Italian [[Serie A]], playing for [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] and [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], before a brief spell with the Scottish club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]. He subsequently spent seven years in the English [[Premier League]] with [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]. He returned to Italy in 2004, playing for Lazio and [[Atletico Roma F.C.|Cisco Roma]] before retiring in 2008. He played for the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italian under-21s]], making 9 appearances and scoring 2 goals, and was notably a member of the squad that finished in third place at the [[1990 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] under manager [[Cesare Maldini]], but was never capped for the [[Italy national football team|senior team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=401&squadra=1|title=Nazionale in Cifre: Convocazioni e presenze in campo - Di Canio, Paolo|website=figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong the individual awards he received as a player, Di Canio was named [[SPFA Players' Player of the Year]] in 1997 and West Ham's [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|player of the season]] in 2000. However, his career was at times characterised by controversy: he received an eleven-match ban in 1998 for pushing a referee and attracted negative publicity over his self allegiance to [[Italian fascism|fascism]].\n\nIn 2011, Di Canio entered football management in England with [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]], guiding them in his first full season as manager to promotion to [[Football League One|League One]]. He was appointed as the [[Sunderland F.C.|Sunderland]] manager at the end of March 2013. His controversial appointment lasted 13 games until he was sacked on 22 September after Sunderland had won only three games under his managership.\n\n==Early life==\nDi Canio was born in Rome, in the district of Quarticciolo, a working-class area populated mainly by [[A.S. Roma]] fans. However, Di Canio was drawn to their local rivals [[S.S. Lazio]]. As a young boy, he was addicted to cola and similar drinks and called ''Pallocca'', a slang term meaning ''lard-ball''. He was fat, and knock-kneed, and needed to wear orthopedic shoes \u2013 \"But I never hid. My response was to exercise; to try to become the kind of person I am.\"<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/paolo-di-canio-my-life-speaks-for-me-6273526.html |title=Paolo Di Canio: 'My life speaks for me' \u2013 Profiles \u2013 People |work=The Independent |date=11 December 2011 |accessdate=2013-04-03 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHe signed for [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] in 1985 and remained there until 1990. Lazio won promotion to Serie A in 1988, having narrowly escaped relegation to [[Serie C1]] the year before. He finally made his first-team debut in October 1988 and went on to play 30 games during the [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389 season]].<ref name=\"ffile\">{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12028/8936979/paolo-di-canio-factfile|title=Paolo Di Canio factfile|publisher=Sky Sports|date=23 September 2013|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> Di Canio scored the winner in the first [[Derby della Capitale|Rome derby]] of the season, a goal which contributed to Lazio's survival in Serie A that season and earning him hero status. In 1990, he was sold to another of Italy's biggest clubs, [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]];<ref name=\"ffile\" /> although he won the [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] with the Turin side in 1993, he struggled to gain playing time during his tenure with the club, due to the presence of other forwards and creative midfielders in the team, such as [[Roberto Baggio]], [[Salvatore Schillaci]], [[Pierluigi Casiraghi]], [[Fabrizio Ravanelli]], [[Gianluca Vialli]], and [[Andreas M\u00f6ller]].<ref name=tuttojuve.com/> He left Juventus after an \"animated exchange\" with then manager [[Giovanni Trapattoni]]<ref name=\"independent1\" /><ref name=\"agr\">{{cite web|last=Fisher|first=Stewart|title=Is Di Canio a martyr or does he have a hidden agenda?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/is-di-canio-a-martyr-or-does-he-have-a-hidden-agenda.20274802|publisher=Herald Scotland|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=20 February 2013}}</ref> and spent the [[1993\u201394 Serie A|1993\u201394]] season with [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]].<ref name=\"independent1\" /> Two seasons followed at [[A.C. Milan]], where, despite winning the [[1995\u201396 Serie A|Serie A title in 1996]], he once again struggled to gain playing time due to heavy competition from his teammates, culminating in another row, this time with [[Fabio Capello]].<ref name=\"independent1\" /><ref name=\"agr\" /><ref name=tuttojuve.com/><ref name=\"Paolo di Canio\"/>\n\n===Celtic===\nIn July 1996 he joined [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in Scotland, and enjoyed a successful season in [[Glasgow]], scoring 15 goals in 37 appearances<ref>{{cite web|last=Haggerty|first=Anthony|title=Subbuteo team was reason I joined Celtic, admits Paolo Di Canio|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/subbuteo-team-was-reason-i-joined-celtic-1002987|publisher=Daily Record|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=24 December 2008}}</ref>  and winning the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|SPFA Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=\"celt1\">{{cite web|title=Di Canio's Celtic years: good, bad and ugly|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/di-canio-s-celtic-years-good-bad-and-ugly-1-3106641|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=23 September 2013}}</ref>  His time in Glasgow was dogged by controversy though; sent-off during a 2\u20132 draw against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in November 1996<ref>{{cite news|title=Paolo's Italian for loco|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1996-11-30%3A+Celtic+2-2+Hearts,+Premier+Division|accessdate=30 January 2014|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=1 December 1996}}</ref>  and heavily involved in an acrimonious league match against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in March 1997 where he behaved aggressively towards [[Ian Ferguson (footballer born 1967)|Ian Ferguson]] and gestured in the direction of Rangers\u2019 bench as he was led from the field by teammates.<ref name=\"celt1\" /> The Italian was called to the referee\u2019s room after the teams had returned to the dressing room and was shown another yellow card in addition to the one he had received earlier in the game.<ref name=\"celt1\" /> Di Canio then demanded a large wage rise at the end of the season, but this was rebuffed by Celtic.<ref name=\"celt1\" />  He then refused to join the Celtic squad in the Netherlands for their pre-season training during July 1997.<ref name=\"ffile\" />\n\n===Sheffield Wednesday===\nOn 6 August 1997, Di Canio moved to the English [[Premier League|Premiership]] as he joined [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in a transfer deal valued at around \u00a34.2 million.<ref name=\"celt1\" /> Whilst in Sheffield, Di Canio was the club's leading goal scorer for the [[1997\u201398 in English football|1997\u201398]] season with 14 goals and he became a favourite of the fans.\n\nIn September 1998, Di Canio pushed referee [[Paul Alcock]] to the ground after being sent off while playing for Sheffield Wednesday against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at Hillsborough, which resulted in an extended ban of 11 matches<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/199792.stm|title=Di Canio gets 11-match ban for push on ref |date=23 October 1998|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and him being fined \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/199527.stm|title=Di Canio ban too short, say referees |date=24 October 1998|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\n[[File:Paolo Di Canio playing at Tony Carr's testimonial, May 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Di Canio playing in [[Tony Carr]]'s testimonial match in 2010]]\n\nIn January 1999, Di Canio signed for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for \u00a31.5 million. He had not played football since his ban following his push on Paul Alcock. West Ham manager, [[Harry Redknapp]] on signing Di Canio admitted he was taking a chance but said of the player \"He can do things with the ball that people can only dream of\". Di Canio said of his ban, \"I made a mistake and I'm sorry, West Ham have given me a big chance and I'm very happy\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/jan/28/newsstory.sport | title=West Ham sign \u00a31.5m Di Canio | work=The Guardian | date=28 January 1999 | accessdate=30 January 2014 | author=Brodkin, Jon}}</ref> He scored his first goal for West Ham on 27 February 1999 in his fourth game. Playing against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], Di Canio made the first goal in a 2\u20130 win, for [[Ian Pearce]] in the 27th minute and scored the second in the 31st minute.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://football.theguardian.com/Observer_Match_Report/0,,-12997,00.html | title=Di Canio strikes right note | work=The Guardian | date=27 February 1999 | accessdate=31 January 2014 | author=Callow, Nick}}</ref> He helped them to achieve a high league position (5th) and qualify for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] through the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup|Intertoto Cup]]. He was also the OPTA player of the season [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]]. He scored the BBC [[BBC Goal of the Season|Goal of the Season]] in March 2000 with a flying volley against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/premiership/westham/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/00/03/26/SOCCER_West_Ham.html&TEAMHD=westham&DIV=prem&TEAM=WEST--HAM&RH=West--Ham&PREV_SEASON=1998 |title=West Ham 2 Wimbledon 1 |work=Sporting Life|location=UK |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> which is still considered among the best goals in Premiership history<ref>{{cite web|last=Raynor |first=Dominic |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=688402&cc=5739 |title=Paolo Di Canio: Explosive Italian |publisher=ESPN FC |date=23 October 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> and was named as the Premiership's goal of the decade in a December 2009 [[Sky Sports News]] viewers' poll, scoring 30% of votes.<ref>{{Cite episode\n| title = Football Tonight| network = [[British Sky Broadcasting|BSkyB]]| series = [[Sky Sports News]]| airdate = 31 December 2009 | minutes = 50 (approx)}}</ref> In this season he was also voted [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] by the club's fans.\n\nIn December 2000, late in a game against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and with both sides vying for the winning goal, Di Canio shunned a goal-scoring opportunity and stopped play, grabbing the ball from a cross inside the [[penalty area|box]], as the Everton goalkeeper [[Paul Gerrard]] was lying injured on the ground after he twisted his knee attempting a clearance on the edge of the box. The [[Goodison Park]] crowd reacted with a standing ovation.  FIFA officially lauded Di Canio's gesture, describing it as \"a special act of good sportsmanship,\"<ref name=\"Fair Play award\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1682501.stm |title=Di Canio wins Fair Play award |publisher=BBC News |date=17 December 2001 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> and awarded him next year the [[FIFA Fair Play Award]].\n\n[[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] tried to sign him for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] halfway through the [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302 season]], but his attempts were unsuccessful and Di Canio remained in [[East End of London|East London]] for another season and a half.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/manchester_united/s/1023534_ferguson_21_that_got_away |title=Ferguson: 21 that got away \u2013 Manchester Evening News |publisher=Menmedia.co.uk |date=8 November 2007 |accessdate=2013-04-03}}</ref> Di Canio insisted that he wouldn't be able to leave West Ham, who had handed him a lifeline in the worst moment in his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football365.com/news/paolo-di-canio-alex-ferguson-reaction-rejected-man-utd |title=Di Canio reveals Ferguson reaction after he rejected Man Utd |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, with the Hammers struggling at the bottom of the league, Di Canio had a very public row with manager [[Glenn Roeder]] and was dropped from the first team. However, he returned at the end of the season (after Roeder, stricken by a brain tumour, was replaced by [[Trevor Brooking]]) and scored a winner against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the penultimate game of the season, a game that boosted West Ham's chances of staying in the Premiership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2968013.stm |title=Di Canio grabs West Ham lifeline |publisher=BBC News |date=3 May 2003 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> However, they were relegated on the final day of the season after a 2\u20132 draw away to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], where Di Canio scored an 89th-minute equaliser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/cc_championship/westham/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/03/05/11/SOCCER_Birmingham.html&TEAMHD=westham&DIV=nat1&TEAM=WEST--HAM&RH=West--Ham&PREV_SEASON=2001 |title=Birmingham 2 West Ham 2 |work=Sporting Life|location=UK |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> He was released on a free transfer and signed  with [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] for the start of the [[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304 season]].<ref name=\"ch1\">{{cite news|title=Di Canio joins Charlton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/3142339.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 January 2014|date=11 August 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nIn his one season at [[The Valley (London)|The Valley]], Di Canio helped [[Charlton Athletic]] finish the season in 7th position, the club's highest league finish since the 1950s. However, he only scored four league goals for the Addicks, all of which came from the penalty spot (one from a rebound). one of the penalty kicks was an audacious '[[Anton\u00edn Panenka#Panenka penalty|Panenka]]' style penalty kick against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arsenal back on top|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3206860.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 January 2014|date=26 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Matt|title=Extra time with Paolo Di Canio|url=http://www.votvonline.com/back-issues/memories-of-paolo/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140130134621/http://www.votvonline.com/back-issues/memories-of-paolo/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2014|publisher=Voice of the Valley|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>  Di Canio however continued to be a provider of goals as well, notably in October 2003 when he came on as second-half substitute with Charlton trailing 0\u20131 away at [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. He provided most of the spark for Charlton's much-improved second-half display, and after [[Jonathan Fortune]] had equalised for Charlton, it was from Di Canio's corner kick in the last minute that [[Shaun Bartlett]] headed home the winning goal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlton snatch late win|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3123632.stm|accessdate=30 January 2014|date=4 October 2003|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Jimmy|title=CAFC Moments: Di Canio inspires comeback|url=http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/20131121-cafc-moments-paolo-di-canio-1188285.aspx|publisher=cafc.co.uk|accessdate=30 January 2014|date=21 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201194633/http://www.cafc.co.uk/news/article/20131121-cafc-moments-paolo-di-canio-1188285.aspx|archivedate=1 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Italy===\nEven though he had already signed an extension to his Charlton contract, in August 2004 he returned to his home team of [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] taking a massive pay cut in order to return to the economically stretched Roman team.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/aug/06/newsstory.charltonathletic</ref>  Lazio fans were happy to have a Rome-bred Lazio supporter in the team again, something missing since the departure of [[Alessandro Nesta]] in 2002. He scored in the [[Rome derby]], just as he had in 1989, leading the team to a 3\u20131 victory over [[A.S. Roma]] in January (6 January 2005). However the negative publicity that Di Canio generated for Lazio, including his intimate relationship with club's [[ultras]] and their increased influence thanks to his presence in the team, coupled with problems with some teammates and coaches, exasperated club president and majority shareholder, [[Claudio Lotito]], with whom he already had a difficult relationship. As a result, Di Canio's contract was not renewed in the summer of 2006. During several of his games for Lazio \u2013 including during [[goal celebration]]s \u2013 Di Canio made a fascist salute to their right-wing fans.<ref>{{cite news |title=I'm a fascist, not a racist, says Paolo di Canio |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1506262/Im-a-fascist-not-a-racist-says-Paolo-di-Canio.html |accessdate=9 October 2018 |work=Telegraph}}</ref> He subsequently signed with [[Atletico Roma F.C.|Cisco Roma]] of [[Serie C2]] on a free transfer. In his first season with Cisco Roma, his team failed promotion to playoffs, despite a runners-up position in the regular season. He subsequently agreed to stay with Cisco for another season, in a second attempt to win promotion to [[Serie C1]] with the Roman side.\n\nOn 10 March 2008, Di Canio announced his retirement from football, ending his 23-year playing career before the end of the season due to physical issues. It was his intention to begin coaching lessons at [[Centro Tecnico Federale di Coverciano|Coverciano]] to gain a coaching position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.eurosport.yahoo.com/10032008/44/canio-smette-giocare-addio-cisco-roma-86.html|title=Di Canio Smette di giocare, addio alla Cisco Roma|date=10 March 2008|publisher=[[Eurosport|Yahoo! Eurosport Italia]]}}</ref> In an interview he revealed that his dream would be to manage former club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]], and applied for the position after the resignation of [[Alan Curbishley]] in September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/7598744.stm|title=Di Canio wants to be Hammers boss|date=4 September 2008|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Di Canio played in [[Tony Carr|Tony Carr's]] testimonial game at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]] on 5 May 2010, which featured a West Ham team against West Ham [[The Academy of Football|Academy]] old boys. He played for both sides during the match. The West Ham team won 5\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100506/paolos-pride_2236884_2044685 |title=Paolo's pride |publisher=Whufc.com |accessdate=12 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509041725/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100506/paolos-pride_2236884_2044685 |archivedate=9 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In July 2010, in honour of Di Canio, West Ham announced the opening of the Paolo Di Canio Lounge, within the West Stand, at their [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]] ground,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100716/take-your-seat-in-the-di-canio-lounge_2236884_2093957 |title=Take your seat in the Di Canio Lounge &#124; West Ham United |publisher=Whufc.com |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718092059/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100716/take-your-seat-in-the-di-canio-lounge_2236884_2093957 |archivedate=18 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which was formally launched by the unveiling of a plaque by Di Canio himself, on 11 September 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100913/di-canio-lounge-a-hit_2236884_2152448 |title=Di Canio Lounge a hit |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |accessdate=13 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916014138/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20100913/di-canio-lounge-a-hit_2236884_2152448 |archivedate=16 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Swindon Town===\n[[File:Paolo Di Canio at Upton Park.jpg|thumb|upright|Di Canio at the [[Boleyn Ground]], [[Upton Park, London|Upton Park]] in 2010]]\n\nOn 20 May 2011, Di Canio was appointed manager of [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on a two-year contract, following the club's relegation to League Two.<ref>{{cite news |title=Swindon Town confirm Paolo Di Canio as new manager |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/13466915 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2011 |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> Di Canio began his career as a manager with a 3\u20130 win over [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 6 August 2011.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} On 30 August 2011, Di Canio was involved in a pitch-side altercation with Swindon striker [[Leon Clarke]] after their defeat in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/sportlatest/9226141.Time_called_on_Clarke/ |title=Time called on Clarke  |work=Swindon Advertiser |date=1 September 2011 |accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref> In January 2012, Swindon caused a [[2011\u201312 FA Cup|FA Cup]] shock by defeating [[Premier League]] club [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] 2\u20131. Di Canio stated that he believed his players deserved to have their names put on the stadium and dedicated the victory to his father, who died late in 2011.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16372054.stm | title=Swindon 2 \u2013 1 Wigan | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | date=7 January 2012 | accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> He was sent to the stands later in the month in a league game against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] for vociferously venting his frustration at his side not being awarded a free-kick. Swindon won the match 1\u20130 and with over half the season gone, his team were fighting for promotion to [[EFL League One|League One]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16559842.stm | title=Swindon 1 \u2013 0 Macclesfield | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | date=21 January 2012 | accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nUnder Di Canio, Swindon reached the [[2012 Football League Trophy Final]], where they were defeated 2\u20130 by [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/mar/25/chesterfield-swindon-johnstones-paint-trophy-final|title=Chesterfield 2-0 Swindon Town {{!}} Johnstone's Paint Trophy match report|last=Wembley|first=Sachin Nakrani at|date=2012-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April 2012, Swindon were promoted to the League One after [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]]'s 1\u20131 draw with [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] and [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]'s 2\u20130 loss to [[AFC Wimbledon]], despite Di Canio's side having lost 3\u20131 to [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] on the same day. He dedicated the promotion to his parents, his mother having died shortly after his father in April of that year.<ref name=Robinspromotion>{{cite news|last=Crook|first=Alex|title=Gillingham 3 Swindon Town 1: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/league-two/9218843/Gillingham-3-Swindon-Town-1-match-report.html|accessdate=22 April 2012|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=21 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> One week later, Swindon won the [[Football League Two]] thanks to an emphatic 5\u20130 victory over [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]].<ref name=\"Port Vale\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17795329 |title=Swindon 5\u20130 Port Vale |publisher=BBC |date=28 April 2012 |accessdate=2013-04-03}}</ref> Swindon finished the season on 93 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballsite.co.uk/Statistics/LeagueTables/Season2011-12/League22011-12.htm |title=Football League 2 table 2011/12 |publisher=footballsite |accessdate=2013-04-03}}</ref>\n\nAlthough in the 2012\u201313 season, Swindon were knocked out of the [[FA Cup]] and the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] in their first game against opposition from lower leagues, they did have a solid run in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in which they won against three teams from higher leagues. They beat [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] 3\u20130, won against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] 3\u20134 [[Overtime (sports)|after extra time]], and beat [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] 3\u20131 before narrowly missing out against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 3\u20132 at home.\n\nIn January 2013, with Swindon under a transfer embargo and in financial difficulty, Di Canio offered to pay \u00a330,000 of his own money to keep loan players [[John Bostock]], [[Chris Martin (footballer, born 1988)|Chris Martin]] and [[Danny Hollands]] at the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paolo Di Canio offers own money to keep Swindon players|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20928212|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2013, ahead of Swindon's Saturday clash with [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]], Di Canio worked into the night alongside approximately 200 volunteers to clear a snow-covered pitch at the [[County Ground, Swindon|County Ground]], thus allowing the game to go ahead. He showed his appreciation by ordering everyone pizza. Swindon won the match 2\u20130, which Di Canio publicly deemed a present to the volunteers.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/01/19/paolo-di-canio-shovels-snow-off-swindon-pitch-and-orders-pizza-for-helpers-3358148/ | title=Paolo Di Canio shovels snow off Swindon pitch and orders pizza for helpers | publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | date=19 January 2013 | accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/news/article/pdcvictoryapresent-608835.aspx | title=PDC \u2013 Victory a present | publisher=Swindon Town FC | date=19 January 2013 | accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.swindontownfc.co.uk/news/article/shrewsgameon-607948.aspx | title=Shrewsbury game on | publisher=Swindon Town FC | date=19 January 2013 | accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, the Swindon Town chairman announced that due to financial difficulties, no money would be made available for future signings. Di Canio offered to pay \u00a330,000 of his own money to keep loan players at the club. With the possibility of the club entering administration, a new buyer was found, subject to Football League approval, and without the knowledge of Di Canio, player [[Matt Ritchie]] was sold to [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]]. Further attempts to sign players by Di Canio were rejected by the Football League due to the club's financial situation with Di Canio \"considering his future\" at Swindon due to off-field financial problems. In February, Di Canio offered his resignation but said he would withdraw this if approval for the new owners, by the Football League, was received by 18 February. This did not happen and he resigned as manager of Swindon Town.<ref>{{cite news |title=Paolo Di Canio quits as manager of Swindon Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21499926 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 February 2013 |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\nOn 31 March 2013, [[Sunderland A.F.C|Sunderland]] appointed Di Canio as manager on a two-and-a-half-year contract, following the dismissal of [[Martin O'Neill]] the previous day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Paolo Di Canio appointed Sunderland head coach |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21990117 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> The appointment prompted the immediate resignation of club vice-chairman [[David Miliband]] due to Di Canio's \"past political statements\".<ref name=\"miliband\">{{cite news|title=David Miliband quits Sunderland FC in Di Canio protest|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/01/david-miliband-resign-sunderland-di-canio|newspaper=The Guardian|date=1 April 2013|accessdate=1 April 2013|location=London|first=Ben|last=Quinn}}</ref> The appointment of Di Canio also sparked opposition from the [[Durham Miners' Association]],<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-22049080 | work=BBC News | title=Miners' Di Canio protest 'will only end with Sunderland campaign support' | date=6 April 2013}}</ref> which decided to remove one of its mining banners from Sunderland's [[Stadium of Light]], which is built on the former site of the [[Monkwearmouth Colliery]], as a symbol of its anger over the appointment.<ref>[http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved Durham Miners' Association: Our Issues With Di Canio At Sunderland Now Resolved - Sky Tyne and Wear<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625103549/http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62109/durham-miners-association-our-issues-with-di-canio-now-resolved |date=25 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/apr/02/paolo-di-canio-sunderland-miners-banner | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Matthew | last=Taylor | title=Sunderland miners demand return of banner after Paolo Di Canio's arrival | date=2 April 2013}}</ref> The background to the opposition was past statements made by Di Canio supporting [[fascism]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/miners-join-opposition-to-paolo-di-canios-appointment-at-sunderland-8556525.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Miners join opposition to Paolo Di Canio's appointment at Sunderland | date=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nDi Canio was tasked with keeping Sunderland in the [[Premier League]], following a run of only three points from a possible 24. His first game as manager of Sunderland resulted in a 2\u20131 away defeat to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/8624046/Premier-League-round-u | work=Sky Sports | title=Premier League round-up \u2013 Sky Sports}}</ref> Di Canio's second game in charge was the [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] at [[St James' Park]] on 14 April. Sunderland defeated their fierce rivals 3\u20130, their first away victory in the fixture in over a decade. Each goal sparked wild celebrations from Di Canio and the Sunderland bench.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22056537|title= Newcastle 0 Sunderland 3|date=14 April 2013|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=24 April 2013 }}</ref> Di Canio then got his first win at the Stadium of Light against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/premier-league/10007646/Sunderland-1-Everton-0-match-report.html|title=Sunderland 1 Everton 0|date=20 April 2013|work=Daily Telegraph\n|accessdate=24 April 2013|location=London|first=Luke|last=Edwards}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the team did not win the next three matches, including drawing the final two home games and a heavy 6\u20131 defeat to [[Aston Villa]], Sunderland secured their Premier League survival when [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] were defeated at [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and relegated, trailing then-17th placed Sunderland by four points with only one game to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/130514/football-podolski-double-condemns-wigan-relegation-0|title=Podolski double condemns Wigan to relegation|date=14 May 2013|work=Global Post\n|accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[2013\u201314 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season, Di Canio signed fourteen new players and sold experienced players such as [[Simon Mignolet]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/10142422/Liverpool-sign-Sunderland-goalkeeper-Simon-Mignolet.html | title=Liverpool sign Sunderland goalkeeper Simon Mignolet | publisher=Daily Telegraph | date=25 June 2013 | accessdate=24 September 2013 | author=Edwards, Luke | location=London}}</ref> [[James McClean]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23631972 | title=Wigan: James McClean took pay cut to join - Owen Coyle | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> and [[St\u00e9phane Sess\u00e8gnon]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/sunderland/10322293/Sunderland-manager-Paolo-Di-Canio-I-had-to-sell-Stephane-Sessegnon-to-West-Bromwich-Albion.html | title=Sunderland manager Paolo Di Canio: I had to sell Stephane Sessegnon to West Bromwich Albion | publisher=Daily Telegraph | date=20 September 2013 | accessdate=24 September 2013 | author=Edwards, Luke | location=London}}</ref> After five league games, Sunderland had gained only a single point, from an away draw with [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23737155 | title=Southampton 1-1 Sunderland | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> Di Canio was dismissed on 22 September 2013, the day after the fifth match of the season, a 3\u20130 defeat to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], and only his 13th match in charge.<ref name=\"Paolo Di Canio: Sunderland reign that lasted only six months\">{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Rose |title=Paolo Di Canio: Sunderland reign that lasted only six months |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24199482 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2013 |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> Sunderland chief executive officer Margaret Byrne stated that Di Canio had been sacked after senior players had approached her and that his situation became untenable due to his \"brutal and vitriolic\" criticism of the squad.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24214706 | title=Paolo Di Canio: Sunderland players met CEO before sacking | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> Di Canio denies this.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24356449|title=Paolo Di Canio denies bust-up with players caused Sunderland exit|publisher=[[BBC]]|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 October 2013|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent managerial links===\nDi Canio was linked with the [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] job in May 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/26/paolo-di-canio-celtic-manager|title=Paolo Di Canio puts himself forward for Celtic manager's job|date=26 May 2014|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> and applied for vacant managerial positions at [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in October 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/oct/08/paolo-di-canio-neil-lennon-bolton-wanderers|title=Paolo Di Canio and Neil Lennon apply for job as Bolton Wanderers manager|last=Hunter|first=Andy|date=8 October 2014|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>, and [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] in September 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/30/paolo-di-canio-reject-rotherham-united|title=Rotherham reject approach from Paolo Di Canio over manager's job|date=30 September 2015|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> and again in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/08/paolo-di-canio-rotherham-job|title=Paolo Di Canio applies for Rotherham manager job for second time|date=8 February 2016|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nIn 2005, he characterised his political views by declaring that he was \"a fascist, not a racist\".<ref name=\"telegraphreport\">{{cite news|last=Fenton |first=Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1506262/Im-a-fascist-not-a-racist-says-Paolo-di-Canio.html |title=I'm a fascist, not a racist, says Paolo di Canio |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=24 December 2005 |accessdate=1 May 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nHis use of the [[Roman salute]] toward [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] supporters, a gesture adopted by [[Italian Fascism|Italian fascists]] in the 20th century, has created controversy. Documented uses of the salute include in matches against arch-rivals [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] and [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]], a club inclined to left-wing politics.<ref name=\"Kassimeris\">{{cite book|last=Kassimeris|first=Christos |title=European football in black and white: tackling racism in football |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2008|page=70|isbn=9780739119600}}</ref> Di Canio received a one-match ban after the second event and was fined \u20ac7,000.<ref name=\"Bar-On\">{{cite book|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir |title=Where have all the fascists gone?|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2007|page=1|isbn=9780754671541}}</ref> He was later quoted as saying, \"I will always salute as I did because it gives me a sense of belonging to my people ... I saluted my people with what for me is a sign of belonging to a group that holds true values, values of civility against the standardisation that this society imposes upon us.\"<ref name=\"Nursey\">{{cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-139900733 |title=Football: ll Di Canio new salute row |last=Nursey |first=James |date=19 December 2005 |work=Daily Mirror |location=London (UK) |accessdate=28 February 2013}}</ref> His salute has been featured on unofficial merchandise sold outside [[Stadio Olimpico]] after the ban.<ref name=\"Kassimeris\" />\n\nHe has also expressed admiration for the fascist dictator [[Benito Mussolini]]. In his 2001 autobiography ''Paolo Di Canio: l'Autobiografia'' (Paolo Di Canio: The Autobiography), published by ''Libreria dello Sport'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.libreriadellosport.it/libri/paolo-di-canio---l-autobiografia.php |title=PAOLO DI CANIO - L'AUTOBIOGRAFIA |publisher=www.libreriadellosport.it |language=Italian |accessdate=12 September 2019 }}</ref> he praised Mussolini as \"basically a very principled, ethical individual\" who was \"deeply misunderstood\".<ref name=\"independentarticle\">{{cite news|title=Paolo Di Canio: 'My life speaks for me'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/paolo-di-canio-my-life-speaks-for-me-6273526.html|work=The Independent|date=11 December 2013|accessdate=1 April 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4158591.stm|title=Footballer's 'fascist salute' row |last=Duff|first=Mark|date=9 January 2005|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Di Canio attended the funeral of senior fascist [[Paolo Signorelli (politician)|Paolo Signorelli]], where mourners were photographed making mass fascist salutes towards Signorelli's coffin.<ref>[http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/news/article/2644/paolo-di-canio-at-bomb-fascists-funeral HOPE not hate news: Paolo Di Canio at bomb fascist\u2019s funeral<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406032230/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/news/article/2644/paolo-di-canio-at-bomb-fascists-funeral |date=6 April 2013}}</ref> Signorelli had been convicted of involvement in the [[Bologna massacre]], a neo-fascist terrorist attack which killed 85 people and wounded more than 200.<ref name=Zavoli>Sergio Zavoli, ''La notte della Repubblica'', Nuova Eri, 1992 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nDi Canio's political ideology has been a source of controversy in the course of his managerial career. When Di Canio was appointed as the manager of [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in 2011, the trade union [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] terminated its sponsorship agreement with the club, worth around \u00a34,000 per season, due to Di Canio's fascist views.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/may/21/swindon-di-canio-sponsor-gmb</ref>\n\nHe was appointed as manager of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 31 March 2013. The club's vice-chairman [[David Miliband]], a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and former [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|foreign secretary]], subsequently stepped down. Miliband stated that he had taken the decision to resign \"in the light of the new manager's past political statements\".<ref name=\"miliband\" />\n\nIn a profile piece in 2011, an unnamed source asserted that Di Canio was not \"an ideological fascist\", attributing his behaviour to \"his psychological history, particularly his former compulsive tendencies and pronounced mood swings\". In the same article, Di Canio said that he was not politically active: \"I don't vote, I haven't voted for 14 years. Italian politicians\u2014all of them\u2014think only about themselves, and making money.\"<ref name=\"independentarticle\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nDi Canio has several tattoos, including on his right [[biceps]] the [[Latin language|Latin]] word \"''DUX''\", meaning \"''leader''\" or, in Italian, [[duce|Il Duce]]\u2014a nickname for [[Benito Mussolini]].<ref name=Tatts>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/sports/political%2Bfootball%2Bpaolo%2Bdi%2Bcanio/1643547.html |title=Political Football: Paolo Di Canio|date=26 April 2008|publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=19 May 2011}}</ref> [[Sky Italia|Sky Sport Italia]] was forced to apologize after Di Canio appeared as a pundit in September 2016 in a short-sleeved shirt, thus revealing the tattoo to television viewers; he was later suspended by the station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/14/sky-sport-italia-suspends-paolo-di-canio-after-showing-dux-tattoo|title=Sky Sport Italia suspends Paolo Di Canio after showing 'dux' tattoo|last=Dobson|first=Mark|date=14 September 2016|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> His back is covered with a tattoo of fascist imagery, including an eagle, [[fasces]] and a portrait of Mussolini.<ref>https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-wednesday/latest-owls-news/mussolini-tattoos-and-fascist-salutes-troubling-political-history-former-sheffield-wednesday-forward-paolo-di-canio-1306644</ref> He also has a [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] tattoo on his left upper arm<ref>https://www.hammers.news/columnist/where-are-they-now-paolo-di-canio/</ref> and a tattoo of his father on his chest.<ref>{{cite web|last=Warren |first=Andy |url=http://www.swindonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/sportlatest/9679359.The_man_with_the_Swindon_tattoo/ |title=The man with the Swindon tattoo (From Swindon Advertiser) |publisher=Swindonadvertiser.co.uk |date=1 May 2012 |accessdate=2013-04-03}}</ref>\n\nDi Canio has spoken also of the growing influence in his life of [[Samurai]] culture, and of the Japanese spiritual mentality from reading [[Yukio Mishima|Mishima]], and the teachings in the traditions of [[Hagakure]] and [[Bushido]].<ref name=\"independent1\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club!!rowspan=\"2\"|Season!!colspan=\"3\"|League!!colspan=\"2\"|Cup{{ref|a|1}}!!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup{{ref|a|2}}!!colspan=\"2\"|Continental{{ref|a|3}}!!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref|a|4}}!!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Ternana Calcio|Ternana]] (loan)||1986\u201387||[[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione|Serie C2]]||27||2||6||3||rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||33||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]||[[1988\u201389 S.S. Lazio season|1988\u201389]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Serie A]]||30||1||6||1||36||4\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 S.S. Lazio season|1989\u201390]]||24||3||2||1||26||4\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!54!!4!!8!!2!!colspan=\"6\"|\u2014!!62!!6\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]||[[1990\u201391 Juventus F.C. season|1990\u201391]]||rowspan=\"3\"|Serie A||23||3||6||0||rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0||rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||34||3\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Juventus F.C. season|1991\u201392]]||24||0||9||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||1\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Juventus F.C. season|1992\u201393]]||31||3||4||0||9||0||44||4\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!78!!6!!19!!1!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!14!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!111!!7\n|-\n|[[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]||[[1993\u201394 S.S.C. Napoli season|1993\u201394]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Serie A]]||26||5||1||0||rowspan=\"3\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||col