]]||Premier League||31||4||1||0||1||1||colspan=\"4\"|\u2014||33||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]||[[2004\u201305 S.S. Lazio season|2004\u201305]]||rowspan=\"2\"|Serie A||23||6||1||0||rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||1||1||0||30||7\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 S.S. Lazio season|2005\u201306]]||27||5||1||0||4||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!50!!11!!2!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!9!!3!!1!!0!!62!!14\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[A.S. Cisco Calcio Roma|Cisco Roma]]||[[2006\u201307 Serie C2|2006\u201307]]||rowspan=\"2\"|Serie C2||28||7||5||3||rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||33||10\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Serie C2|2007\u201308]]||18||7||2||0||20||7\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!46!!14!!7!!3!!colspan=\"6\"|\u2014!!53!!17\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals!!534!!126!!64!!14!!15!!5!!46!!4!!1!!0!!670!!149\n|}\n*1.{{note|a}}Includes [[Coppa Italia]], [[Scottish Cup]] and [[FA Cup]]\n*2.{{note|a}}Includes [[Scottish League Cup]] and [[EFL Cup]].\n*3.{{note|a}}Includes [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]].\n*4.{{note|a}}Includes [[Supercoppa Italiana]].\n\n===Managerial statistics===\n{{updated|22 September 2013}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]]\n|align=left|20 May 2011\n|align=left|18 February 2013\n{{WDL|95|54|18|23|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"Managers: Paolo Di Canio\"/>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|align=left|31 March 2013\n|align=left|22 September 2013\n{{WDL|13|3|3|7|decimals=1}}\n|<ref name=\"Paolo Di Canio: Sunderland reign that lasted only six months\"/><ref name=\"Managers: Paolo Di Canio\">{{cite web |title=Managers: Paolo Di Canio |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=2373 |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|108|57|21|30|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Lazio'''<ref name=\"Paolo di Canio\"/>\n* [[Serie B]] promotion: [[1987\u201388 Serie B|1987\u201388]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]] runner-up: [[2004 Supercoppa Italiana|2004]]\n\n'''Juventus'''<ref name=\"Il Pallone Racconta: Paolo Di Canio\"/>\n* [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[1993 UEFA Cup Final|1992\u201393]]\n* [[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[1991\u201392 Coppa Italia|1991\u201392]]\n\n'''Milan'''<ref name=\"Paolo di Canio\"/>\n* [[Serie A]]: [[1995\u201396 Serie A|1995\u201396]]\n* [[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[1994 European Super Cup|1994]]\n* [[UEFA Champions League]] runner-up: [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League|1994\u201395]]\n* [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] runner-up: [[1994 Intercontinental Cup|1994]]\n\n'''West Ham United'''\n* [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[1999 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1999]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/429277.stm|title=Intertoto win gives Hammers Uefa spot  |publisher=BBC |date=24 August 1999 |accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n* [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year]]: 1996\u201397<ref>https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/sheffield-wednesday-legend-paolo-di-canio-announces-return-city-158272</ref>\n* [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.#Player of the Year winners|Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Player of the Year]]: 1998<ref>[http://www.myfootballfacts.com/Sheffield_Wednesday_Player_of_the_Year.html]</ref>\n* [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]]: 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/club/history/records-and-honours/hammer-of-the-year|title=Awards |publisher=West Ham United F.C.|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[BBC Goal of the Season]]: 1999\u20132000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13466915.stm|title=Swindon Town confirm Paolo di Canio as new manager|date=20 May 2011|accessdate=16 December 2011|publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref>\n* [[FIFA Fair Play Award]]: 2001<ref name=\"Fair Play award\"/>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Swindon Town'''\n* [[EFL League Two|Football League Two]]: [[2011\u201312 Football League Two|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"Port Vale\" />\n* [[Football League Trophy]] runner-up: [[2012 Football League Trophy Final|2011\u201312]]<ref name=BBC-Chapman>{{cite news|title=Chesterfield 2\u20130 Swindon|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17419742|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n* [[League Managers Association Awards|LMA League Two Manager of the Year]]: [[2011\u201312 Football League Two|2012]]<ref name=\"MOTM\" />\n* [[Football League Two Manager of the Month]]: February 2012<ref name=\"MOTM\">{{Cite news\n| title = NPower Manager of the Month\n| url = http://www.football-league.co.uk/page/ManageroftheMonthArticle/0,,10794,00.html\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131021015130/http://www.football-league.co.uk/archive/20120504/npower-manager-of-the-month-201112_2293449_2898698\n| archivedate = 2013-10-21\n| publisher = Football League\n| date = September 2011 \u2013 April 2012\n| accessdate = 6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Paolo Di Canio, ''Paolo Di Canio: l'Autobiografia'', Milan, Libreria dello Sport, 2001, {{ISBN|88-86753-40-3}} (Paolo Di Canio: The Autobiography). {{in lang|it}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Di_Canio_Paolo}}\n*[https://www.figc.it/it/nazionali/nazionali-in-cifre/dettaglio-convocato/?calciatoreId=46768&squadraId=13 Profile at FIGC] {{in lang|it}}\n*[https://www.premierleague.com/players/1451/Paolo-Di-Canio/overview Premier League Profile]\n\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{SPFA Players' Player of the Year}}\n{{Sheffield Wednesday F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{West Ham United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Goal of the Season}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 = \n{{Swindon Town F.C. managers}}\n{{Sunderland A.F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Canio, Paolo}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rome]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:S.S. Lazio players]]\n[[Category:Ternana Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Napoli players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Atletico Roma F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Italy under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Pro Licence holders]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian neo-fascists]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:be81:9b00:34aa:63ce:850:e799", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paolo_Di_Canio"}
{"title_page": "Nicole Galloway", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Nicole Galloway\n|image       = Nicole Galloway Photo.jpg\n|office      = 38th [[State Auditor of Missouri|Auditor of Missouri]]\n|governor    = [[Jay Nixon]]<br>[[Eric Greitens]]<br>[[Mike Parson]]\n|term_start  = April 27, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Tom Schweich]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Nicole Marie Rogge\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|6|13}}\n|birth_place = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Jon Galloway\n|children    = 3\n|education   = [[Missouri University of Science and Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Missouri]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|auditor.mo.gov|Government website}}\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Galloway''' (born June 13, 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auditor.mo.gov/aboutus/historical |title=State Auditors Historical Listing &#124; Nicole Galloway, CPA |website=Auditor.mo.gov|access-date=July 16, 2016}}</ref> is an American politician, who has served as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] since 2015, and is a candidate for [[List of governors of Missouri|governor of Missouri]] in the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election|2020 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article233766967.html|title=Galloway plays up \u2018watchdog\u2018 role in video announcing run for Missouri governor|date=August 12, 2019|website=Kansas City Star}}</ref> Galloway, a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], was elected to a full term as State Auditor of Missouri in the [[2018 Missouri State Auditor election|2018 election]] on November 6, 2018, winning by 135,571 votes, or nearly 6 percent, with 50.4% of the vote to her opponent's 44.6%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/democrat-galloway-fends-off-gop-challenger-in-race-for-missouri/article_fc252962-ceeb-54c8-a9f2-038eaf532c2b.html|title=Democrat Galloway fends off GOP challenger in race for Missouri auditor|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|work=stltoday.com|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Galloway was appointed as State Auditor of Missouri by Governor [[Jay Nixon]] on April 14, 2015, following the resignation of John Watson.<ref>{{cite web |title=State Auditors Historical Listing |url=https://www.auditor.mo.gov/aboutus/historical |website=The Office of Missouri State Auditor |publisher=The Office of Missouri State Auditor |accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref> John Watson was appointed as State Auditor following the death of [[Tom Schweich]] in February 2015, before Galloway's appointment as State Auditor nearly two months later.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/nixon-picks-boone-county-treasurer-for-state-auditor-job/article_d53a844a-ccde-582c-8bea-41e9776bc88e.html |title=Nixon picks Boone County treasurer for state auditor job |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=April 15, 2015 |access-date=April 24, 2015 }}</ref> Following the defeat of U.S. Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] in the [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|2018 U.S. Senate election]], Galloway is the only female state officeholder and the only Democratic statewide elected official in Missouri.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Democrat Galloway fends off GOP challenger in race for Missouri auditor |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/democrat-galloway-fends-off-gop-challenger-in-race-for-missouri/article_fc252962-ceeb-54c8-a9f2-038eaf532c2b.html |website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref> \n\nOn August 12, 2019, Galloway announced that she is entering the Democratic primary for the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election]]. If elected, Galloway will be the first female [[List of governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]].<ref>https://www.apnews.com/45aef9ef051a403f8889af884a4e2484</ref>\n\n==Boone County Treasurer==\nGalloway served as Treasurer of [[Boone County, Missouri]] from April 2011 until her appointment to statewide office. As Treasurer, she managed a $100 million investment portfolio and issued all general obligation and revenue bonds for the county. Galloway developed a debt issuance policy in 2012 that provided increased transparency. In 2011, Boone County became the first Missouri county to maintain an online search and claim system for unclaimed property. Galloway's office distributed about $20,000 in unclaimed property in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/local/galloway-plans-to-bring-innovation-energy-to-auditor-role/article_847b4172-78c7-520f-b3fb-87dcc0549c62.html?_dc=775010517798.3641|title=Galloway plans to bring innovation, energy to auditor role|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=Columbia Daily Tribune}}</ref>\n\nWhen serving as County Treasurer, Galloway served on the Missouri Technology Corporation and Missouri County Employees\u2019 Retirement Fund.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://columbiabusinesstimes.com/24897/2014/12/23/20-under-40-nicole-galloway/|title=20 Under 40: Nicole Galloway |date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=July 16, 2016 |newspaper=Columbia Business Times}}</ref> As a board member for retirement fund board she was the leader for expanding benefits to members\u2019 same-sex spouses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/virginia-young/pension-system-for-most-county-employees-will-recognize-gay-marriages/article_807081e4-ddde-5d17-b258-101519269f91.html|title=Pension system for most county employees will recognize gay marriages |date=December 9, 2014|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Galloway's resignation as Boone County Treasurer on April 27, 2015, Kay Murray was appointed as interim County Treasurer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/a/188046/boone-county-ready-to-name-kay-murray-interim-treasurer-while-awaiting-governors-appointment/Boone |title=Boone County ready to name Kay Murray interim treasurer while awaiting governor's appointment |date=April 23, 2015 |newspaper=The Columbia Missourian |first=William |last=Schmitt}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri State Auditor==\n\nGalloway has said her goals as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] are to hold her office and others to the highest professional standards and being accountable to Missourians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krcu.org/post/nixon-taps-boone-county-official-be-new-state-auditor |title=Nixon taps Boone County official to be new state auditor|date=April 15, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|website=KRCU 90.9}}</ref>\n\nUpon taking the oath of office in 2015, Galloway said one of her first priorities as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] would be [[cybersecurity]] by making protection of Missourians' private data part of audit procedures for the State Auditor's Office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/galloway-sworn-in-as-state-auditor/article_d763f379-f346-5412-bc68-e1b747941a70.html|title=Galloway sworn in as state auditor|date=April 27, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref>\n\nAs [[State Auditor of Missouri]], Galloway manages about 115 employees. The State Auditor's staff is made up of CPAs, with about 65 percent of all audit staff having at least one professional license, certification or advanced degree. Employment as an auditor with the State Auditor's Office qualifies as mandatory experience required for licensure by the Missouri State Board of Accountancy as a certified public accountant.<ref name=\"auditor1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.auditor.mo.gov/AboutUs/Overview.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518105819/http://www.auditor.mo.gov/AboutUs/Overview.aspx |archivedate=May 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAdditional responsibilities of the State Auditor's Office include serving as the independent, professional watchdog for government. The State Auditor's Office works to ensure the proper use of public funds and to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of Missouri government by performing audits of state agencies, boards and commissions, the circuit court system, the counties in Missouri that do not have a county auditor, and other political subdivisions upon petition by the voters. These audits examine financial accountability, waste, opportunities for fraud, and whether government organizations and programs are achieving their purposes and operating economically and efficiently.<ref name=\"auditor1\"/>\n\n=== Callaway County Collector Guilty of Embezzling $300,000 ===\nOn September 24, 2018, Auditor Galloway delivered an auditor report showing $300,000 missing from the Callaway County Collector\u2019s Office from January 2016 to March 2018. The former collector pleaded guilty in federal court to embezzling the funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://939theeagle.com/ex-callaway-county-collector-admits-to-embezzlement/|title=Ex-Callaway County Collector admits to embezzlement|date=September 25, 2018|website=93.9 The Eagle}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2019, former Callaway County Collector Pamela Oestreich was sentenced to two years and six months in federal prison without parole for embezzling more than $300,000 from taxpayers in [[Callaway County, Missouri|Callaway County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/local/former-callaway-county-collector-sentenced-for-embezzling-almost/article_7c235530-3ec5-11e9-b300-bf6ce239d140.html|title=Former Callaway County collector sentenced for embezzling almost $300,000|date=March 4, 2019|website=Columbia Missourian}}</ref>\n\n=== Putnam County Hospital ===\nIn 2017, Auditor Galloway issued an audit that uncovered a billing scheme in which Putnam County Memorial Hospital billed insurance companies for lab services conducted across the country. The questionable activity began in September 2016, after the Putnam County Hospital Board hired David Byrns and his company, Hospital Partners Inc., to take over day-to-day management of the hospital. Her report uncovered $90 million in inappropriate lab billings. The findings of the audit were covered by national news outlets and resulted in calls for a federal investigation into hospital billing schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fultonsun.com/news/local/story/2018/jul/12/auditor-issues-report-putnam-hospital/734191/|title=Auditor issues report on Putnam hospital|date=July 12, 2018|website=Fulton Sun}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the audit, dozens of major insurers banded together to file lawsuits against affiliated hospitals in Missouri and other states, demanding hundreds of millions in restitution. The lawsuits describe the lab-billing operation as a \"widespread fraudulent scheme\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/state-and-regional/the-collapse-of-a-hospital-empire-and-the-small-towns/article_de56b76d-f0d0-5cf7-88c9-1916e5f4de9a.html|title=The collapse of a hospital empire \u2014 and the small towns left in the wreckage|date=August 25, 2019|website=St. Louis Post Dispatch}}</ref>\n\n=== City of Viburnum Audit ===\nOn June 21, 2017, Auditor Galloway released an audit showing the city clerk of [[Viburnum, Missouri]] stole $100,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/06/21/small-town-missouri-city-clerk-accused-of-stealing-100000/|title=Small town Missouri city clerk accused of stealing $100,000|date=June 21, 207|website=Missourinet}}</ref> Dana Mayberry served as the Viburnum City Clerk for 14 years. The city identified inconsistencies in accounts she oversaw after she lost her reelection bid in April 2016.\u00a0At that time, most of the city and municipal division records disappeared in the Iron County town of less than 1,000 residents. Mayberry admitted to stealing city funds, after which the mayor notified the State Auditor\u2019s Office.\u00a0An audit began in August 2016 after the Viburnum Board of Aldermen authorized one. The examination began to uncover a scheme in which the former clerk adjusted customer utility accounts and then destroyed records and other evidence.\u00a0 \n\nThe former city Clerk was charged with receiving stolen property, a Class B Felony as a result of the audit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kfvs12.com/story/35698088/audit-shows-improvement-for-city-of-viburnum-after-former-clerk-charged-for-stealing/|title=Audit shows improvement for city of Viburnum after former clerk charged for stealing|date=June 19, 2017|website=KFVS TV}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2018, the former city Clerk was sentenced to five years probation and ordered to pay the City of Viburnum $100,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mymoinfo.com/2018/08/15/former-viburnum-city-clerk-sentenced-for-felony/|title=Former Viburnum City Clerk Sentenced for Felony|date=August 15, 2018|website=KREI Radio}}</ref>\n\n=== Missouri Alliance for Freedom v Galloway ===\n\nIn May 2017, the 501(c)(4) non-profit Missouri Alliance for Freedom submitted multiple open-records requests to the Office of State Auditor. The requests sought a wide variety of communications, including those specifically concerning the auditor\u2019s scrutiny of the [[Missouri Department of Revenue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/gop-leaning-group-files-open-records-lawsuit-against-missouri-auditor/article_b57e36c1-f0b4-5bf7-8a92-94c945192a4b.html|title=GOP-leaning group files open records lawsuit against Missouri auditor, senator|date=July 19, 2017|website=Stltoday.com}}</ref> The Auditor's office responded that non-substantial messages that relate to the office's business are not required to be produced in sunshine law requests.<ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref> The State Auditor's Office produced approximately 47,000 pages at no charge to Missouri Alliance for Freedom, including 254 screenshots of text messages to and from the State Auditor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courts.mo.gov/fv/c/Judgment_FINAL.pdf?l=SMPDB0004_CT19&di=1516218|title=FINDINGS OF FACT, CONCLUSIONS OF LAW and JUDGMENT|date=January 28, 2019|website=Case.net}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2017, Missouri Alliance for Freedom sued the State Auditor's Office. The legal team working for Missouri Alliance for Freedom was Graves Garrett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/08/29/arguments-made-in-lawsuit-alleging-missouri-auditor-galloway-violated-sunshine-law/|title=Arguments made in lawsuit alleging Missouri Auditor Galloway violated Sunshine Law|date=August 29, 2018|website=Missourinet}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2017 the Missouri Alliance for Freedom filed a formal complaint with Republican Missouri attorney general [[Josh Hawley]] alleging that Galloway \"unlawfully withheld public records from her State-provided cell phone.\"<ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref> In February 2018, attorney general Hawley issued a report that found Galloway complied with the Missouri Sunshine Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/reports/auditorsunshinereport.pdf?sfvrsn=2|title=FINAL REPORT: AGO INQUIRY INTO SUNSHINE LAW COMPLAINT FILED BY MISSOURI ALLIANCE FOR FREEDOM|date=February 1, 2018|website=Missouri Attorney General's Office}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Attorney General's report on February 7, 2018, the judge dismissed the majority of the claims against the State Auditor's Office, and ordered Missouri Alliance for Freedom re-plead its claims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auditor.mo.gov/media/pdf/17accc00365-order|title=Missouri Alliance for Freedom v Galloway order|date=February 7, 2018|website=State Auditor's Office}}</ref> \n\nThe Missouri Alliance for Freedom alleged that Galloway had her cell phone automatically delete text messages after 30 days. Because Galloway\u2019s office had taken more than 30 days to respond to previous sunshine requests, it was unclear if Galloway\u2019s office knowingly violated or subverted the Missouri sunshine law.<ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref>\n\nCircuit Judge Jon Beetem ruled against Missouri Alliance for Freedom on January 28, 2019, ending the suit in favor of Galloway. The judgement stated, \"The Court finds in favor of Defendant State Auditor Nicole Galloway on all claims...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courts.mo.gov/fv/c/Judgment_FINAL.pdf?l=SMPDB0004_CT19&di=1516218|title=Findings of Fact, Conclusions of Law and Judgement|date=January 28, 2019|website=Case.net}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 election ===\n{{Main|2018 Missouri State Auditor election}}\n\nGalloway, who was appointed to the post of [[State Auditor of Missouri|Missouri State Auditor]] by then-Gov. [[Jay Nixon]] following a vacancy in 2015, won election to a full term as Missouri State Auditor on November 6, 2018. Her term will expire in January 2023.\n\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Missouri State Auditor election, 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://enr.sos.mo.gov/ |title=State of Missouri General Election Unofficial Results |date=November 6, 2018 |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |access-date=November 20, 2018 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Nicole Galloway\n  |votes      = 1,199,346\n  |percentage = 50.3%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Sandra McDowell\n  |votes      = 1,063,775\n  |percentage = 44.6%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Sean O'Toole\n  |votes      = 51,652\n  |percentage = 2.2%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Jacob Luetkemeyer\n  |votes      = 48,534\n  |percentage = 2.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Gubernatorial campaign==\nIn August 2019, Galloway announced that she was seeking the Democratic nomination for the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election]]. If nominated, Galloway is expected to face incumbent Republican governor [[Mike Parson]] in what is anticipated to be a close race. Parson, a former lieutenant governor who assumed the post following the resignation of [[Eric Greitens]] in 2018, announced in September 2019 that he would seek a full term as Governor<ref>{{cite web |author1=Jack Suntrup |title=Missouri Gov. Mike Parson, a cattle-farming former sheriff, announces bid for 4-year term |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-gov-mike-parson-a-cattle-farming-former-sheriff-announces/article_d91658bf-cba4-5fb2-8a19-89f53e35a035.html |website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=16 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911182125/https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-gov-mike-parson-a-cattle-farming-former-sheriff-announces/article_d91658bf-cba4-5fb2-8a19-89f53e35a035.html |archivedate=2019-09-11}}</ref>. In her announcement video, Galloway emphasized her record in exposing public corruption, pledged to reduce the influence of special interest groups on the Missouri legislature, and attacked the Parson administration for its efforts to curb the effects of a government transparency initiative that was passed by statewide ballot in 2018 <ref>https://www.apnews.com/45aef9ef051a403f8889af884a4e2484</ref>. Galloway is currently the only Democratic politician holding statewide office in Missouri, as well as the only female. Fellow Democrat [[Jay Nixon]] served two terms as Missouri's governor from 2009 to 2017, while 2016 nominee [[Chris Koster]], a former Republican, was defeated by Greitens.\n\n==Personal life==\nGalloway holds a bachelor's degree in applied mathematics and economics from [[Missouri University of Science and Technology]] in Rolla, and a master's degree in business administration from the [[University of Missouri]]. She is a [[Certified Public Accountant]] and [[Certified Fraud Examiner]]. A native of [[Fenton, Missouri]], she lives in [[Columbia, Missouri]] with her husband, Jon Galloway and their three sons. Jon Galloway is a former press secretary to State Treasurer [[Clint Zweifel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.governing.com/topics/mgmt/tns-missouri-auditor-nicole-galloway.html |title=Missouri Replaces State Auditor Who Committed Suicide |publisher=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]] |date=April 15, 2015 |access-date=April 24, 2015 }}</ref> Galloway is [[Roman Catholic]], and graduated high school from [[Ursuline Academy (Oakland, Missouri)|Ursuline Academy]] in [[Oakland, Missouri]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ursulinestl.org/notable-alumnae/|title=Notable Alumnae - Ursuline Academy {{!}} Girls Catholic High School Kirkwood|work=Ursuline Academy {{!}} Girls Catholic High School Kirkwood|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In August 2016, she announced that she was pregnant with her third child, due in January 2017, and was the first statewide officeholder in Missouri history to become pregnant while in office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/missouri-auditor-nicole-galloway-making-state-history/article_7ebe99cc-4a23-5e5a-a7d5-8a716753f312.html |title=Missouri Auditor Nicole Galloway making state history |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=August 12, 2016 |first=Joe |last=Holleman |access-date=November 22, 2016 }}</ref> Her son, Joseph Nickels Galloway was born on January 6, 2017.<ref>[https://www.auditor.mo.gov/content/statement-auditor-galloway-birth-her-son Statement from Auditor Galloway on the birth of her son-Press Release-Office of State Auditor Nicole Galloway (January 8,, 2017)]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.auditor.mo.gov/ Missouri State Auditor's Office website]\n* [http://www.nicolegalloway.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://showmeboone.com/treasurer/ Showmeboone.com]\n* [http://www.connectmidmissouri.com/news/story.aspx?id=676007#.T-i8Do5u0mk Connectmidmissouri.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=John Watson<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[State Auditor of Missouri|Auditor of Missouri]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Missouri statewide political officials}}\n{{U.S. State Auditors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galloway, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:Missouri University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Columbia, Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:State Auditors of Missouri]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Missouri politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Nicole Galloway\n|image       = Nicole Galloway Photo.jpg\n|office      = 38th [[State Auditor of Missouri|Auditor of Missouri]]\n|governor    = [[Jay Nixon]]<br>[[Eric Greitens]]<br>[[Mike Parson]]\n|term_start  = April 27, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Tom Schweich]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Nicole Marie Rogge\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|6|13}}\n|birth_place = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Jon Galloway\n|children    = 3\n|education   = [[Missouri University of Science and Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[University of Missouri]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|website     = {{url|auditor.mo.gov|Government website}}\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Galloway''' (born June 13, 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auditor.mo.gov/aboutus/historical |title=State Auditors Historical Listing &#124; Nicole Galloway, CPA |website=Auditor.mo.gov|access-date=July 16, 2016}}</ref> is an American politician, who has served as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] since 2015, and is a candidate for [[List of governors of Missouri|governor of Missouri]] in the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election|2020 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article233766967.html|title=Galloway plays up \u2018watchdog\u2018 role in video announcing run for Missouri governor|date=August 12, 2019|website=Kansas City Star}}</ref> Galloway, a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], was elected to a full term as State Auditor of Missouri in the [[2018 Missouri State Auditor election|2018 election]] on November 6, 2018, winning by 135,571 votes, or nearly 6 percent, with 50.4% of the vote to her opponent's 44.6%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/democrat-galloway-fends-off-gop-challenger-in-race-for-missouri/article_fc252962-ceeb-54c8-a9f2-038eaf532c2b.html|title=Democrat Galloway fends off GOP challenger in race for Missouri auditor|last=Erickson|first=Kurt|work=stltoday.com|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Galloway was appointed as State Auditor of Missouri by Governor [[Jay Nixon]] on April 14, 2015, following the resignation of John Watson.<ref>{{cite web |title=State Auditors Historical Listing |url=https://www.auditor.mo.gov/aboutus/historical |website=The Office of Missouri State Auditor |publisher=The Office of Missouri State Auditor |accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref> John Watson was appointed as State Auditor following the death of [[Tom Schweich]] in February 2015, before Galloway's appointment as State Auditor nearly two months later.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/nixon-picks-boone-county-treasurer-for-state-auditor-job/article_d53a844a-ccde-582c-8bea-41e9776bc88e.html |title=Nixon picks Boone County treasurer for state auditor job |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=April 15, 2015 |access-date=April 24, 2015 }}</ref> Following the defeat of U.S. Senator [[Claire McCaskill]] in the [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|2018 U.S. Senate election]], Galloway is the only female state officeholder and the only Democratic statewide elected official in Missouri.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Kurt |title=Democrat Galloway fends off GOP challenger in race for Missouri auditor |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/democrat-galloway-fends-off-gop-challenger-in-race-for-missouri/article_fc252962-ceeb-54c8-a9f2-038eaf532c2b.html |website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |publisher=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref> \n\nOn August 12, 2019, Galloway announced that she is entering the Democratic primary for the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election]]. If elected, Galloway will be the first female [[List of governors of Missouri|Governor of Missouri]].<ref>https://www.apnews.com/45aef9ef051a403f8889af884a4e2484</ref>\n\n==Boone County Treasurer==\nGalloway served as Treasurer of [[Boone County, Missouri]] from April 2011 until her appointment to statewide office. As Treasurer, she managed a $100 million investment portfolio and issued all general obligation and revenue bonds for the county. Galloway developed a debt issuance policy in 2012 that provided increased transparency. In 2011, Boone County became the first Missouri county to maintain an online search and claim system for unclaimed property. Galloway's office distributed about $20,000 in unclaimed property in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/local/galloway-plans-to-bring-innovation-energy-to-auditor-role/article_847b4172-78c7-520f-b3fb-87dcc0549c62.html?_dc=775010517798.3641|title=Galloway plans to bring innovation, energy to auditor role|date=April 26, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=Columbia Daily Tribune}}</ref>\n\nWhen serving as County Treasurer, Galloway served on the Missouri Technology Corporation and Missouri County Employees\u2019 Retirement Fund.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://columbiabusinesstimes.com/24897/2014/12/23/20-under-40-nicole-galloway/|title=20 Under 40: Nicole Galloway |date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=July 16, 2016 |newspaper=Columbia Business Times}}</ref> As a board member for retirement fund board she was the leader for expanding benefits to members\u2019 same-sex spouses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/virginia-young/pension-system-for-most-county-employees-will-recognize-gay-marriages/article_807081e4-ddde-5d17-b258-101519269f91.html|title=Pension system for most county employees will recognize gay marriages |date=December 9, 2014|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Galloway's resignation as Boone County Treasurer on April 27, 2015, Kay Murray was appointed as interim County Treasurer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/a/188046/boone-county-ready-to-name-kay-murray-interim-treasurer-while-awaiting-governors-appointment/Boone |title=Boone County ready to name Kay Murray interim treasurer while awaiting governor's appointment |date=April 23, 2015 |newspaper=The Columbia Missourian |first=William |last=Schmitt}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri State Auditor==\n\nGalloway has said her goals as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] are to hold her office and others to the highest professional standards and being accountable to Missourians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krcu.org/post/nixon-taps-boone-county-official-be-new-state-auditor |title=Nixon taps Boone County official to be new state auditor|date=April 15, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|website=KRCU 90.9}}</ref>\n\nUpon taking the oath of office in 2015, Galloway said one of her first priorities as [[State Auditor of Missouri]] would be [[cybersecurity]] by making protection of Missourians' private data part of audit procedures for the State Auditor's Office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/galloway-sworn-in-as-state-auditor/article_d763f379-f346-5412-bc68-e1b747941a70.html|title=Galloway sworn in as state auditor|date=April 27, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2019|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch}}</ref>\n\nAs [[State Auditor of Missouri]], Galloway manages about 115 employees. The State Auditor's staff is made up of CPAs, with about 65 percent of all audit staff having at least one professional license, certification or advanced degree. Employment as an auditor with the State Auditor's Office qualifies as mandatory experience required for licensure by the Missouri State Board of Accountancy as a certified public accountant.<ref name=\"auditor1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.auditor.mo.gov/AboutUs/Overview.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518105819/http://www.auditor.mo.gov/AboutUs/Overview.aspx |archivedate=May 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAdditional responsibilities of the State Auditor's Office include serving as the independent, professional watchdog for government. The State Auditor's Office works to ensure the proper use of public funds and to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of Missouri government by performing audits of state agencies, boards and commissions, the circuit court system, the counties in Missouri that do not have a county auditor, and other political subdivisions upon petition by the voters. These audits examine financial accountability, waste, opportunities for fraud, and whether government organizations and programs are achieving their purposes and operating economically and efficiently.<ref name=\"auditor1\"/>\n\n=== Callaway County Collector Guilty of Embezzling $300,000 ===\nOn September 24, 2018, Auditor Galloway delivered an auditor report showing $300,000 missing from the Callaway County Collector\u2019s Office from January 2016 to March 2018. The former collector pleaded guilty in federal court to embezzling the funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://939theeagle.com/ex-callaway-county-collector-admits-to-embezzlement/|title=Ex-Callaway County Collector admits to embezzlement|date=September 25, 2018|website=93.9 The Eagle}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2019, former Callaway County Collector Pamela Oestreich was sentenced to two years and six months in federal prison without parole for embezzling more than $300,000 from taxpayers in [[Callaway County, Missouri|Callaway County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/local/former-callaway-county-collector-sentenced-for-embezzling-almost/article_7c235530-3ec5-11e9-b300-bf6ce239d140.html|title=Former Callaway County collector sentenced for embezzling almost $300,000|date=March 4, 2019|website=Columbia Missourian}}</ref>\n\n=== Putnam County Hospital ===\nIn 2017, Auditor Galloway issued an audit that uncovered a billing scheme in which Putnam County Memorial Hospital billed insurance companies for lab services conducted across the country. The questionable activity began in September 2016, after the Putnam County Hospital Board hired David Byrns and his company, Hospital Partners Inc., to take over day-to-day management of the hospital. Her report uncovered $90 million in inappropriate lab billings. The findings of the audit were covered by national news outlets and resulted in calls for a federal investigation into hospital billing schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fultonsun.com/news/local/story/2018/jul/12/auditor-issues-report-putnam-hospital/734191/|title=Auditor issues report on Putnam hospital|date=July 12, 2018|website=Fulton Sun}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the audit, dozens of major insurers banded together to file lawsuits against affiliated hospitals in Missouri and other states, demanding hundreds of millions in restitution. The lawsuits describe the lab-billing operation as a \u201cwidespread fraudulent scheme\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/state-and-regional/the-collapse-of-a-hospital-empire-and-the-small-towns/article_de56b76d-f0d0-5cf7-88c9-1916e5f4de9a.html|title=The collapse of a hospital empire \u2014 and the small towns left in the wreckage|date=August 25, 2019|website=St. Louis Post Dispatch}}</ref>\n\n=== City of Viburnum Audit ===\nOn June 21, 2017, Auditor Galloway released an audit showing the city clerk of [[Viburnum, Missouri]] stole $100,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/06/21/small-town-missouri-city-clerk-accused-of-stealing-100000/|title=Small town Missouri city clerk accused of stealing $100,000|date=June 21, 207|website=Missourinet}}</ref> Dana Mayberry served as the Viburnum City Clerk for 14 years. The city identified inconsistencies in accounts she oversaw after she lost her reelection bid in April 2016.\u00a0At that time, most of the city and municipal division records disappeared in the Iron County town of less than 1,000 residents. Mayberry admitted to stealing city funds, after which the mayor notified the State Auditor\u2019s Office.\u00a0An audit began in August 2016 after the Viburnum Board of Aldermen authorized one. The examination began to uncover a scheme in which the former clerk adjusted customer utility accounts and then destroyed records and other evidence.\u00a0 \n\nThe former city Clerk was charged with receiving stolen property, a Class B Felony as a result of the audit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kfvs12.com/story/35698088/audit-shows-improvement-for-city-of-viburnum-after-former-clerk-charged-for-stealing/|title=Audit shows improvement for city of Viburnum after former clerk charged for stealing|date=June 19, 2017|website=KFVS TV}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2018, the former city Clerk was sentenced to five years probation and ordered to pay the City of Viburnum $100,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mymoinfo.com/2018/08/15/former-viburnum-city-clerk-sentenced-for-felony/|title=Former Viburnum City Clerk Sentenced for Felony|date=August 15, 2018|website=KREI Radio}}</ref>\n\n=== Missouri Alliance for Freedom v Galloway ===\n\nIn May 2017, the 501(c)(4) non-profit Missouri Alliance for Freedom submitted multiple open-records requests to the Office of State Auditor. The requests sought a wide-variety of communications, including those specifically concerning the auditor\u2019s scrutiny of the [[Missouri Department of Revenue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/gop-leaning-group-files-open-records-lawsuit-against-missouri-auditor/article_b57e36c1-f0b4-5bf7-8a92-94c945192a4b.html|title=GOP-leaning group files open records lawsuit against Missouri auditor, senator|date=July 19, 2017|website=Stltoday.com}}</ref> The Auditor\u2019s office responded that non-substantial messages that relate to the office\u2019s business are not required to be produced in sunshine law requests.<ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref> The State Auditor's Office produced approximately 47,000 pages at no charge to Missouri Alliance for Freedom, including 254 screenshots of text messages to and from the State Auditor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courts.mo.gov/fv/c/Judgment_FINAL.pdf?l=SMPDB0004_CT19&di=1516218|title=FINDINGS OF FACT, CONCLUSIONS OF LAW and JUDGMENT|date=January 28, 2019|website=Case.net}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2017, Missouri Alliance for Freedom sued the State Auditor's Office. The legal team working for Missouri Alliance for Freedom was Graves Garrett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/08/29/arguments-made-in-lawsuit-alleging-missouri-auditor-galloway-violated-sunshine-law/|title=Arguments made in lawsuit alleging Missouri Auditor Galloway violated Sunshine Law|date=August 29, 2018|website=Missourinet}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2017 the Missouri Alliance for Freedom filed a formal complaint with Republican Missouri attorney general, [[Josh Hawley]], alleging that Galloway \u201cunlawfully withheld public records from her State-provided cell phone.\u201d<ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref> In February 2018, attorney general Hawley issued a report that found Galloway complied with the Missouri Sunshine Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/reports/auditorsunshinereport.pdf?sfvrsn=2|title=FINAL REPORT: AGO INQUIRY INTO SUNSHINE LAW COMPLAINT FILED BY MISSOURI ALLIANCE FOR FREEDOM|date=February 1, 2018|website=Missouri Attorney General's Office}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Attorney General's report on February 7, 2018, the judge dismissed the majority of the claims against the State Auditor's Office, and ordered Missouri Alliance for Freedom re-plead its claims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auditor.mo.gov/media/pdf/17accc00365-order|title=Missouri Alliance for Freedom v Galloway order|date=February 7, 2018|website=State Auditor's Office}}</ref> \n\nThe Missouri Alliance for Freedom alleged that Galloway had her cell phone automatically delete text messages after 30 days. Because Galloway\u2019s office had taken more than 30 days to respond to previous sunshine requests, it was unclear if Galloway\u2019s office knowingly violated or subverted the Missouri sunshine law. <ref>https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/politics/2018/08/24/auditor-nicole-galloway-accused-allowing-deletion-public-records/1072971002/</ref>\n\nCircuit Judge Jon Beetem ruled against Missouri Alliance for Freedom on Jan. 28, 2019, ending the suit in favor of Galloway. The judgement stated, \"The Court finds in favor of Defendant State Auditor Nicole Galloway on all claims...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courts.mo.gov/fv/c/Judgment_FINAL.pdf?l=SMPDB0004_CT19&di=1516218|title=Findings of Fact, Conclusions of Law and Judgement|date=January 28, 2019|website=Case.net}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 election ===\n{{Main|2018 Missouri State Auditor election}}\n\nGalloway, who was appointed to the post of [[State Auditor of Missouri|Missouri State Auditor]] by then-Gov. [[Jay Nixon]] following a vacancy in 2015, won election to a full term as Missouri State Auditor on Nov. 6, 2018. Her term will expire in January 2023.\n\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Missouri State Auditor election, 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://enr.sos.mo.gov/ |title=State of Missouri General Election Unofficial Results |date=November 6, 2018 |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |access-date=November 20, 2018 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Nicole Galloway\n  |votes      = 1,199,346\n  |percentage = 50.3%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Sandra McDowell\n  |votes      = 1,063,775\n  |percentage = 44.6%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Sean O'Toole\n  |votes      = 51,652\n  |percentage = 2.2%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Jacob Luetkemeyer\n  |votes      = 48,534\n  |percentage = 2.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Gubernatorial campaign==\nIn August 2019, Galloway announced that she was seeking the Democratic nomination for the [[2020 Missouri gubernatorial election]]. If nominated, Galloway is expected to face incumbent Republican governor [[Mike Parson]] in what is anticipated to be a close race. Parson, a former lieutenant governor who assumed the post following the resignation of [[Eric Greitens]] in 2018, announced in September 2019 that he would seek a full term as Governor<ref>{{cite web |author1=Jack Suntrup |title=Missouri Gov. Mike Parson, a cattle-farming former sheriff, announces bid for 4-year term |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-gov-mike-parson-a-cattle-farming-former-sheriff-announces/article_d91658bf-cba4-5fb2-8a19-89f53e35a035.html |website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |accessdate=16 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911182125/https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-gov-mike-parson-a-cattle-farming-former-sheriff-announces/article_d91658bf-cba4-5fb2-8a19-89f53e35a035.html |archivedate=2019-09-11}}</ref>. In her announcement video, Galloway emphasized her record in exposing public corruption, pledged to reduce the influence of special interest groups on the Missouri legislature, and attacked the Parson administration for its efforts to curb the effects of a government transparency initiative that was passed by statewide ballot in 2018 <ref>https://www.apnews.com/45aef9ef051a403f8889af884a4e2484</ref>. Galloway is currently the only Democratic politician holding statewide office in Missouri, as well as the only female. Fellow Democrat [[Jay Nixon]] served two terms as Missouri's governor from 2009 to 2017, while 2016 nominee [[Chris Koster]], a former Republican, was defeated by Greitens.\n\n==Personal life==\nGalloway holds a bachelor's degree in applied mathematics and economics from [[Missouri University of Science and Technology]] in Rolla, and a master's degree in business administration from the [[University of Missouri]]. She is a [[Certified Public Accountant]] and [[Certified Fraud Examiner]]. A native of [[Fenton, Missouri]], she lives in [[Columbia, Missouri]] with her husband, Jon Galloway and their three sons. Jon Galloway is a former press secretary to State Treasurer [[Clint Zweifel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.governing.com/topics/mgmt/tns-missouri-auditor-nicole-galloway.html |title=Missouri Replaces State Auditor Who Committed Suicide |publisher=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]] |date=April 15, 2015 |access-date=April 24, 2015 }}</ref> Galloway is [[Roman Catholic]], and graduated high school from [[Ursuline Academy (Oakland, Missouri)|Ursuline Academy]] in [[Oakland, Missouri]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ursulinestl.org/notable-alumnae/|title=Notable Alumnae - Ursuline Academy {{!}} Girls Catholic High School Kirkwood|work=Ursuline Academy {{!}} Girls Catholic High School Kirkwood|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In August 2016, she announced that she was pregnant with her third child, due in January 2017, and was the first statewide officeholder in Missouri history to become pregnant while in office.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/missouri-auditor-nicole-galloway-making-state-history/article_7ebe99cc-4a23-5e5a-a7d5-8a716753f312.html |title=Missouri Auditor Nicole Galloway making state history |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=August 12, 2016 |first=Joe |last=Holleman |access-date=November 22, 2016 }}</ref> Her son, Joseph Nickels Galloway was born on January 6, 2017.<ref>[https://www.auditor.mo.gov/content/statement-auditor-galloway-birth-her-son Statement from Auditor Galloway on the birth of her son-Press Release-Office of State Auditor Nicole Galloway (January 8,, 2017)]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.auditor.mo.gov/ Missouri State Auditor's Office website]\n* [http://www.nicolegalloway.com/ Campaign website]\n* [http://showmeboone.com/treasurer/ Showmeboone.com]\n* [http://www.connectmidmissouri.com/news/story.aspx?id=676007#.T-i8Do5u0mk Connectmidmissouri.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=John Watson<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[State Auditor of Missouri|Auditor of Missouri]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Missouri statewide political officials}}\n{{U.S. State Auditors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galloway, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:Missouri University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Columbia, Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:State Auditors of Missouri]]\n[[Category:University of Missouri alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Missouri politics]]\n", "name_user": "Ewulp", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicole_Galloway"}
