p deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = * 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46F\n* 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 8L46F\n* {{convert|48000|kW|hp|abbr=on}} (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = [[Diesel-electric transmission|Diesel-electric]]; three [[azimuth thruster]]s; (3{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}10{{nbsp}}MW)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deltamarin.fi/articles/blog/updated-titanic-ii-model-tests/9-32 |date=2013-09-20 |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111193447/http://www.deltamarin.fi/articles/blog/updated-titanic-ii-model-tests/9-32 |archivedate=2013-11-11 |work=Deltamarin Blog |title=Updated Titanic II model tests}}</ref>\n| Ship sail plan = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|24|kn}} (maximum)<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2284933/Titanic-II-Australian-tycoon-unveils-plans-replica-doomed-vessel.html The Titanic sails again: Australian tycoon unveils plans for perfect replica of doomed vessel (except with a few more lifeboats)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511021533/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2284933/Titanic-II-Australian-tycoon-unveils-plans-replica-doomed-vessel.html |date=2013-05-11 }}. Daily Mail, 25 February 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-05-11}}</ref>\n| Ship capacity = 1,680 (double capacity); 2,435 (maximum)\n| Ship crew = 900\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Titanic II''''' is a planned [[ocean liner]] intended to be a functional modern-day replica of the [[Olympic class ocean liner|''Olympic''-class]] {{RMS|Titanic}}. The new ship is planned to have a [[gross tonnage]] (GT) of 56,000 while the original ship measured about 46,000 [[gross register tons]] (GRT).<ref group=\"note\" name=\"gt\" /> The project was announced by [[Australian]] billionaire<!-- this is correct according to Forbes magazine - do not change! --> [[Clive Palmer]] in April 2012 as the flagship of the proposed cruise company Blue Star Line Pty. Ltd. of [[Brisbane]], Australia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Calligeros|first=Marissa|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/clive-palmer-plans-to-build-titanic-ii-20120430-1xtrc.html|title=Clive Palmer plans to build Titanic II|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 April 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724113115/http://www.smh.com.au/business/clive-palmer-plans-to-build-titanic-ii-20120430-1xtrc.html|archive-date=24 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The intended launch date was originally set in 2016,<ref>{{cite news|last=Fickling|first=David|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-30/titanic-ii-to-be-built-by-billionaire-palmer-chinese-yard.html|title=Titanic II to Be Built by Billionaire Palmer, Chinese Yard|publisher=Bloomberg|date=30 April 2012|access-date=12 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127092941/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-30/titanic-ii-to-be-built-by-billionaire-palmer-chinese-yard.html|archive-date=27 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> delayed to 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/titanic-ii-set-to-sail-in-2018-says-aussie-billionaire-31492220.html|title=Titanic II set to sail in 2018, says Aussie billionaire - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313093926/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/titanic-ii-set-to-sail-in-2018-says-aussie-billionaire-31492220.html|archive-date=2017-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> then 2022.<ref name=MIDEAST>{{cite web |url=https://www.logisticsmiddleeast.com/transport/maritime/31491-titanic-ii-replica-ships-cruise-from-dubai-delayed-until-2022 |title=Titanic II replica ship\u2019s cruise from Dubai delayed until 2022 |publisher=Logistics Middle East |access-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018003142/https://www.logisticsmiddleeast.com/transport/maritime/31491-titanic-ii-replica-ships-cruise-from-dubai-delayed-until-2022 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The development of the project was resumed in November 2018 after a hiatus which began in 2015, caused by a financial dispute<ref>{{cite news |title=Deltamarin continues work on Titanic II |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/oct/24/titanic-2-australian-billionaire-refloats-dream-clive-palmer |date24 october= |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=December 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215222234/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/oct/24/titanic-2-australian-billionaire-refloats-dream-clive-palmer |archive-date=December 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bluestarline.com.au/deltamarin-continues-work-on-titanic-ii/|title=Deltamarin continues to work on Titanic II|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=9 November 2018|accessdate=December 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215222408/https://www.bluestarline.com.au/deltamarin-continues-work-on-titanic-ii/|archive-date=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> that affected the $500 million project.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shabina|url=https://traveljee.com/luxury/titanic-ii-ship/|title=Titanic II Ship Ticket Prices 2022, Release Date, Construction Cost, Facts and Latest Updates|publisher=Traveljee|date=13 February 2019|access-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401174918/https://traveljee.com/luxury/titanic-ii-ship/|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Previous projects==\n[[File:Titanic.jpg|thumb|305px|right|The original {{RMS|Titanic}} in 1912.]]\n[[File:TitanicII-001.jpg|thumb|305px|right|The proposed ship]]\nThe concept of a functioning replica of the ''Titanic'' has been explored several times, especially following the resurgence of interest following the release of [[James Cameron]]'s [[Titanic (1997 film)|film]] in 1997. The most widely publicized project was that of South African businessman Sarel Gous in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ringshaw|first=Grant|title=A Titanic task|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|date=19 November 2000|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=24 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629185602/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|archive-date=29 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe South African project began in 1998, and was one of the subjects of an article in ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' magazine in September of that year.<ref>{{cite book | last = Wilson | first = James | title = Titanic Reborn | publisher = [[Popular Mechanics]] | date = September 1998 | pages = 56\u201359 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YmYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA4&dq=Titanic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=z4QsT8ngNufY0QGaqLTPCg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Titanic&f=true | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131231225552/http://books.google.com/books?id=YmYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA4&dq=Titanic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=z4QsT8ngNufY0QGaqLTPCg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Titanic&f=true | archive-date = 31 December 2013 | url-status = live }}</ref> The article discussed the changes to the original design required to produce a safe and economically viable ship, including a welded rather than riveted hull, [[diesel-electric]] propulsion in place of steam engines, and a [[bulbous bow]]. The article concluded that although the various ''Titanic'' revival projects would cost $400\u2013$600 million, they could be economically viable.\n\nAlthough he originally intended to construct the ship in [[Durban]], Gous presented his \u00a3500 million proposal to [[Belfast City Council]] in June 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tycoon presents Titanic II proposal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/783531.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 August 2012|date=9 June 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122104446/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/783531.stm|archive-date=22 January 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> He commissioned Olsen Designs to design the ship, advised by [[Harland and Wolff]] Technical Services who produced a [[feasibility study]], and Callcott Anderson to design the interior. In November 2000, he began his attempts to raise capital, including through government grants and a stock market flotation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ringshaw|first=Grant|title=A Titanic task|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=11 October 2012|date=19 November 2000|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105085431/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After signing an agreement with a Monaco-based investment banking company, Gous claimed that construction would begin at Harland and Wolff within nine months.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oldham|first=Jeanette|title=Dreams afloat to build Titanic II|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-67126861|publisher=Questia Online Library|accessdate=11 October 2012 |date=20 November 2000 }}</ref> The design changed repeatedly, with claims emerging of 'the world's largest liner' with capacity for 2,600 passengers, and increasingly divergent plans for a heliport, swimming pools and discos eventually being released.<ref name=Epstein>{{cite web|last=Louis|first=Epstein|title=To Build a New Titanic?|url=http://www.put.com/gigantic/|accessdate=11 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817193413/http://www.put.com/gigantic/|archivedate=17 August 2012}}</ref> In 2006, after repeatedly failing to secure investment, the project was abandoned.<ref name=Epstein />\n\n==Design stage==\n[[File:Clive Palmer Aug15 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Clive Palmer, chairman of the Blue Star Line]]\nClive Palmer first announced the project in a press conference on 30 April 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Clive Palmer Launches Titanic II|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120430.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=30 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312004302/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120430.html|archivedate=12 March 2013}}</ref> following the signature of a [[memorandum of understanding]] with state-owned Chinese shipyard CSC Jinling ten days before.<ref>{{cite web|title=MOU CSC Jinling and Blue Star Line|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120420.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=20 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721235318/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120420.html|archivedate=21 July 2012}}</ref> On 19 June, it was announced that Finnish naval architecture firm Deltamarin Ltd. had been commissioned to undertake the design of the ship,<ref>{{cite news|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/travel/titanic-ii-a-step-closer-to-reality-20120619-20l96.html|title=Titanic II a step closer to reality|publisher=Brisbane Times|date=19 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Global Ship Design Firm Commissioned to Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120619.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309073721/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120619.html|archivedate=9 March 2013}}</ref> and on 17 July a preliminary general arrangement was published.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Glimpse At Titanic II Plans|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120717.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720205448/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120717.html|archivedate=20 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Blue Star Line announced that ''Titanic'' expert Steve Hall had been appointed as Design Consultant and Historian for the project,<ref>{{cite web|title=Renown Titanic Historian Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=1 October 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809054357/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/|archive-date=9 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and that ''Titanic'' interiors expert Daniel Klistorner had been appointed as Interior Design Consultant and Historian.<ref name=Klistorner>{{cite web|title=Titanic Researcher and Interiors Expert Joins Blue Star Line|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1221|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=11 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024234906/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1221|archivedate=24 October 2012}}</ref> Hall and Klistorner had previously co-authored books such as ''Titanic: The Ship Magnificent'' and ''Titanic in Photographs'', and gave a technical presentation at the unveiling of the designs in New York, as well as at the dinner in London.<ref name=Klistorner /> Later that month, it was announced that an advisory board would be formed to provide \"suggestions and recommendations to Blue Star Line to ensure the ''Titanic II'' appropriately and respectfully pays homage to ''Titanic'', her crew and passengers.\" Terry Ismay, the great-great nephew of [[White Star Line]] chairman and ''Titanic'' survivor [[J. Bruce Ismay]], will be a member of the board,<ref>{{cite web|title=White Star Line Chairman Descendant Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1235|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 October 2012|access-date=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024225846/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1235|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> as well as Helen Benziger, great-granddaughter of ''Titanic'' survivor [[Margaret Brown|Margaret \"Molly\" Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Molly Brown Descendant Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1242|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=21 October 2012|access-date=21 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024225854/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1242|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe design for the ''Titanic II'' was unveiled at worldwide launch events in Macau (China), New York (United States), Halifax (Canada), London & Southampton (United Kingdom). The gala event in New York was the official Global Launch and was held aboard the [[USS Intrepid (CV-11)|USS ''Intrepid'']] in New York City on 26 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Dates for Titanic II Global Launch and Events|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1303|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=20 December 2012|access-date=20 December 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114214830/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1303|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Design for Titanic II to be unveiled in NYC|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19722578/design-for-titanic-ii-to-be-unveiled-in-nyc|publisher=MYFOXNY.COM|date=3 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006001239/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19722578/design-for-titanic-ii-to-be-unveiled-in-nyc|archivedate=6 October 2012}}</ref> The gala dinner in London (UK) was held at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] on 2 March, and was accompanied by a display of items salvaged from the ''Titanic''.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Event To Celebrate Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1214|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=9 October 2012|access-date=11 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024234901/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1214|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> There was also a breakfast held in [[Southampton]] on 13 March.\n\nOn 16 April 2013 it was announced that Deltamarin had been contracted for the project development phase, and would be responsible for coordinating the various parties involved in the project, including the shipyard, architects, interior designers and operations managers.<ref name=projdev>{{cite web|last=Crook|first=Andrew|title=Deltamarin to manage Titanic II project development|url=http://www.setcorp.ru/main/pressrelease.phtml?news_id=46609&language=english|publisher=Blue Star Line - Delta Marin Group via setcorp.ru|accessdate=26 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730102917/http://www.setcorp.ru/main/pressrelease.phtml?news_id=46609&language=english|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The feasibility study was complete, and the project development phase was ongoing. The signature of a contract and keel laying was expected in March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Titanic II tycoon Clive Palmer plans movie cameo|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10396090/Titanic-II-tycoon-Clive-Palmer-plans-movie-cameo.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=23 October 2013|location=London|date=22 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026154059/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10396090/Titanic-II-tycoon-Clive-Palmer-plans-movie-cameo.html|archive-date=26 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFurther contracts and agreements relating to the design and construction were announced later in 2013; the appointment of V.Ships Leisure as ship management services partner,<ref>{{cite web|title=V.SHIPS Leisure Appointed To Titanic II|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6228/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=29 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607051124/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6228/|archive-date=7 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and of Tillberg Design as provider of architectural and interior design services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titanic II Engages World\u2019s Leading Marine Architecture and Interior Design Company|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6240/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=29 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609171437/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6240/|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tillbergdesign.com/ajax/getnewpost.php?postid=247 |title=Titanic II (May 29, 2013) |publisher=Tillberg Design of Sweden |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209001546/http://www.tillbergdesign.com/ajax/getnewpost.php?postid=247 |archive-date=9 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nOn 17 July 2013, Blue Star Line announced that the [[classification society]] [[Lloyd's Register of Shipping|Lloyd's Register]] has joined the ''Titanic II'' project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lloyd\u2019s Register Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/07/6248/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=20 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723215347/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/07/6248/|archive-date=2013-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The work carried by Lloyd's would ensure that the ship's design complied with the current [[International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea|SOLAS]] regulations.\n\n[[Ship model basin|Model testing]] using a {{convert|9.3|m|ft|adj=on}} wooden model was undertaken in September 2013 at the Hamburgische Schiffbau-Versuchsanstalt (HSVA). Resistance and powering tests were carried out in a {{convert|300|m|ft|adj=on}} towing tank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clive Palmer announces Titanic II model tests to be held in Germany|url=http://www.robertsleading.com/wordpress/clive-palmer-announces-titanic2-model-test-germany/|publisher=Robert's Cruise & Tour Leading E.U.|accessdate=14 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817084529/http://www.robertsleading.com/wordpress/clive-palmer-announces-titanic2-model-test-germany/|archive-date=17 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Titanic II: Replica of proposed liner tested|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24156988|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=20 September 2013|date=19 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919210920/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24156988|archive-date=19 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in February 2014, Palmer claimed that keel laying would take place in September 2014. He cautioned that the project was \"a big job\", that the original ''Titanic'' took seven years to build while they have been working for only two and a half, and said that he would have liked to start sooner but \"wanted to make sure we don't make any mistakes\". He claimed that a selection of cabins were being constructed on land for approval, and that this would be completed by July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Clive Palmer|url=http://michellegrattan.podbean.com/2014/02/27/clive-palmer/|accessdate=7 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307212250/http://michellegrattan.podbean.com/2014/02/27/clive-palmer/|archive-date=7 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016 the administrators for Palmer's closed nickel refining company, Queensland Nickel alleged that almost $6 million had been taken from that company to pay for the development and marketing of the ''Titanic II''. At that time the administrators indicated that they would seek to recover this money.<ref name=\"Koziol_Queensland_Nickel\">{{cite news|last1=Koziol|first1=Michael|title=Queensland Nickel 'paid $6 million' towards Clive Palmer's stalled Titanic II project|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/collapsed-queensland-nickel-paid-6-million-toward-clive-palmers-stalled-titanic-ii-project-20160412-go4y5k.html|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=The Canberra Times|date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414141745/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/collapsed-queensland-nickel-paid-6-million-toward-clive-palmers-stalled-titanic-ii-project-20160412-go4y5k.html|archive-date=14 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\nThe [[gross tonnage]] of the replica will be 56,000 GT, considerably more than that of the original.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"gt\">The original ''Titanic'' had a [[gross register tonnage]] of 46,328 GRT, which is not directly comparable with modern [[gross tonnage]]. However, as one register ton is equal to {{convert|100|cuft|m3|2}}, an approximate value of 39,640 GT can be calculated by using the formulae given in [http://www.admiraltylawguide.com/conven/tonnage1969.html ''The International Convention on Tonnage Measurement of Ships, 1969''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710100511/http://www.admiraltylawguide.com/conven/tonnage1969.html |date=2012-07-10 }}.</ref>\n\n===Comparison with the original RMS ''Titanic''===\nThe ship is designed to be as similar in internal and external appearance to the ''Titanic'' as possible. However, today's safety regulations and economic considerations dictated several major changes to the design, including:\n\n* Greater [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] for enhanced stability<ref name=Plan>{{cite web|title=General Arrangement, Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/documents/pdf/TitanicII_GA_12%2007%202012%20COLOUR.pdf|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=31 July 2012|author=Deltamarin}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Get a Glimpse of Titanic II|url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruise-news/get-a-glimpse-of-titanic-ii/|publisher=Cruise News|date=25 July 2012|access-date=2 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128155130/http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruise-news/get-a-glimpse-of-titanic-ii|archive-date=28 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Welded, not riveted, hull<ref name=Plan />\n* Reduced [[Draft (hull)|draught (draft)]]<ref name=Plan />\n* Bulbous bow for higher fuel efficiency, although moderately sized compared to ships of newer designs<ref name=Plan />\n[[File:Titanic II Profile Comparison.png|thumb|500px|right|A preliminary comparison of the profiles of the ''Titanic'' (blue) and the ''Titanic II'' (red)]]\n* [[Stabilizer (ship)|Stabilizers]] to reduce [[Ship motions#Rotation motions|roll]]<ref name=Plan />\n* Diesel-electric propulsion system with four diesel generating sets providing power for three [[azimuth thruster]]s to replace the original coal-fired boilers, steam engines and steam turbine, as well as the rudder. Also, the ship would have had 2 bow thrusters.<ref name=Plan />\n* An additional \"safety deck\" between C and D decks for [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]]s and [[marine evacuation system]]s, with the boat deck housing replicas of the original lifeboats. Space for the deck was made by lowering decks D and below by 2.8 metres, and for the taller centre section of the safety deck, which would have housed the lifeboats, by raising the [[superstructure]] by 1.3 metres. In spite of the reduced draft, space was made for the lowered decks by removing the [[Orlop|orlop deck]], which mainly housed the boilers.<ref name=Plan />\n* New 'escape staircases' in addition to the original staircases, housed in the redundant boiler exhaust uptakes.<ref name=Plan />\n* Observation decks in the redundant first two funnels, which would have had, according to Deltamarin, tinted window coverings to blend in with the funnels' color, intended to be as close as possible to the original \"White Star buff.\" <ref name=Plan />\n* No [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]] or [[Camber (ship)|camber]],<ref name=Plan /> unlike the original. Pronounced sheer was a cosmetic feature of ocean liners, intended to add a graceful appearance to the ship, but made construction more difficult and therefore costly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vandersteel|first=William|title=SS Oceanic; A Matter of Design|url=http://www.ssmaritime.com/oceanic.htm|publisher=ssmaritime.com|accessdate=26 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020010906/http://www.ssmaritime.com/oceanic.htm|archive-date=20 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Renderings released in February 2013 showed an upwards rake added to C Deck at the bow and stern to give a superficial appearance of sheer, although an inauthentic wedge-shaped gap has had to be added between C and D decks in these areas to produce this effect.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Return of a Legend|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/?page_id=1607|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=16 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219042600/http://bluestarline.com.au/?page_id=1607|archive-date=19 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n* A higher bridge relative to the bow, as the superstructure has been raised by 1.3 metres by the centre section of the safety deck, and also by the removal of the sheer.<ref name=Plan /> This negates the requirement on the original ''Titanic'' for lookouts.\n* An overall increase in the height of the ship above the waterline (due to the insertion of the safety deck). However, the total height of the ship from the keel to funnels would be the same as the original, at {{convert|175|ft}}.<ref name=EBook>{{cite web|title=Titanic II: Return Of The Legend|url=http://publ.com/mNahlZu|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=26 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429143310/http://publ.com/mNahlZu|archive-date=29 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Power plant and propulsion===\nFor economic reasons, the steam engines and coal-fired boilers of the original ''Titanic'' would be replaced with a modern [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] propulsion system. The space which housed the boilers would be used for crew quarters and ships systems. Power was to be produced by four [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 46F [[Diesel engine#Medium-speed engines|medium-speed]] [[Four-stroke engine|four-stroke]] [[Diesel generator#Diesel generator set|diesel generating sets]]; two [[V12 engine|twelve-cylinder]] 12V46F engines producing {{convert|14400|kW|hp}} each, and two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] 8L46F engines producing {{convert|9600|kW|hp}} each, running on [[heavy fuel oil]] and [[Fuel oil#Maritime|marine gas oil]].<ref name=Plan /> Propulsion would have been by three [[azimuth thruster]]s which would also be used for manoeuvring, while the replica of the [[rudder]] of the ''Titanic II'' is purely cosmetic, and would not have extended substantially below the waterline.<ref name=Plan /> The positioning of the azimuth thrusters necessitated the stern being made substantially more blunt than the original.<ref name=Plan />\n[[File:Queen Mary Hotel Cabin Corridor.jpg|thumb|250px|View of a corridor on the {{RMS|Queen Mary}} showing the [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]]. This feature was to be lost on the ''Titanic II''.]]\n\n===Interior===\nThe interior of the ship was intended to be as similar as possible to the original. Tillberg Design of Sweden was contracted to produce drawings replicating ''Titanic''{{'s}} original interiors. However, the original wooden panelling does not conform to modern fire regulations, so as in ''[[Queen Mary 2]]'', veneers would have had to be used. Plans showed a layout broadly similar to the original, but with the third-class cabins modernised, and consideration being given to en-suite bathrooms throughout the ship.{{Update after|2013|4|6}} The room freed up by eliminating the steam boilers of the original ship would have been used for crew quarters and various services.<ref name=Plan />\n\n==Criticism==\nThe ''Titanic II'' would represent the first major passenger vessel constructed in China, a country with much more experience of building cargo ships than cruise ships, and a significant investment would be required to ensure it met the much more stringent safety requirements for passenger vessels.<ref name=Globaltimes>{{cite web|last=Yi|first=Zheng|title=Titanic II agreed but no contract signed|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/NEWS/tabid/99/ID/707501/Titanic-II-agreed-but-no-contract-signed.aspx|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130407151034/http://www.globaltimes.cn/NEWS/tabid/99/ID/707501/Titanic-II-agreed-but-no-contract-signed.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 April 2013|publisher=Global Times|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese state-owned CSC Jinling shipyard has never built a large passenger vessel. In addition, it has no [[drydock]], instead using [[Ship naming and launching#Methods of launch|side launching]] from a 200&nbsp;m slipway.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Partners|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/our-partners.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811034645/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/our-partners.html|archive-date=2012-08-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 269&nbsp;m ''Titanic II'' would have been the largest side-launched vessel in history by a huge margin,<ref>{{cite web|last=Khetan|first=Ashok|title=World's Biggest Side Launch of Ship in Gujarat|url=http://gmbports.org/emusing_forth_edition/glance_through1.htm|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018000645/http://gmbports.org/emusing_forth_edition/glance_through1.htm|archive-date=2013-10-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> and would have required a significant extension to the shipyard's facilities.\n\nRepresentatives from the shipyard had questioned whether the ship could have been completed by 2016, and emphasized that no contract had been signed.<ref name=Globaltimes />\n\nClive Palmer has been described as an \"eccentric billionaire\" with a reputation for bizarre publicity stunts, such as the attempt to create a massive ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'' style dinosaur theme park at his golf resort.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alwyn-Jones|first=John|title=Clive Palmer goes even more eccentric|url=http://www.eglobaltravelmedia.com.au/2-headline-news/clive-palmer-goes-even-more-eccentric-dinosaurs-at-palmer-coolum-resort.html|publisher=E-Global Travel Media|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103065144/http://www.eglobaltravelmedia.com.au/2-headline-news/clive-palmer-goes-even-more-eccentric-dinosaurs-at-palmer-coolum-resort.html|archive-date=2012-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Titanic, a dinosaur, JFK and the Australian PGA Championship|url=http://www.aussiegolfer.net/2012/12/the-titanic-dinosaur-jfk-and-australian.html|publisher=aussiegolfer.net|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214160616/http://www.aussiegolfer.net/2012/12/the-titanic-dinosaur-jfk-and-australian.html|archive-date=2012-12-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Is an Australian billionaire about to launch the real-life Jurassic Park?|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2182751/Is-Australian-billionaire-launch-real-life-Jurassic-Park.html|publisher=Daily Mail|accessdate=17 February 2013|location=London|date=2 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121221060608/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2182751/Is-Australian-billionaire-launch-real-life-Jurassic-Park.html|archive-date=21 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>  It has also been noted that the publicity surrounding the ''Titanic II'' coincided with Palmer's announcement of his entry into Australian federal politics, which was made immediately following the ''Titanic II'' conference.<ref>{{cite web|last=McKechnie|first=Kirrin|title=Clive Palmer's Titanic bid for federal politics|url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2012/s3491728.htm|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216222602/http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2012/s3491728.htm|archive-date=16 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Palmer had previously claimed that he was the target of a conspiracy involving [[Barack Obama]], the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]], the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] and [[Greenpeace]], who he believed were attempting to close down his mining operation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Farr|first=Malcolm|title=Mining magnate Clive Palmer says CIA is behind campaign to kill coal industry|url=http://www.news.com.au/business/mining-magnate-clive-palmer-says-cia-is-behind-campaign-to-kill-coal-industry/story-e6frfm1i-1226305462536|publisher=News.com.au|accessdate=17 February 2013|date=22 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710091443/http://www.news.com.au/business/mining-magnate-clive-palmer-says-cia-is-behind-campaign-to-kill-coal-industry/story-e6frfm1i-1226305462536|archive-date=10 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Palmer started a company called Zeppelin International, with the intention of making a commercially viable [[Zeppelin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cowie|first=Tom|title=Clive Palmer\u2019s magnificent flying machines|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2010/12/14/clive-palmers-magnificent-flying-machines/|publisher=Crikey.com.au|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022021219/http://www.crikey.com.au/2010/12/14/clive-palmers-magnificent-flying-machines/|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After the plan came to nothing, it was ridiculed as the 'bizarre move of the year' by Australian business website Smartcompany.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomson|first=James|title=The best & the worst of 2010|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/wealth/20101220-the-best-the-worst-of-2010.html|publisher=Smartcompany|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410192320/http://www.smartcompany.com.au/wealth/20101220-the-best-the-worst-of-2010.html|archive-date=2012-04-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has gained a reputation in Australia for floating ambitious and unusual business ideas which he fails to see through, and the ''Titanic II'' has been described as \"a classic Clive Palmer announcement.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomson|first=James|title=How Clive Palmer funds his amazing adventures|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/entrepreneurs/049525-rich-pickings-clive-palmer-s-incredible-adventures.html|publisher=Smartcompany|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111025120/http://www.smartcompany.com.au/entrepreneurs/049525-rich-pickings-clive-palmer-s-incredible-adventures.html|archive-date=11 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of a commercialised replica of the ''Titanic'' has itself been criticised, being described as \"insensitive\" and \"a mockery of the memory of those who died\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gaynor|first=Hazel|title=Sinking feeling: unease about Titanic II plan|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/humaninterest/sinking-feeling-unease-about-titanic-ii-plan-228623.html|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=26 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424042618/http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/humaninterest/sinking-feeling-unease-about-titanic-ii-plan-228623.html|archive-date=24 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Cunard Line]], which acquired the White Star Line legacy when the companies merged in 1934, stated that they \"have always been very mindful and very respectful of such a tragic event [and] don't think that building a replica or a 'II' is appropriate.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/05/28/57551-2/2 |title=Titanic II- Bigger replica of the iconic liner, to set sail in 2018 \u2026 |last=Patrick |first=Neil |publisher=Timera Media |date=May 28, 2016 |website=VingateNews.com |access-date=2 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103005141/https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/05/28/57551-2/2 |archive-date=3 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPalmer's alleged use of funds drawn from Queensland Nickel for the ''Titanic II'' project was criticised by the administrators appointed for that company after it closed. In their April 2016 report, the administrators stated that payments from Queensland Nickel to Blue Star Line had been \"uncommercial and director-related transactions\".<ref name=\"Koziol_Queensland_Nickel\" /> Palmer has rejected the claims made against him in the report, including those related to the ''Titanic II''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Remeikis|first1=Amy|last2=Danckert|first2=Sarah|title=Queensland Nickel report 'filled with innuendo': Clive Palmer|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-report-filled-with-innuendo-clive-palmer-20160413-go52fp.html|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=Brisbane Times|date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420022559/http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-report-filled-with-innuendo-clive-palmer-20160413-go52fp.html|archive-date=20 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Project status==\nWhen the project was first announced in 2012, Palmer claimed that construction would begin before the end of the year, with a 2016 launch.  The following year reports emerged that Clive Palmer was experiencing financial difficulties.<ref name=Financial>{{cite web |last=Khadem |first=Nassim |title=Clive Palmer disputes \u2018beat-up\u2019 about Queensland Nickel\u2019s future |url=http://www.brw.com.au/p/business/clive_palmer_disputes_beat_up_about_gW1VXcpOLGMRwNOk7QhpTN |publisher=BRW |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001120657/http://www.brw.com.au/p/business/clive_palmer_disputes_beat_up_about_gW1VXcpOLGMRwNOk7QhpTN |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mccullough |first=James |title=Clive Palmer still Queensland's richest person |url=http://www.news.com.au/national-news/queensland/clive-palmer-still-queenslands-richest-person-according-to-brw-rich-200-list-gina-rineheart-australias-richest-person/story-fnii5v6w-1226648503100 |publisher=news.com.au |accessdate=30 May 2018 |date=22 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916023012/http://www.news.com.au/national-news/queensland/clive-palmer-still-queenslands-richest-person-according-to-brw-rich-200-list-gina-rineheart-australias-richest-person/story-fnii5v6w-1226648503100 |archive-date=16 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The start of construction was postponed to March 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Australian tycoon says Titanic project is about love |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/travel/article/australian-tycoon-says-titanic-project-is-about-love |publisher=The Malay Mail |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024142217/http://www.themalaymailonline.com/travel/article/australian-tycoon-says-titanic-project-is-about-love |archive-date=24 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> then to late 2014.<ref name=delta>{{cite web |title=Deltamarin designs Titanic II |url=https://www.deltamarin.com/2013/09/deltamarin-designs-titanic-ii/ |publisher=Deltamarin |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024035423/https://www.deltamarin.com/2013/09/deltamarin-designs-titanic-ii/ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> When construction had still not begun in 2015 a spokesman for Palmer said the project had merely been delayed, and that the new ship would be launched in 2018 - two years later than initially planned.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cruiseshipnews.co.uk/20150914/titanic-2-ticket-demand-renewed-following-latest-launch-news |title=Titanic 2 ticket demand renewed following latest launch news |publisher=CruiseNews, Dansway Communications LTD |access-date=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703112635/http://www.cruiseshipnews.co.uk/20150914/titanic-2-ticket-demand-renewed-following-latest-launch-news |archive-date=2017-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However Deltamarin had told an [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] journalist that work on the ''Titanic II'' project had been halted<ref name=\"ABC Palmer's empire feeling the pinch\">{{cite news|last1=McCutcheon|first1=Peter|title=Clive Palmer's empire feeling the pinch from falling iron ore prices|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-27/clive-palmer-empire-and-impact-of-falling-iron-ore-prices/6354104|accessdate=30 May 2018|work=ABC News|date=27 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327103815/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-27/clive-palmer-empire-and-impact-of-falling-iron-ore-prices/6354104|archive-date=27 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while workers at the Chinese shipyard identified as the likely site of construction were highly skeptical that the project would ever move beyond the proposal stage<ref name=\"Palmer\u2019s Titanic II plans all but scuttled\">{{cite web | url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2015/03/20/11/16/palmers-titanic-ii-plans-all-but-scuttled | title=Palmer\u2019s Titanic II plans all but scuttled | publisher=9News.com Finance | date=20 March 2015 | accessdate=30 May 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825181301/https://www.9news.com.au/national/2015/03/20/11/16/palmers-titanic-ii-plans-all-but-scuttled | archive-date=25 August 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the Blue Star Line trademark was \"abandoned.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Trademark Category > Chemical Products > TITANIC II BLUE STAR LINE|url=http://www.trademarkia.com/titanic-ii-blue-star-line-79142812.html|website=LegalForce Trademarks|publisher=Trademarkia, Inc.|accessdate=30 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180248/https://www.trademarkia.com/titanic-ii-blue-star-line-79142812.html|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Queensland Nickel went bankrupt and Palmer faced freezing of personal assets to recoup money owed the company's employees and creditors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Branco|first1=Brace|title=Queensland Nickel liquidators could freeze Clive Palmer's assets|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-liquidators-could-freeze-clive-palmers-assets-20160422-gocym3.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824100832/http://www.smh.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-liquidators-could-freeze-clive-palmers-assets-20160422-gocym3.html|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When he declined to stand for re-election to his House of Representatives seat he stated that he might resume work on the project in his retirement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeans|first1=David|title=Is mining billionaire Clive Palmer's Titanic II dream under water? Finnish shipbuilder 'has stopped working on plans' to design a replica of the doomed ocean liner|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3578686/Is-mining-billionaire-Clive-Palmer-s-Titanic-II-dream-water-Finnish-shipbuilder-stopped-working-plans-design-replica-doomed-ocean-liner.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=The Daily Mail|date=May 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226050800/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3578686/Is-mining-billionaire-Clive-Palmer-s-Titanic-II-dream-water-Finnish-shipbuilder-stopped-working-plans-design-replica-doomed-ocean-liner.html|archive-date=26 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2018 the Blue Star Line, in a press release on their official web site, announced that work on the project would recommence.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Palmer Building Titanic II |url=https://www.bluestarline.com.au/palmer-building-titanic-ll/ |location= |publisher=Blue Star Line |agency= |date=September 27, 2018 |access-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030022000/https://www.bluestarline.com.au/palmer-building-titanic-ll/ |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2019 a European maritime equipment consortium published a list of all cruise ships on order through 2027 but none of the listed vessels fit Deltamarin's specifications for ''Titanic II''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amem.at/pdf/AMEM_Cruise-Ships-on-Order.pdf |title=AMEM Cruise Ships on Order 2016-2027 |publisher=Austrian Marine Equipment Manufacturers |access-date=24 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603135131/https://www.amem.at/pdf/AMEM_Cruise-Ships-on-Order.pdf |archive-date=3 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a reply to a reader query on their website in December 2019, Deltamarin responded that while design work was still ongoing, any questions regarding the start of construction had to be referred to the ship owners.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deltamarin.com/2019/01/deltamarins-further-involvement-in-titanic-ii-project-confirmed/ |title=Deltamarin\u2019s further involvement in Titanic II project confirmed |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Romandisea ''Titanic''==\nPalmer's project should not be confused with a [[Romandisea Titanic|Chinese Romandisea ''Titanic'' replica ship]] which had its keel laying on November 29, 2016. Commissioned by Seven Star Energy Investment, it is to function as a part of Romandisea resort on the River Qi in [[Sichuan|Sichuan province]]. Unlike Palmer's ''Titanic II'', the all-Chinese replica is not intended to sail on any ocean but will be permanently docked within a reservoir.<ref>{{cite news\n |author       = Burford, Rachel\n |title        = Work begins on \u00a3116million life-size replica of the TITANIC in China which will allow visitors to relive the sinking which claimed 1,500 lives\n |url          = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3987472/Work-begins-116million-life-size-replica-TITANIC-China-allow-visitors-relive-sinking-claimed-1-500-lives.html\n |newspaper    = Daily Mail\n |location     = London, UK\n |date         = November 30, 2016\n |access-date  = 5 December 2016\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20161204144310/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3987472/Work-begins-116million-life-size-replica-TITANIC-China-allow-visitors-relive-sinking-claimed-1-500-lives.html\n |archive-date = 4 December 2016\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>  As of August 2019 construction had reached D deck, according to their official media site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/RomandiseaT2/status/1167253573672951808 |title=Assembly on D deck midship|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Transport}}\n*[[Replica Titanic|Replica ''Titanic'']]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bluestarline.com.au Blue Star Line Official Site]\n\n{{RMS Titanic}}\n\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Proposed ships]]\n[[Category:Replica ships]]\n[[Category:RMS Titanic]]\n[[Category:Ocean liners of Australia]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2012]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Clive Palmer project|the 2010 disaster film|Titanic II (film)|the Titanic replica ship under construction in Sichuan|Romandisea Titanic}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin\n| display title = ital\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = Titanic II.jpg\n| Ship caption = 3D rendering of ''Titanic II''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship flag = [[File:Blue Star Line Cruises Flag 2.svg|100x35px]]\n| Ship name = ''Titanic II''\n| Ship owner = Blue Star Line Pty. Ltd., [[Brisbane]], Australia\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship registry = \n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = [[CSC Jinling]], [[Nanjing]]<ref name=\"orderbook\" />\n| Ship original cost = $500 million (estimated)<ref name=\"orderbook\">[http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/cruise-ship-orderbook.html Cruise Ship Orderbook] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712071905/http://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/cruise-ship-orderbook.html |date=2016-07-12 }}. Cruise Industry News. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-04-23}}</ref>\n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship christened = \n| Ship completed = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship identification = \n| Ship status = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship class = Modern interpretation of [[Olympic-class ocean liner|''Olympic''-class]] [[ocean liner]]\n| Ship type = \n| Ship tonnage = {{GT|56,000}} (estimate)\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = {{convert|269.15|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|32.2|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = {{convert|53.35|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = {{convert|7.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}} (normal){{br}}{{convert|7.926|m|ftin|abbr=on}} (max)\n| \n| Ship depth = {{convert|19.74|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 10\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = * 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46F\n* 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 8L46F\n* {{convert|48000|kW|hp|abbr=on}} (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = [[Diesel-electric transmission|Diesel-electric]]; three [[azimuth thruster]]s; (3{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}10{{nbsp}}MW)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deltamarin.fi/articles/blog/updated-titanic-ii-model-tests/9-32 |date=2013-09-20 |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111193447/http://www.deltamarin.fi/articles/blog/updated-titanic-ii-model-tests/9-32 |archivedate=2013-11-11 |work=Deltamarin Blog |title=Updated Titanic II model tests}}</ref>\n| Ship sail plan = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|24|kn}} (maximum)<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2284933/Titanic-II-Australian-tycoon-unveils-plans-replica-doomed-vessel.html The Titanic sails again: Australian tycoon unveils plans for perfect replica of doomed vessel (except with a few more lifeboats)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511021533/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2284933/Titanic-II-Australian-tycoon-unveils-plans-replica-doomed-vessel.html |date=2013-05-11 }}. Daily Mail, 25 February 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-05-11}}</ref>\n| Ship capacity = 1,680 (double capacity); 2,435 (maximum)\n| Ship crew = 900\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Titanic II''''' is a planned [[ocean liner]] intended to be a functional modern-day replica of the [[Olympic class ocean liner|''Olympic''-class]] {{RMS|Titanic}}. The new ship is planned to have a [[gross tonnage]] (GT) of 56,000 while the original ship measured about 46,000 [[gross register tons]] (GRT).<ref group=\"note\" name=\"gt\" /> The project was announced by [[Australian]] billionaire<!-- this is correct according to Forbes magazine - do not change! --> [[Clive Palmer]] in April 2012 as the flagship of the proposed cruise company Blue Star Line Pty. Ltd. of [[Brisbane]], Australia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Calligeros|first=Marissa|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/clive-palmer-plans-to-build-titanic-ii-20120430-1xtrc.html|title=Clive Palmer plans to build Titanic II|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 April 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724113115/http://www.smh.com.au/business/clive-palmer-plans-to-build-titanic-ii-20120430-1xtrc.html|archive-date=24 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The intended launch date was originally set in 2016,<ref>{{cite news|last=Fickling|first=David|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-30/titanic-ii-to-be-built-by-billionaire-palmer-chinese-yard.html|title=Titanic II to Be Built by Billionaire Palmer, Chinese Yard|publisher=Bloomberg|date=30 April 2012|access-date=12 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127092941/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-30/titanic-ii-to-be-built-by-billionaire-palmer-chinese-yard.html|archive-date=27 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> delayed to 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/titanic-ii-set-to-sail-in-2018-says-aussie-billionaire-31492220.html|title=Titanic II set to sail in 2018, says Aussie billionaire - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313093926/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/titanic-ii-set-to-sail-in-2018-says-aussie-billionaire-31492220.html|archive-date=2017-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> then 2022.<ref name=MIDEAST>{{cite web |url=https://www.logisticsmiddleeast.com/transport/maritime/31491-titanic-ii-replica-ships-cruise-from-dubai-delayed-until-2022 |title=Titanic II replica ship\u2019s cruise from Dubai delayed until 2022 |publisher=Logistics Middle East |access-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018003142/https://www.logisticsmiddleeast.com/transport/maritime/31491-titanic-ii-replica-ships-cruise-from-dubai-delayed-until-2022 |archive-date=18 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The development of the project was resumed in November 2018 after a hiatus which began in 2015, caused by a financial dispute<ref>{{cite news |title=Deltamarin continues work on Titanic II |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/oct/24/titanic-2-australian-billionaire-refloats-dream-clive-palmer |date24 october= |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=December 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215222234/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/oct/24/titanic-2-australian-billionaire-refloats-dream-clive-palmer |archive-date=December 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bluestarline.com.au/deltamarin-continues-work-on-titanic-ii/|title=Deltamarin continues to work on Titanic II|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=9 November 2018|accessdate=December 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215222408/https://www.bluestarline.com.au/deltamarin-continues-work-on-titanic-ii/|archive-date=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> that affected the $500 million project.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shabina|url=https://traveljee.com/luxury/titanic-ii-ship/|title=Titanic II Ship Ticket Prices 2022, Release Date, Construction Cost, Facts and Latest Updates|publisher=Traveljee|date=13 February 2019|access-date=17 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401174918/https://traveljee.com/luxury/titanic-ii-ship/|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Previous projects==\n[[File:Titanic.jpg|thumb|305px|right|The original {{RMS|Titanic}} in 1912.]]\n[[File:TitanicII-001.jpg|thumb|305px|right|The proposed ship]]\nThe concept of a functioning replica of the ''Titanic'' has been explored several times, especially following the resurgence of interest following the release of [[James Cameron]]'s [[Titanic (1997 film)|film]] in 1997. The most widely publicized project was that of South African businessman Sarel Gous in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ringshaw|first=Grant|title=A Titanic task|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|date=19 November 2000|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=24 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629185602/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|archive-date=29 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe South African project began in 1998, and was one of the subjects of an article in ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' magazine in September of that year.<ref>{{cite book | last = Wilson | first = James | title = Titanic Reborn | publisher = [[Popular Mechanics]] | date = September 1998 | pages = 56\u201359 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YmYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA4&dq=Titanic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=z4QsT8ngNufY0QGaqLTPCg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Titanic&f=true | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131231225552/http://books.google.com/books?id=YmYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA4&dq=Titanic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=z4QsT8ngNufY0QGaqLTPCg&ved=0CGEQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Titanic&f=true | archive-date = 31 December 2013 | url-status = live }}</ref> The article discussed the changes to the original design required to produce a safe and economically viable ship, including a welded rather than riveted hull, [[diesel-electric]] propulsion in place of steam engines, and a [[bulbous bow]]. The article concluded that although the various ''Titanic'' revival projects would cost $400\u2013$600 million, they could be economically viable.\n\nAlthough he originally intended to construct the ship in [[Durban]], Gous presented his \u00a3500 million proposal to [[Belfast City Council]] in June 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tycoon presents Titanic II proposal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/783531.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 August 2012|date=9 June 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122104446/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/783531.stm|archive-date=22 January 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> He commissioned Olsen Designs to design the ship, advised by [[Harland and Wolff]] Technical Services who produced a [[feasibility study]], and Callcott Anderson to design the interior. In November 2000, he began his attempts to raise capital, including through government grants and a stock market flotation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ringshaw|first=Grant|title=A Titanic task|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=11 October 2012|date=19 November 2000|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105085431/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/comment/4472821/A-Titanic-task.html|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After signing an agreement with a Monaco-based investment banking company, Gous claimed that construction would begin at Harland and Wolff within nine months.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oldham|first=Jeanette|title=Dreams afloat to build Titanic II|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-67126861|publisher=Questia Online Library|accessdate=11 October 2012 |date=20 November 2000 }}</ref> The design changed repeatedly, with claims emerging of 'the world's largest liner' with capacity for 2,600 passengers, and increasingly divergent plans for a heliport, swimming pools and discos eventually being released.<ref name=Epstein>{{cite web|last=Louis|first=Epstein|title=To Build a New Titanic?|url=http://www.put.com/gigantic/|accessdate=11 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817193413/http://www.put.com/gigantic/|archivedate=17 August 2012}}</ref> In 2006, after repeatedly failing to secure investment, the project was abandoned.<ref name=Epstein />\n\n==Design stage==\n[[File:Clive Palmer Aug15 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Clive Palmer, chairman of the Blue Star Line]]\nClive Palmer first announced the project in a press conference on 30 April 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Clive Palmer Launches Titanic II|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120430.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=30 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130312004302/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120430.html|archivedate=12 March 2013}}</ref> following the signature of a [[memorandum of understanding]] with state-owned Chinese shipyard CSC Jinling ten days before.<ref>{{cite web|title=MOU CSC Jinling and Blue Star Line|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120420.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=20 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721235318/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120420.html|archivedate=21 July 2012}}</ref> On 19 June, it was announced that Finnish naval architecture firm Deltamarin Ltd. had been commissioned to undertake the design of the ship,<ref>{{cite news|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/travel/titanic-ii-a-step-closer-to-reality-20120619-20l96.html|title=Titanic II a step closer to reality|publisher=Brisbane Times|date=19 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Global Ship Design Firm Commissioned to Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120619.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309073721/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120619.html|archivedate=9 March 2013}}</ref> and on 17 July a preliminary general arrangement was published.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Glimpse At Titanic II Plans|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120717.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120720205448/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/media-20120717.html|archivedate=20 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Blue Star Line announced that ''Titanic'' expert Steve Hall had been appointed as Design Consultant and Historian for the project,<ref>{{cite web|title=Renown Titanic Historian Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=1 October 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809054357/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/|archive-date=9 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and that ''Titanic'' interiors expert Daniel Klistorner had been appointed as Interior Design Consultant and Historian.<ref name=Klistorner>{{cite web|title=Titanic Researcher and Interiors Expert Joins Blue Star Line|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1221|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=11 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024234906/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1221|archivedate=24 October 2012}}</ref> Hall and Klistorner had previously co-authored books such as ''Titanic: The Ship Magnificent'' and ''Titanic in Photographs'', and gave a technical presentation at the unveiling of the designs in New York, as well as at the dinner in London.<ref name=Klistorner /> Later that month, it was announced that an advisory board would be formed to provide \"suggestions and recommendations to Blue Star Line to ensure the ''Titanic II'' appropriately and respectfully pays homage to ''Titanic'', her crew and passengers.\" Terry Ismay, the great-great nephew of [[White Star Line]] chairman and ''Titanic'' survivor [[J. Bruce Ismay]], will be a member of the board,<ref>{{cite web|title=White Star Line Chairman Descendant Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1235|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=19 October 2012|access-date=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024225846/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1235|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> as well as Helen Benziger, great-granddaughter of ''Titanic'' survivor [[Margaret Brown|Margaret \"Molly\" Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Molly Brown Descendant Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1242|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=21 October 2012|access-date=21 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024225854/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1242|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe design for the ''Titanic II'' was unveiled at worldwide launch events in Macau (China), New York (United States), Halifax (Canada), London & Southampton (United Kingdom). The gala event in New York was the official Global Launch and was held aboard the [[USS Intrepid (CV-11)|USS ''Intrepid'']] in New York City on 26 February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Dates for Titanic II Global Launch and Events|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1303|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=20 December 2012|access-date=20 December 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130114214830/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1303|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Design for Titanic II to be unveiled in NYC|url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19722578/design-for-titanic-ii-to-be-unveiled-in-nyc|publisher=MYFOXNY.COM|date=3 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006001239/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19722578/design-for-titanic-ii-to-be-unveiled-in-nyc|archivedate=6 October 2012}}</ref> The gala dinner in London (UK) was held at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] on 2 March, and was accompanied by a display of items salvaged from the ''Titanic''.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Event To Celebrate Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1214|publisher=Blue Star Line|date=9 October 2012|access-date=11 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024234901/http://bluestarline.com.au/titanic-ii/?p=1214|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> There was also a breakfast held in [[Southampton]] on 13 March.\n\nOn 16 April 2013 it was announced that Deltamarin had been contracted for the project development phase, and would be responsible for coordinating the various parties involved in the project, including the shipyard, architects, interior designers and operations managers.<ref name=projdev>{{cite web|last=Crook|first=Andrew|title=Deltamarin to manage Titanic II project development|url=http://www.setcorp.ru/main/pressrelease.phtml?news_id=46609&language=english|publisher=Blue Star Line - Delta Marin Group via setcorp.ru|accessdate=26 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730102917/http://www.setcorp.ru/main/pressrelease.phtml?news_id=46609&language=english|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The feasibility study was complete, and the project development phase was ongoing. The signature of a contract and keel laying was expected in March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Titanic II tycoon Clive Palmer plans movie cameo|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10396090/Titanic-II-tycoon-Clive-Palmer-plans-movie-cameo.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=23 October 2013|location=London|date=22 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026154059/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10396090/Titanic-II-tycoon-Clive-Palmer-plans-movie-cameo.html|archive-date=26 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFurther contracts and agreements relating to the design and construction were announced later in 2013; the appointment of V.Ships Leisure as ship management services partner,<ref>{{cite web|title=V.SHIPS Leisure Appointed To Titanic II|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6228/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=29 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607051124/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6228/|archive-date=7 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and of Tillberg Design as provider of architectural and interior design services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titanic II Engages World\u2019s Leading Marine Architecture and Interior Design Company|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6240/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=29 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609171437/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/05/6240/|archive-date=9 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tillbergdesign.com/ajax/getnewpost.php?postid=247 |title=Titanic II (May 29, 2013) |publisher=Tillberg Design of Sweden |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209001546/http://www.tillbergdesign.com/ajax/getnewpost.php?postid=247 |archive-date=9 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nOn 17 July 2013, Blue Star Line announced that the [[classification society]] [[Lloyd's Register of Shipping|Lloyd's Register]] has joined the ''Titanic II'' project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lloyd\u2019s Register Joins Titanic II Project|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/07/6248/|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=20 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723215347/http://bluestarline.com.au/2013/07/6248/|archive-date=2013-07-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The work carried by Lloyd's would ensure that the ship's design complied with the current [[International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea|SOLAS]] regulations.\n\n[[Ship model basin|Model testing]] using a {{convert|9.3|m|ft|adj=on}} wooden model was undertaken in September 2013 at the Hamburgische Schiffbau-Versuchsanstalt (HSVA). Resistance and powering tests were carried out in a {{convert|300|m|ft|adj=on}} towing tank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clive Palmer announces Titanic II model tests to be held in Germany|url=http://www.robertsleading.com/wordpress/clive-palmer-announces-titanic2-model-test-germany/|publisher=Robert's Cruise & Tour Leading E.U.|accessdate=14 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817084529/http://www.robertsleading.com/wordpress/clive-palmer-announces-titanic2-model-test-germany/|archive-date=17 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Titanic II: Replica of proposed liner tested|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24156988|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=20 September 2013|date=19 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919210920/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-24156988|archive-date=19 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in February 2014, Palmer claimed that keel laying would take place in September 2014. He cautioned that the project was \"a big job\", that the original ''Titanic'' took seven years to build while they have been working for only two and a half, and said that he would have liked to start sooner but \"wanted to make sure we don't make any mistakes\". He claimed that a selection of cabins were being constructed on land for approval, and that this would be completed by July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Clive Palmer|url=http://michellegrattan.podbean.com/2014/02/27/clive-palmer/|accessdate=7 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307212250/http://michellegrattan.podbean.com/2014/02/27/clive-palmer/|archive-date=7 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016 the administrators for Palmer's closed nickel refining company, Queensland Nickel alleged that almost $6 million had been taken from that company to pay for the development and marketing of the ''Titanic II''. At that time the administrators indicated that they would seek to recover this money.<ref name=\"Koziol_Queensland_Nickel\">{{cite news|last1=Koziol|first1=Michael|title=Queensland Nickel 'paid $6 million' towards Clive Palmer's stalled Titanic II project|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/collapsed-queensland-nickel-paid-6-million-toward-clive-palmers-stalled-titanic-ii-project-20160412-go4y5k.html|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=The Canberra Times|date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414141745/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/collapsed-queensland-nickel-paid-6-million-toward-clive-palmers-stalled-titanic-ii-project-20160412-go4y5k.html|archive-date=14 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\nThe [[gross tonnage]] of the replica will be 56,000 GT, considerably more than that of the original.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"gt\">The original ''Titanic'' had a [[gross register tonnage]] of 46,328 GRT, which is not directly comparable with modern [[gross tonnage]]. However, as one register ton is equal to {{convert|100|cuft|m3|2}}, an approximate value of 39,640 GT can be calculated by using the formulae given in [http://www.admiraltylawguide.com/conven/tonnage1969.html ''The International Convention on Tonnage Measurement of Ships, 1969''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710100511/http://www.admiraltylawguide.com/conven/tonnage1969.html |date=2012-07-10 }}.</ref>\n\n===Comparison with the original RMS ''Titanic''===\nThe ship is designed to be as similar in internal and external appearance to the ''Titanic'' as possible. However, today's safety regulations and economic considerations dictated several major changes to the design, including:\n\n* Greater [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] for enhanced stability<ref name=Plan>{{cite web|title=General Arrangement, Titanic II Project|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/documents/pdf/TitanicII_GA_12%2007%202012%20COLOUR.pdf|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=31 July 2012|author=Deltamarin}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Get a Glimpse of Titanic II|url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruise-news/get-a-glimpse-of-titanic-ii/|publisher=Cruise News|date=25 July 2012|access-date=2 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128155130/http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruise-news/get-a-glimpse-of-titanic-ii|archive-date=28 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Welded, not riveted, hull<ref name=Plan />\n* Reduced [[Draft (hull)|draught (draft)]]<ref name=Plan />\n* Bulbous bow for higher fuel efficiency, although moderately sized compared to ships of newer designs<ref name=Plan />\n[[File:Titanic II Profile Comparison.png|thumb|500px|right|A preliminary comparison of the profiles of the ''Titanic'' (blue) and the ''Titanic II'' (red)]]\n* [[Stabilizer (ship)|Stabilizers]] to reduce [[Ship motions#Rotation motions|roll]]<ref name=Plan />\n* Diesel-electric propulsion system with four diesel generating sets providing power for three [[azimuth thruster]]s to replace the original coal-fired boilers, steam engines and steam turbine, as well as the rudder. Also, the ship would have had 2 bow thrusters.<ref name=Plan />\n* An additional \"safety deck\" between C and D decks for [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]]s and [[marine evacuation system]]s, with the boat deck housing replicas of the original lifeboats. Space for the deck was made by lowering decks D and below by 2.8 metres, and for the taller centre section of the safety deck, which would have housed the lifeboats, by raising the [[superstructure]] by 1.3 metres. In spite of the reduced draft, space was made for the lowered decks by removing the [[Orlop|orlop deck]], which mainly housed the boilers.<ref name=Plan />\n* New 'escape staircases' in addition to the original staircases, housed in the redundant boiler exhaust uptakes.<ref name=Plan />\n* Observation decks in the redundant first two funnels, which would have had, according to Deltamarin, tinted window coverings to blend in with the funnels' color, intended to be as close as possible to the original \"White Star buff.\" <ref name=Plan />\n* No [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]] or [[Camber (ship)|camber]],<ref name=Plan /> unlike the original. Pronounced sheer was a cosmetic feature of ocean liners, intended to add a graceful appearance to the ship, but made construction more difficult and therefore costly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vandersteel|first=William|title=SS Oceanic; A Matter of Design|url=http://www.ssmaritime.com/oceanic.htm|publisher=ssmaritime.com|accessdate=26 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020010906/http://www.ssmaritime.com/oceanic.htm|archive-date=20 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Renderings released in February 2013 showed an upwards rake added to C Deck at the bow and stern to give a superficial appearance of sheer, although an inauthentic wedge-shaped gap has had to be added between C and D decks in these areas to produce this effect.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Return of a Legend|url=http://bluestarline.com.au/?page_id=1607|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=16 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219042600/http://bluestarline.com.au/?page_id=1607|archive-date=19 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n* A higher bridge relative to the bow, as the superstructure has been raised by 1.3 metres by the centre section of the safety deck, and also by the removal of the sheer.<ref name=Plan /> This negates the requirement on the original ''Titanic'' for lookouts.\n* An overall increase in the height of the ship above the waterline (due to the insertion of the safety deck). However, the total height of the ship from the keel to funnels would be the same as the original, at {{convert|175|ft}}.<ref name=EBook>{{cite web|title=Titanic II: Return Of The Legend|url=http://publ.com/mNahlZu|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=26 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429143310/http://publ.com/mNahlZu|archive-date=29 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Power plant and propulsion===\nFor economic reasons, the steam engines and coal-fired boilers of the original ''Titanic'' would be replaced with a modern [[Diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] propulsion system. The space which housed the boilers would be used for crew quarters and ships systems. Power was to be produced by four [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 46F [[Diesel engine#Medium-speed engines|medium-speed]] [[Four-stroke engine|four-stroke]] [[Diesel generator#Diesel generator set|diesel generating sets]]; two [[V12 engine|twelve-cylinder]] 12V46F engines producing {{convert|14400|kW|hp}} each, and two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] 8L46F engines producing {{convert|9600|kW|hp}} each, running on [[heavy fuel oil]] and [[Fuel oil#Maritime|marine gas oil]].<ref name=Plan /> Propulsion would have been by three [[azimuth thruster]]s which would also be used for manoeuvring, while the replica of the [[rudder]] of the ''Titanic II'' is purely cosmetic, and would not have extended substantially below the waterline.<ref name=Plan /> The positioning of the azimuth thrusters necessitated the stern being made substantially more blunt than the original.<ref name=Plan />\n[[File:Queen Mary Hotel Cabin Corridor.jpg|thumb|250px|View of a corridor on the {{RMS|Queen Mary}} showing the [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]]. This feature was to be lost on the ''Titanic II''.]]\n\n===Interior===\nThe interior of the ship was intended to be as similar as possible to the original. Tillberg Design of Sweden was contracted to produce drawings replicating ''Titanic''{{'s}} original interiors. However, the original wooden panelling does not conform to modern fire regulations, so as in ''[[Queen Mary 2]]'', veneers would have had to be used. Plans showed a layout broadly similar to the original, but with the third-class cabins modernised, and consideration being given to en-suite bathrooms throughout the ship.{{Update after|2013|4|6}} The room freed up by eliminating the steam boilers of the original ship would have been used for crew quarters and various services.<ref name=Plan />\n\n==Criticism==\nThe ''Titanic II'' would represent the first major passenger vessel constructed in China, a country with much more experience of building cargo ships than cruise ships, and a significant investment would be required to ensure it met the much more stringent safety requirements for passenger vessels.<ref name=Globaltimes>{{cite web|last=Yi|first=Zheng|title=Titanic II agreed but no contract signed|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/NEWS/tabid/99/ID/707501/Titanic-II-agreed-but-no-contract-signed.aspx|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130407151034/http://www.globaltimes.cn/NEWS/tabid/99/ID/707501/Titanic-II-agreed-but-no-contract-signed.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 April 2013|publisher=Global Times|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese state-owned CSC Jinling shipyard has never built a large passenger vessel. In addition, it has no [[drydock]], instead using [[Ship naming and launching#Methods of launch|side launching]] from a 200&nbsp;m slipway.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Partners|url=http://www.bluestarline.com.au/our-partners.html|publisher=Blue Star Line|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811034645/http://www.bluestarline.com.au/our-partners.html|archive-date=2012-08-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 269&nbsp;m ''Titanic II'' would have been the largest side-launched vessel in history by a huge margin,<ref>{{cite web|last=Khetan|first=Ashok|title=World's Biggest Side Launch of Ship in Gujarat|url=http://gmbports.org/emusing_forth_edition/glance_through1.htm|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018000645/http://gmbports.org/emusing_forth_edition/glance_through1.htm|archive-date=2013-10-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> and would have required a significant extension to the shipyard's facilities.\n\nRepresentatives from the shipyard had questioned whether the ship could have been completed by 2016, and emphasized that no contract had been signed.<ref name=Globaltimes />\n\nClive Palmer has been described as an \"eccentric billionaire\" with a reputation for bizarre publicity stunts, such as the attempt to create a massive ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'' style dinosaur theme park at his golf resort.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alwyn-Jones|first=John|title=Clive Palmer goes even more eccentric|url=http://www.eglobaltravelmedia.com.au/2-headline-news/clive-palmer-goes-even-more-eccentric-dinosaurs-at-palmer-coolum-resort.html|publisher=E-Global Travel Media|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103065144/http://www.eglobaltravelmedia.com.au/2-headline-news/clive-palmer-goes-even-more-eccentric-dinosaurs-at-palmer-coolum-resort.html|archive-date=2012-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Titanic, a dinosaur, JFK and the Australian PGA Championship|url=http://www.aussiegolfer.net/2012/12/the-titanic-dinosaur-jfk-and-australian.html|publisher=aussiegolfer.net|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214160616/http://www.aussiegolfer.net/2012/12/the-titanic-dinosaur-jfk-and-australian.html|archive-date=2012-12-14|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Is an Australian billionaire about to launch the real-life Jurassic Park?|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2182751/Is-Australian-billionaire-launch-real-life-Jurassic-Park.html|publisher=Daily Mail|accessdate=17 February 2013|location=London|date=2 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121221060608/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2182751/Is-Australian-billionaire-launch-real-life-Jurassic-Park.html|archive-date=21 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>  It has also been noted that the publicity surrounding the ''Titanic II'' coincided with Palmer's announcement of his entry into Australian federal politics, which was made immediately following the ''Titanic II'' conference.<ref>{{cite web|last=McKechnie|first=Kirrin|title=Clive Palmer's Titanic bid for federal politics|url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2012/s3491728.htm|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216222602/http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2012/s3491728.htm|archive-date=16 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Palmer had previously claimed that he was the target of a conspiracy involving [[Barack Obama]], the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]], the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] and [[Greenpeace]], who he believed were attempting to close down his mining operation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Farr|first=Malcolm|title=Mining magnate Clive Palmer says CIA is behind campaign to kill coal industry|url=http://www.news.com.au/business/mining-magnate-clive-palmer-says-cia-is-behind-campaign-to-kill-coal-industry/story-e6frfm1i-1226305462536|publisher=News.com.au|accessdate=17 February 2013|date=22 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710091443/http://www.news.com.au/business/mining-magnate-clive-palmer-says-cia-is-behind-campaign-to-kill-coal-industry/story-e6frfm1i-1226305462536|archive-date=10 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Palmer started a company called Zeppelin International, with the intention of making a commercially viable [[Zeppelin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cowie|first=Tom|title=Clive Palmer\u2019s magnificent flying machines|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2010/12/14/clive-palmers-magnificent-flying-machines/|publisher=Crikey.com.au|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022021219/http://www.crikey.com.au/2010/12/14/clive-palmers-magnificent-flying-machines/|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> After the plan came to nothing, it was ridiculed as the 'bizarre move of the year' by Australian business website Smartcompany.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomson|first=James|title=The best & the worst of 2010|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/wealth/20101220-the-best-the-worst-of-2010.html|publisher=Smartcompany|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410192320/http://www.smartcompany.com.au/wealth/20101220-the-best-the-worst-of-2010.html|archive-date=2012-04-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has gained a reputation in Australia for floating ambitious and unusual business ideas which he fails to see through, and the ''Titanic II'' has been described as \"a classic Clive Palmer announcement.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomson|first=James|title=How Clive Palmer funds his amazing adventures|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/entrepreneurs/049525-rich-pickings-clive-palmer-s-incredible-adventures.html|publisher=Smartcompany|accessdate=17 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111025120/http://www.smartcompany.com.au/entrepreneurs/049525-rich-pickings-clive-palmer-s-incredible-adventures.html|archive-date=11 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of a commercialised replica of the ''Titanic'' has itself been criticised, being described as \"insensitive\" and \"a mockery of the memory of those who died\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gaynor|first=Hazel|title=Sinking feeling: unease about Titanic II plan|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/humaninterest/sinking-feeling-unease-about-titanic-ii-plan-228623.html|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=26 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424042618/http://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/humaninterest/sinking-feeling-unease-about-titanic-ii-plan-228623.html|archive-date=24 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Cunard Line]], which acquired the White Star Line legacy when the companies merged in 1934, stated that they \"have always been very mindful and very respectful of such a tragic event [and] don't think that building a replica or a 'II' is appropriate.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/05/28/57551-2/2 |title=Titanic II- Bigger replica of the iconic liner, to set sail in 2018 \u2026 |last=Patrick |first=Neil |publisher=Timera Media |date=May 28, 2016 |website=VingateNews.com |access-date=2 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103005141/https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/05/28/57551-2/2 |archive-date=3 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPalmer's alleged use of funds drawn from Queensland Nickel for the ''Titanic II'' project was criticised by the administrators appointed for that company after it closed. In their April 2016 report, the administrators stated that payments from Queensland Nickel to Blue Star Line had been \"uncommercial and director-related transactions\".<ref name=\"Koziol_Queensland_Nickel\" /> Palmer has rejected the claims made against him in the report, including those related to the ''Titanic II''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Remeikis|first1=Amy|last2=Danckert|first2=Sarah|title=Queensland Nickel report 'filled with innuendo': Clive Palmer|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-report-filled-with-innuendo-clive-palmer-20160413-go52fp.html|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=Brisbane Times|date=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420022559/http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-report-filled-with-innuendo-clive-palmer-20160413-go52fp.html|archive-date=20 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Project status==\nWhen the project was first announced in 2012, Palmer claimed that construction would begin before the end of the year, with a 2016 launch.  The following year reports emerged that Clive Palmer was experiencing financial difficulties.<ref name=Financial>{{cite web |last=Khadem |first=Nassim |title=Clive Palmer disputes \u2018beat-up\u2019 about Queensland Nickel\u2019s future |url=http://www.brw.com.au/p/business/clive_palmer_disputes_beat_up_about_gW1VXcpOLGMRwNOk7QhpTN |publisher=BRW |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001120657/http://www.brw.com.au/p/business/clive_palmer_disputes_beat_up_about_gW1VXcpOLGMRwNOk7QhpTN |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mccullough |first=James |title=Clive Palmer still Queensland's richest person |url=http://www.news.com.au/national-news/queensland/clive-palmer-still-queenslands-richest-person-according-to-brw-rich-200-list-gina-rineheart-australias-richest-person/story-fnii5v6w-1226648503100 |publisher=news.com.au |accessdate=30 May 2018 |date=22 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916023012/http://www.news.com.au/national-news/queensland/clive-palmer-still-queenslands-richest-person-according-to-brw-rich-200-list-gina-rineheart-australias-richest-person/story-fnii5v6w-1226648503100 |archive-date=16 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The start of construction was postponed to March 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Australian tycoon says Titanic project is about love |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/travel/article/australian-tycoon-says-titanic-project-is-about-love |publisher=The Malay Mail |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024142217/http://www.themalaymailonline.com/travel/article/australian-tycoon-says-titanic-project-is-about-love |archive-date=24 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> then to late 2014.<ref name=delta>{{cite web |title=Deltamarin designs Titanic II |url=https://www.deltamarin.com/2013/09/deltamarin-designs-titanic-ii/ |publisher=Deltamarin |accessdate=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024035423/https://www.deltamarin.com/2013/09/deltamarin-designs-titanic-ii/ |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> When construction had still not begun in 2015 a spokesman for Palmer said the project had merely been delayed, and that the new ship would be launched in 2018 - two years later than initially planned.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cruiseshipnews.co.uk/20150914/titanic-2-ticket-demand-renewed-following-latest-launch-news |title=Titanic 2 ticket demand renewed following latest launch news |publisher=CruiseNews, Dansway Communications LTD |access-date=30 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703112635/http://www.cruiseshipnews.co.uk/20150914/titanic-2-ticket-demand-renewed-following-latest-launch-news |archive-date=2017-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However Deltamarin had told an [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] journalist that work on the ''Titanic II'' project had been halted<ref name=\"ABC Palmer's empire feeling the pinch\">{{cite news|last1=McCutcheon|first1=Peter|title=Clive Palmer's empire feeling the pinch from falling iron ore prices|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-27/clive-palmer-empire-and-impact-of-falling-iron-ore-prices/6354104|accessdate=30 May 2018|work=ABC News|date=27 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327103815/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-27/clive-palmer-empire-and-impact-of-falling-iron-ore-prices/6354104|archive-date=27 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while workers at the Chinese shipyard identified as the likely site of construction were highly skeptical that the project would ever move beyond the proposal stage<ref name=\"Palmer\u2019s Titanic II plans all but scuttled\">{{cite web | url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2015/03/20/11/16/palmers-titanic-ii-plans-all-but-scuttled | title=Palmer\u2019s Titanic II plans all but scuttled | publisher=9News.com Finance | date=20 March 2015 | accessdate=30 May 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825181301/https://www.9news.com.au/national/2015/03/20/11/16/palmers-titanic-ii-plans-all-but-scuttled | archive-date=25 August 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the Blue Star Line trademark was \"abandoned.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Trademark Category > Chemical Products > TITANIC II BLUE STAR LINE|url=http://www.trademarkia.com/titanic-ii-blue-star-line-79142812.html|website=LegalForce Trademarks|publisher=Trademarkia, Inc.|accessdate=30 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180248/https://www.trademarkia.com/titanic-ii-blue-star-line-79142812.html|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Queensland Nickel went bankrupt and Palmer faced freezing of personal assets to recoup money owed the company's employees and creditors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Branco|first1=Brace|title=Queensland Nickel liquidators could freeze Clive Palmer's assets|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-liquidators-could-freeze-clive-palmers-assets-20160422-gocym3.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824100832/http://www.smh.com.au/business/mining-and-resources/queensland-nickel-liquidators-could-freeze-clive-palmers-assets-20160422-gocym3.html|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> When he declined to stand for re-election to his House of Representatives seat he stated that he might resume work on the project in his retirement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeans|first1=David|title=Is mining billionaire Clive Palmer's Titanic II dream under water? Finnish shipbuilder 'has stopped working on plans' to design a replica of the doomed ocean liner|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3578686/Is-mining-billionaire-Clive-Palmer-s-Titanic-II-dream-water-Finnish-shipbuilder-stopped-working-plans-design-replica-doomed-ocean-liner.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=The Daily Mail|date=May 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226050800/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3578686/Is-mining-billionaire-Clive-Palmer-s-Titanic-II-dream-water-Finnish-shipbuilder-stopped-working-plans-design-replica-doomed-ocean-liner.html|archive-date=26 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2018 the Blue Star Line, in a press release on their official web site, announced that work on the project would recommence.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Palmer Building Titanic II |url=https://www.bluestarline.com.au/palmer-building-titanic-ll/ |location= |publisher=Blue Star Line |agency= |date=September 27, 2018 |access-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030022000/https://www.bluestarline.com.au/palmer-building-titanic-ll/ |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2019 a European maritime equipment consortium published a list of all cruise ships on order through 2027 but none of the listed vessels fit Deltamarin's specifications for ''Titanic II''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amem.at/pdf/AMEM_Cruise-Ships-on-Order.pdf |title=AMEM Cruise Ships on Order 2016-2027 |publisher=Austrian Marine Equipment Manufacturers |access-date=24 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603135131/https://www.amem.at/pdf/AMEM_Cruise-Ships-on-Order.pdf |archive-date=3 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a reply to a reader query on their website in December 2019, Deltamarin responded that while design work was still ongoing any questions regarding the start of construction had to be referred to the ship owners.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deltamarin.com/2019/01/deltamarins-further-involvement-in-titanic-ii-project-confirmed/ |title=Deltamarin\u2019s further involvement in Titanic II project confirmed |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Romandisea ''Titanic''==\nPalmer's project should not be confused with a [[Romandisea Titanic|Chinese Romandisea ''Titanic'' replica ship]] which had its keel laying on November 29, 2016. Commissioned by Seven Star Energy Investment, it is to function as a part of Romandisea resort on the River Qi in [[Sichuan|Sichuan province]]. Unlike Palmer's ''Titanic II'', the all-Chinese replica is not intended to sail on any ocean but will be permanently docked within a reservoir.<ref>{{cite news\n |author       = Burford, Rachel\n |title        = Work begins on \u00a3116million life-size replica of the TITANIC in China which will allow visitors to relive the sinking which claimed 1,500 lives\n |url          = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3987472/Work-begins-116million-life-size-replica-TITANIC-China-allow-visitors-relive-sinking-claimed-1-500-lives.html\n |newspaper    = Daily Mail\n |location     = London, UK\n |date         = November 30, 2016\n |access-date  = 5 December 2016\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20161204144310/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3987472/Work-begins-116million-life-size-replica-TITANIC-China-allow-visitors-relive-sinking-claimed-1-500-lives.html\n |archive-date = 4 December 2016\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>  As of August 2019 construction had reached D deck, according to their official media site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/RomandiseaT2/status/1167253573672951808 |title=Assembly on D deck midship|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Transport}}\n*[[Replica Titanic|Replica ''Titanic'']]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bluestarline.com.au Blue Star Line Official Site]\n\n{{RMS Titanic}}\n\n[[Category:Ocean liners]]\n[[Category:Proposed ships]]\n[[Category:Replica ships]]\n[[Category:RMS Titanic]]\n[[Category:Ocean liners of Australia]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2012]]\n", "name_user": "FeanorStar7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProject status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Titanic_II"}
{"title_page": "Lebanese cuisine", "text_new": "{{short description|Culinary traditions of Lebanon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6517.jpg\n| image2 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6520.jpg\n| image3 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6518.jpg\n| image4 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6516.jpg\n| image5 = Taboul\u00e9.JPG\n| footer = '''''Top:''''' Typical Lebanese dining, with [[mezze]] and wine, taken at a restaurant in [[Beirut]], Lebanon, 1950. '''''Bottom:''''' The famous Lebanese salad [[tabbouleh]], usually eaten in a mezze and served with lettuce.\n| direction = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n| align = \n}}\n'''Lebanese cuisine''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a}}) is the culinary traditions and practices originating from [[Lebanon]]. It includes an abundance of [[whole grain]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[vegetable]]s, [[starches]], fresh [[Fish (food)|fish]] and [[seafood]]; animal fats are consumed sparingly. [[Poultry]] is eaten more often than [[red meat]], and when red meat is eaten, it is usually [[lamb and mutton|lamb]] on the coastal regions, and [[goat meat]] in the mountain regions. It also includes copious amounts of [[garlic]] and [[olive oil]], often seasoned by [[lemon juice]]. Chickpeas and parsley are also staples of the Lebanese diet.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheehan|first=Sean|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BrEG42oO2fgC&q=lebanese+chickpeas&dq=lebanese+chickpeas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi25K-9xsXoAhU7ThUIHffIAPgQ6AEIwgEwEg|title=Lebanon|date=September 1996|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-0283-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWell known savoury dishes include [[baba ghanouj]], a dip made of char-grilled [[eggplant]]; [[falafel]], small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]], fava beans, or a combination of the two; and [[shawarma]], a sandwich with marinated meat skewered and cooked on large rods. An important component of many Lebanese meals is [[hummus]], a dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], typically eaten with pita bread.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kayyali|first=Randa A.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2rc0RI7EqYC&pg=PA84&dq=lebanese+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC3vXtxsXoAhWtShUIHR8TDZsQ6AEIrwMwMQ#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20cuisine&f=false|title=The Arab Americans|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33219-7|language=en}}</ref> A well known dessert is [[baklava]], which is made of layered filo pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and steeped in date syrup or honey. Some desserts are specifically prepared on special occasions: the ''[[meghli]]'', for instance, is served to celebrate a newborn baby in the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gall|first=Timothy L.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZLhZAAAAYAAJ&q=meghli+lebanon&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio5J2yr8LoAhVzQUEAHaKJC9sQ6AEITjAE|title=Worldmark Encyclopedia of Cultures and Daily Life|last2=Hobby|first2=Jeneen|date=2009|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-1-4144-4892-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT155&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoury1x8XoAhUESRUIHTjRAHgQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meghli%20lebanon&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Arak (distilled beverage)|Arak]], an anise-flavored liqueur, is the Lebanese national drink and usually served with a traditional convivial Lebanese meal. Another historic and traditional drink is [[Lebanese wine]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zurayk|first=Rami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3lk-AQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+arak&dq=lebanese+arak&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip8d7Ex8XoAhU6UhUIHYpiAioQ6AEIVzAG|title=From \u02bbAkk\u0101r to \u02bbAmel: Lebanon's slow food trail : places, products and producers from Lebanon|last2=Rahman|first2=Sami Abdul|date=2008|publisher=Slow Food Beirut|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Blair|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b5ptAAAAMAAJ&q=lebanese+wine&dq=lebanese+wine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHlb3Vx8XoAhWCqHEKHVkMBQEQ6AEIlgEwDg|title=Lebanon: an insider's guide|date=2000|publisher=Prana Publishers|language=en}}</ref>\n== History ==\n[[File:LocationLebanon.svg|thumb|Lebanon in western [[Asia]] at the crossroads of the [[Mediterranean Basin]] and the [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabian]] hinterlands (in red)|alt=]]\nLebanese cuisine is an ancient one and part of the cuisine of the [[Levantine cuisine|Levant]]. Many dishes in Lebanese cuisine can be traced back thousands of years to eras of [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Ancient Egypt]]ian, [[Phoenicia under Babylonian rule|Babylonian]], [[Phoenicia under Assyrian rule|Assyrian]], [[Hittites|Hittite]] and [[Phoenicia]]n rule.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDnQwCJXUowC|title=Lebanon a country study|date=1989|language=en}}</ref> More recently, Lebanese cuisine was influenced by the different foreign civilizations that held power. From 1516 to 1918, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] controlled Lebanon and introduced a variety of foods that have become staples in the Lebanese diet, such as cooking with [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]. After the Ottomans were defeated in [[World War I]] (1914\u20131918), [[France]] took control of Lebanon until 1943, when the country achieved its independence. The [[France|French]] introduced foods such as [[Flan (pie)|flan]], a [[caramel custard]] dessert dating back to the 16th century AD, [[eclairs]], [[french fries]] and [[croissant]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YEcLaAEACAAJ|title=The Culinary Heritage of Lebanon|last=Choueiri|first=Ramzi N.|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Ramzi Choueiri|isbn=978-9953-0-0753-3|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Lebanese diaspora]] who live worldwide have introduced new foods, spices and culinary practices into Lebanese cuisine, keeping the cuisine innovative and renowned both beyond and within its borders.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hannam|first=Kevin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cHTDCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136|title=Event Mobilities: Politics, place and performance|last2=Mostafanezhad|first2=Mary|last3=Rickly|first3=Jillian|date=2016-03-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-45047-4|page=136}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n[[File:Byblos- Jbeil.jpg|alt=|thumb|A restaurant in the historic quarter and souks of [[Byblos]] (also called Jbeil)]]\nMost often foods are grilled, baked or saut\u00e9ed in olive oil; butter or cream is rarely used other than in a few desserts. Vegetables are often eaten raw, pickled, or cooked. Like most Mediterranean countries, much of what the Lebanese eat is dictated by the seasons and what is available. Lebanese cuisine also varies by region. South Lebanon is famous for its Kibbe, the [[Beqaa Valley]] for its meat pastries (such as [[sfiha]]), and north Lebanon and Saida ([[Sidon]]) for its sweets. \n\nIn [[Lebanon]], very rarely are drinks served without being accompanied by food. Similar to the [[tapas]] of [[Spain]], ''mezeluri'' of [[Romania]] and aperitivo of [[Italy]], ''[[mezze]]'' is an array of small dishes placed before the guests creating an array of colors, flavors, textures and aromas.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Walker|first=Harlan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GsNyprRS7EIC&pg=PA268|title=The Meal: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery, 2001|date=2002|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-1-903018-24-8|page=268}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish\">{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979|title=World and Its Peoples|date=September 2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|page=979}}</ref> This style of serving food is less a part of family life than it is of entertaining and caf\u00e9s. Mezze may be as simple as raw or [[pickled vegetables]], [[hummus]], [[baba ghanouj]] and bread, or it may become an entire meal consisting of grilled marinated [[seafood]], skewered meats, a variety of cooked and raw salads and an arrangement of desserts. The assortments of dishes forming the mezze are generally consumed in small bites using a piece of Lebanese bread ([[khubz]], [[pita]]) or a fork.<ref name=\"Cavendish\" /> As a family, it is made up of three or four dishes, but in the restaurant, the mezze can range from twenty to sixty dishes, as the variant combinations and dishes involved are plenty.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jousiffe|first=Ann|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q7IUAQAAIAAJ|title=Lebanon|date=1998|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-0-86442-350-4|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nA typical ''[[mezze]]'' will consist of an elaborate variety of thirty hot and cold dishes and may include: \n\n* Salads such as [[tabbouleh]] and [[fattoush]], together with dip such as [[hummus]], [[baba ghanoush]] or ''moutabal'', and [[kebbeh]],\n* Some patties such as the [[sambusac]],\n*[[Stuffed grape leaves]] and pickles,\n* Roasted nuts, olives and vegetables,\n* Condiments like [[toum]] and [[Tarator|taratour]], ideal for spread on [[sfiha]].<ref name=\"Cavendish\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rombauer|first=Irma S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcq2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|title=Joy of Cooking: 2019 Edition Fully Revised and Updated|last2=Becker|first2=Marion Rombauer|last3=Becker|first3=Ethan|last4=Becker|first4=John|last5=Scott|first5=Megan|date=2019-11-12|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-5011-6971-7|page=46}}</ref>\n\nFamily cuisine offers also a range of dishes, such as stews (or yakhneh), which can be cooked in many forms depending on the ingredients used and are usually served with [[meat]] and rice vermicelli. Although simple fresh fruits are often served towards the end of a Lebanese meal, there is also [[dessert]], such as [[baklava]] and [[coffee]]. Although baklava is the most internationally known dessert, there is a great variety of Lebanese desserts.<ref name=\"Hamadeh\">{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|page=211}}</ref><br /><gallery class=\"left\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed-overlay\" caption=\"''Examples of Lebanese cuisine:''\">\nFile:Palestinianbreakfastfalafel.jpg|[[Falafel]], with hummus, [[Pita]] and various vegetables\nFile:Byblos Harbour, Millwall, London (3639283205).jpg|From left to right: [[Hummus]], [[Ful medames]] (fava bean stew), [[Batata harra]] (spicy potatoes) and [[Moussaka]]\nFile:Mixed Plate (3186676853).jpg|[[Hummus]], [[Falafel]], [[Baba Ghanoush|Baba ghanoush]], [[Tabbouleh]], [[Shawarma]], [[Kafta]] and [[Kibbeh]]\nFile:Sheikhmahshe.JPG|Sheikh Mahshi served with rice\nFile:Labanese Garlic Chicken.JPG|Farrouj Meshwi - Lebanese Garlic Chicken\nFile:Mixedlebanesefood.JPG|Clockwise from bottom right: [[Kafta]] (grilled spiced ground meat), [[Balila (dish)|Balila]] (boiled chickpeas in lemon and garlic dressing), [[Tabbouleh]] and [[Mashawi]] (barbecued spiced meat)\nFile:Tabbouleh2.JPG|Lebanese [[Tabbouleh]] served with lettuce\nFile:Sayadiyah Fish.jpg|Sayadieh Samak (baked fish with rice)\nFile:Selection of Meza From Cafe Nouf Restaurant.JPG|Selection of Lebanese food from a restaurant in [[London]] \n</gallery>\n\n== List of dishes and ingredients ==\n=== Appetizers ===\n[[File:Fatethomos.JPG|thumb|Lebanese [[Fateh]] b'hummus]]\n[[File:Hummus&ful.jpg|thumb|[[Hummus]] (chickpea puree) and [[Ful medames]] (cooked fava beans)]]\n[[File:Fattoush mixed-salad.jpg|thumb|[[Fattoush]] salad made from toasted or fried pieces of [[khubz]] combined with [[Leaf vegetables|mixed greens]] and other [[Vegetable|vegetables]]]]\n[[File:Kousa Mahshi.jpg|thumb|[[Kousa Mahshi]] (stuffed [[zucchini]])]]\n[[File:Mujaddara.jpg|thumb|[[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') consists of cooked [[Lentil|lentils]] together with [[Groat (grain)|groats]], generally [[rice]], and saut\u00e9ed [[Onion|onions]]]]\n[[File:Zaatar Mankousheh.jpg|alt=|thumb|[[Za'atar]] [[Manakish|Manaeesh]] (Zaatar pizza)]]\n[[File:Sfiha2.jpg|thumb|[[Sfiha]], a pie-like dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]]]]\n\n*[[Ackawi cheese|Ackawi]] \u2013 white cheese salty or not depending on choice.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kehler|first=Mateo|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qRg1DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA474&dq=ackawi+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjo9-yxxs7oAhWgR0EAHTwCDSoQ6AEITzAF#v=onepage&q=ackawi%20lebanon&f=false|title=The Oxford Companion to Cheese|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-933088-1|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Halloumi cheese|Halloum]] \u2013 white cheese salty, can be grilled.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wood|first=B. J.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JyvUBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA264&dq=halloumi+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc7O2_xs7oAhWFUcAKHSEtDM0Q6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=halloumi%20lebanon&f=false|title=Microbiology of Fermented Foods|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4613-0309-1|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Baba ghanouj]] \u2013 char-grilled ''aubergine'' ([[eggplant]]), [[tahina]], [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]] puree\u2014served as a dip.\n*[[Batata harra]] \u2013 spicy cube potatoes fried.\n*[[Balila (dish)|Balila]] \u2013 known as [[cumin]] [[chickpeas]].\n*[[Roasting|Roasted]] [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] \u2013 a mix of more than 20 kinds and flavors of [[Seed|kernels]], mostly dry roasted.\n*[[Ejjeh]] - Lebanese fresh-herb omelet\n*[[Fattoush]] \u2013 'peasant' salad of toasted pita bread, [[cucumbers]], [[tomatoes]], [[chickweed]], and [[Mentha|mint]].\n*[[Falafel]] \u2013 small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]].\n*[[Fried cauliflower]] \u2013 served with tarator sauce.\n*[[Fried eggplant]]\n*[[Fatteh]] \u2013 [[chickpeas]], [[yogurt]], [[Ground meat|minced meat]], spices and grilled Lebanese pita cut in triangle.\n*[[Fateh b'hummus]] \u2013 chickpeas with pita and spiced yogurt\n*[[Hummus]] \u2013 dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], and typically eaten with pita bread.\n*[[Hummus ras aasfour]] \u2013 Hummus with meat on top, eaten with pita bread.\n*[[Jwenih]] \u2013 chicken wings cooked with coriander, garlic and lemon, served as mezze.\n*[[Ful medames|Fuul]] (''[[vicia faba]]'') slow cooked mash of brown [[beans]] and red [[lentils]] dressed with [[lemon]], [[olive oil]] and [[cumin]].\n*[[Kibbeh]] \u2013 the national dish, mainly stuffed, can be made in different forms including fried, uncooked, and cooked with [[yogurt]].\n*[[Makdous]] \u2013 stuffed eggplant in olive oil.\n*[[Makhlouta]] - mixed bean soup.\n*[[Mutabbel]] \u2013 made from eggplant.\n*[[Labneh]]- strained yogurt, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n*[[Labneh we toum]] \u2013 strained yogurt mixed with garlic, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kalla|first=Joudie|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PTByDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=Labneh+we+toum&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6odbcx87oAhUfQkEAHe3PCY8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Labneh%20we%20toum&f=false|title=Baladi: Palestine a celebration of food from land and sea|date=2018-10-18|publisher=Jacqui Small|isbn=978-1-911127-86-4|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Shanklish]] \u2013 aged cheese balls.\n*[[Tabbouleh]] \u2013 diced parsley salad with [[burghul]], [[tomato]] and [[Mentha|mint]].\n*[[Dolma|Wara' Enab]] (''dolma'') \u2013 stuffed grape leaves.\n\n=== Main Course ===\n\n====''<u>Vegetarian</u>''====\n\n* [[Kousa Mahshi]] \u2013 stuffed [[zucchini]], many varieties are used.\n* [[Manaeesh]] \u2013 mini pizzas that are made in any number of local bakeries or Furns (Furn Assalam, Ain El Hilwe, Saida), traditionally garnished with [[cheese]], [[Za'atar]], spicy diced tomatoes, [[kashk]] in its Lebanese version, or minced meat and onions. Some bakeries allow you to bring your own toppings and build your own or buy the ones they sell there. Breakfast, lunch and dinner.\n* [[Mfaraket Koussa]] \u2013 spicy zucchini.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&dq=Mfaraket+Koussa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUw-jnx87oAhUUfMAKHaGoBMwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Mfaraket%20Koussa&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Manakousheh zaatar]] \u2013 thyme pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Manakousheh jebneh]] \u2013 only cheese Lebanese pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') \u2013 cooked [[lentils]] together with [[wheat]] or [[rice]], garnished with onions that have been 'sauteed' (lightly cooked in vegetable oil).\n* [[Yakhnet Sabanikh]] \u2013 Spinach stew\n\n====''<u>Meat dishes</u>''====\n\n* [[Kibbeh nayyeh]] \u2013 raw kibbeh eaten like [[steak]] tartar.\n* [[Barout del batata]] \u2013 spicy lamb served with potatoes.\n* [[Chawarma lahmeh]] \u2013  grilled meat with parsley, onion and tarator (served as a sandwich or a plat).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Helou|first=Anissa|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z6dvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT240&dq=shawarma+lahmeh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwierIjwxs7oAhXWgVwKHbNcAFEQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=shawarma%20lahmeh&f=false|title=Feast: Food of the Islamic World|date=2018-10-04|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-5266-0556-6|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Chawarma djeij]] \u2013  grilled poultry with toum (garlic) and lettuce (served as a sandwich or a plat).\n* [[Chich Taouk]] \u2013 grilled chicken marinated with garlic lemon and various oriental spices (cinnamon, cumin...)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cullen|first=David|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YqzJCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA180&dq=Chich+Taouk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiugJCdx87oAhVCi1wKHeyVA4gQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=Chich%20Taouk&f=false|title=The Lebanese Collection|date=2015-05-09|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0-9559911-8-9|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Daoud Bacha]] \u2013 meatballs with tomato sauce.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Coory|first=Kasey|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jwwvCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT123&dq=Daoud+Bacha&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi66M2sx87oAhUYGsAKHV5kDiIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Daoud%20Bacha&f=false|title=Condemn Not My Children: The Consequences of Pious Evil|date=2015-07-10|publisher=Balboa Press|isbn=978-1-4525-2957-8|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Djaj Mechwi]] \u2013 grilled chicken on bbq marinated with a garlic lemon sauce.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stein|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uTCGiN1ZHaAC&q=Djaj+Mechwi&dq=Djaj+Mechwi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwJi5x87oAhXUoVwKHcehB0gQ6AEIKDAA|title=The Washington, Dc., Ethnic Restaurant Guide: Your Passport to Great Ethnic Dining|date=September 1993|publisher=Open Road Publishing|isbn=978-1-883323-01-1|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Sfiha|Lahm bil aj\u0129n]] \u2013 a pastry covered with [[Ground meat|minced meat]], [[onions]], and [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]].[[File:Arabic Shawarma.jpg|thumb|[[Shawarma]] plate served with pickles, olives, french fries and toum]][[File:Toum.jpg|thumb|[[Toum]], Lebanese garlic sauce traditionally crushed together using a wooden [[mortar and pestle]]|alt=]]\n* [[Kofta]] \u2013 fingers, stars or a flat cake of [[Ground meat|minced meat]] and [[spices]] that can be baked or charcoal-grilled on skewers.\n* [[Kubideh]] \u2013 served with ''[[pivaz]]'' (a mix of minced [[parsley]], [[onions]], ground [[cumin]] and [[sumac]]).\n* [[Mulukhiyah]] \u2013 a stew with mallow leaves, [[chicken]], [[beef]], and in the Lebanese fashion, topped with raw chopped onions, and [[vinegar]] over rice. It sometimes has toasted pita chips under the rice.\n* [[Lahm bi ajain]] (also called mankhoucheh lahmeh) \u2013 minced meat with tomatoes and onion, usually served with yogurt drink<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/9789004206106_eifo_sim_1339|title=BAYT LA\u1e24M|website=Encyclop\u00e9die de l\u2019Islam|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* [[Pastirma]] \u2013 cured, seasoned dried beef.\n* [[Qawarma]] \u2013 chopped lamb, salted and kept in the grease of the animal.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Davidson|first=Alan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RL6LAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA662&dq=Qawarma&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjius6WyM7oAhWDlFwKHZi0BQkQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=Qawarma&f=false|title=The Oxford Companion to Food|date=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967733-7|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Shish Barak]] \u2013 meat dumplings in yogurt sauce\n* [[Shish taouk]] \u2013 grilled chicken skewers that utilize only white meat, marinated in olive oil, lemon, parsley, and sumac.\n* [[Shawarma]] \u2013 marinated meat (either [[chicken]] or [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]) that is skewered on big rods and cooked slowly, then shaved and placed in a 10-inch pita roll with [[pickling|pickles]], [[tomatoes]], and other tangy condiments.\n* [[Sfiha]] \u2013 pizza-like dish topped with mutton mince, from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]].\n\n==== ''<u>Fish dishes</u>'' ====\n\n* [[Samkeh Harra]] \u2013 grilled [[fish]] that has been marinated with [[Chili pepper|chili]], [[citrus]], and [[cilantro]]\n* [[Siyyadiyeh]] (or Sayadiyeh) \u2013 delicately spiced fish served on a bed of rice. Fish cooked in [[saffron]] and served on rice with [[onions]], [[sumac]], and a [[tahini]] sauce (the most important part of the dish) originated in Saida.\n\n===Sweets===\n\n* [[Baklawa]] \u2013 a dessert of layered pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and steeped in Attar syrup ([[Orange (fruit)|orange]] or rose water and [[sugar]]), usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape that originates in Lebanon, it is a rich, sweet pastry made of layers of filo pastry filled with chopped nuts and sweetened with syrup or honey .\n* [[Halva]] \u2013 sesame paste sweet, usually made in a slab and studded with [[fruit]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s.\n* [[Kanafeh|Kunafi]] \u2013 either shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet [[white cheese]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}, [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and [[syrup]], or more commonly the version with semolina pastry served on a [[sesame seed]] bun with sweet sugar syrup (very popular for breakfast) made with \" angel hair\" butter and pistachios or nuts. Generally these can be found in sweet shops, as well as bigger bakeries.\n* [[Ladyfinger (biscuit)|Znood Es-sett]] \u2013 filo pastry cigars with various fillings.\n* [[Ma'amoul]] \u2013  cake made from semolina with [[date (fruit)|date]], [[pistachio]] or [[walnut]] filled cookies shaped in a wooden mould called a ''tabi'' made specially for Christian (traditionally Eastern) and Muslim holidays (such as [[Ramadan]]).\n\n===Condiments===\n\n* [[Tahini]] \u2013 sesame paste.\n*[[Tarator]] \u2013 cucumber, yogurt, and lemon dip.\n* [[Toum]] \u2013 garlic sauce.\n* [[Sumac]] \u2013 a tangy spice used in many salads.\n* [[Za'atar]] \u2013 dried [[thyme]] and sumac that can differ from region to region and from family to family. Most are made in house, but can be bought at Lebanese larders.\n* Lebanese Spice Blend \u2013 a mixture of equal parts of [[allspice]], [[black pepper]], [[cinnamon]], [[cloves]], [[fenugreek]], [[nutmeg]] and [[ginger]]. It is commonly used to flavor many Lebanese dishes.\n\n== Sweets ==\n[[File:Middle eastern sweets.jpg|alt=|thumb|Selection of Lebanese sweets sold by the [[Lebanese diaspora]] in Brazil|left]][[File:Noura - Lebanese sweets.jpg|thumb|[[Halawet el Jibn]] (sweet cheese), Karabij (pistachio-filled cookie), [[Qatayef]] (sweet pastry filled with cream or nuts) |alt=]][[File:Lebanon - Baklava - Karabij - Eclair (2318962553).jpg|alt=|thumb|Mix of Lebanese desserts including [[Baklava]], [[\u00c9clair]], Karabij and others]]The modern form of Lebanese desserts have been influenced by [[Ottoman cuisine]] and share many similarties with other Levantine countries, including [[muhallebi]], a milk [[pudding]] made with rice, milk and sugar. Like many other Lebanese desserts it is sweetened with ''[[atar]]'' syrup and served with a garnish of assorted nuts.<ref name=\"sweets\">{{cite book |last1=Roufs |first1=Timothy G. |last2=Roufs |first2=Kathleen Smyth |title=Sweet Treats Around the World |pages=179\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n''[[Barazeh]]'', also found in [[Syrian cuisine]], are cookies with a light and crumbly texture; one size is decorated with sesame seeds and the other [[pistachio]]. ''[[Ma'amoul]]'' are crumbly cookies filled with pistachio, walnuts or [[Dates (fruit)|dates]]. [[Lebanese Christians]] serve ''ma'amoul'' with ''atar'' syrup for Easter, as well as a cake flavored with [[anise]] and ''[[mahlab]]''.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\nPastry shops in Tripoli offer the common ''[[baklava]]'' along with other local specialty pastries like [[Halawet el Jibn]], filled with sweetened cheese and topped with ''atar'', pistachios, [[clotted cream]] (''ashta'') and [[rose jam]]. ''Znoud al-sit'', a syrup-soaked rolled pastry filled with clotted cream and garnished in typical fashion with nuts, orange peels and [[Dates (fruit)|dates]] to the 19th century.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\n[[Semolina]] is used in the preparation of several Lebanese desserts like the pistachio-filled cookie ''[[karabeej|karabij]]'' (or aleppo cookies), flavored with ''[[mahlab]]'' and cinnamon, and served with ''[[natef]]'', a topping similar to [[meringue]]. ''[[Mafroukeh]]'' is a semolina dough layered with caramel and butter, soaked in ''atar'' and served with clotted cream and assorted nuts. It can also be used to make cakes like ''[[basbousa|nammoura]]''.<ref name=sweets/>\n\nDesserts include pastries such as [[Aish as-Saraya]], [[Qatayef]], [[Basbousa]], [[Harees]], [[Kanafeh]], [[baklava]], [[Ka'ak]], [[Sfouf]] and [[Maamoul]]. Lebanese [[ice cream]] is popular with its oriental flavors, including [[Qamar al-Din|Amar al-Din]] made from dried apricots (can also be eaten as a snack); fresh fruits, and pistachio. Lebanese roasted [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] with a variety of different mixes and flavours can be eaten before, during and after meals.<ref name=\"Hamadeh\"/>\n\n== Wine ==\n{{See also|Lebanese wine|Phoenicians and wine}}Lebanon is among the oldest sites of wine production in the world.<ref>McGovern, Patrick E. 2003. Ancient wine: the search for the origins of viniculture. Princeton University Press</ref> The Phoenicians of its coastal strip were instrumental in spreading wine and viticulture throughout the Mediterranean in ancient times. Lebanons [[Beqaa Valley]] contains more than 30 vineyards, including the renowned [[Kefraya]], [[Ksara]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]] labels.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Estreicher|first=Stefan K.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hCzUiYsGNwkC&pg=PA15|title=Wine: From Neolithic Times to the 21st Century|date=2006|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-477-8|page=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyle|first=Paul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0pt5DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|title=Lebanon|date=2016|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-558-4|page=102}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+\n|-\n! Wine Name\n| '''Date of Production'''\n| '''Origin'''\n| '''Founder'''\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Faqra<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vinileb.com/wineries/chateau-fakra.html|title=vinileb.com Chateau Fakra :: Online Wine cellar :: Lebanese Wine Shopping|website=vinileb.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1985\n| Fakra\n| Carlos Guillermo Adem\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau H\u00e9ritage<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateauheritage.com/|title=Lebanese Wine Chateau Heritag