lab]], sweet drink\n*[[Lebanese wine]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Mate (beverage)|Mate]] in [[Shouf]] and [[Aley]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n\n== By region ==\nThese recipes are attributed to these regions in Lebanon, although you find them now as main dishes at most Lebanese homes across the country with local variations.\n\n*Ain-Zibdeh: Hareeseh (wheat and beef)\n*[[Ajaltoun]]: Maakroun bi Thineh (Pastry boiled to which is added lemon and Thineh)\n*[[Aley]]: Tabbouleh bi Dehn (cooked tabouleh with lentils with beef ghee)\n*[[Baalbek]]: Safiha Baalbakieh (meat-stuffed puff pastry)\n*Baino: Kebbe and Lahme bil-khal (meat mixed with crushed wheat and meat soaked in vinegar)\n*[[Baskinta]]: Makhlouta (meat, rice, and nuts)\n*[[Beirut]]: Samkeh Harra and Akhtabout (spicy fish and octopus), Roastuts\n*[[Beit Chabab]]: Riz bi-Djaj (chicken with rice)\n*[[Beit Mery]]: Kebbe Lakteen (pumpkin-flavoured meat)\n*[[Beiteddine]]: Kafta Bithine (spiced meat with sesame concentrate)\n*[[Broummana]]: Deleh Mehshi (stuffed rib cage of lamb)\n*[[Bsharri]]: Koussa bil-Laban (meat and rice-stuffed zucchini cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Dhour El Choueir]]: [[Shishbarak|Shish Barak]] (dough balls stuffed with ground beef and cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Douma, Lebanon|Douma]]: Laban Immo (cooked yoghurt and lamb with rice)\n*[[Ehden]]: Kebbe Zghartweih (oven-cooked meat and crushed wheat blend)\n*[[El-Koura|El Koura]]: Abu Shoushe (taro and lentils stew)\n* Ferzol: [[Freekeh|Freikeh]] (cooked wheat with meat)\n*[[Hammana]]: Fasoulya Hammanieh (kidney bean stew)\n* Hrajel: Zaatar baladi (Thym with sesame, salt and olive oil)\n* Ihmej: Ghameh (stuffed cow intestines)\n*[[Jbeil]]: Koussa and Wark Inab bil-Kastaletah (stuffed zucchini, grape vines and steak)\n* Kifar meshki: Kebbe bil-Kishk (meat mixed with wheat and yoghurt)\n*[[Marjayoun]]: Vine leaves with squash and grilled chicken\n*[[Nabatieh]]: [[Sfiha]] (open-faced [[meat pie]]s made with ground [[mutton]]\n*[[Al-Qalamoun|Qalamoun]]: Fresh Carrot juice with ice cream inside\n*[[Ras el-Matn|Ras El Matn]]: Fatet (yoghurt, fried bread and nuts)\n* Rashana: Mjadrat Fasoulya (lentils and kidney beans)\n*[[Rashaya|Rashaya Al Wadi]]: Kebbe Heeleh (meatballs)\n* Saghbeen and [[Machghara]]: Zinkoul bil-Laban (meat filled pastry and yoghurt)\n*[[Shouf]]: Fatet Batinjan (yoghurt, fried bread and aubergine) and [[mate (beverage)|mate]]\n*[[Sidon]]: Riz bil-Foul (Rice and fava beans)\n*[[Tripoli, Lebanon]]: Mjadrah and Fattoush (crushed lentils and salad)\n*[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]: Saiyadit al-Samak (rice and fish)\n*[[Zahl\u00e9]]: Kebbe Zahleweieh (meat and crushed wheat blend)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Lebanon|Food}}\n* [[Arab cuisine]]\n* [[Levantine cuisine]]\n* [[Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{sisterlinks|Lebanon}}\n\n{{Asian topic|| cuisine}}\n{{Middle East topic |title=[[Middle Eastern cuisine]] |prefix=Cuisine of}}\n{{Mediterranean cuisine}}\n{{Cuisine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanese Cuisine}}\n[[Category:Lebanese cuisine| ]]\n[[Category:Arab cuisine]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Culinary traditions of Lebanon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{multiple image\n| perrow = 2\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6517.jpg\n| image2 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6520.jpg\n| image3 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6518.jpg\n| image4 = Lunch met het gerecht Meze, Bestanddeelnr 255-6516.jpg\n| image5 = Taboul\u00e9.JPG\n| footer = '''''Top:''''' Typical Lebanese dining, with [[mezze]] and wine, taken at a restaurant in [[Beirut]], Lebanon, 1950. '''''Bottom:''''' The famous Lebanese salad [[tabbouleh]], usually eaten in a mezze and served with lettuce.\n| direction = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n| align = \n}}\n'''Lebanese cuisine''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a}}) is the culinary traditions and practices originating from [[Lebanon]]. It includes an abundance of [[whole grain]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[vegetable]]s, [[starches]], fresh [[Fish (food)|fish]] and [[seafood]]; animal fats are consumed sparingly. [[Poultry]] is eaten more often than [[red meat]], and when red meat is eaten, it is usually [[lamb and mutton|lamb]] on the coastal regions, and [[goat meat]] in the mountain regions. It also includes copious amounts of [[garlic]] and [[olive oil]], often seasoned by [[lemon juice]]. Chickpeas and parsley are also staples of the Lebanese diet.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheehan|first=Sean|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BrEG42oO2fgC&q=lebanese+chickpeas&dq=lebanese+chickpeas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi25K-9xsXoAhU7ThUIHffIAPgQ6AEIwgEwEg|title=Lebanon|date=September 1996|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-0283-1|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWell known savoury dishes include [[baba ghanouj]], a dip made of char-grilled [[eggplant]]; [[falafel]], small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]], fava beans, or a combination of the two; and [[shawarma]], a sandwich with marinated meat skewered and cooked on large rods. An important component of many Lebanese meals is [[hummus]], a dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], typically eaten with pita bread.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kayyali|first=Randa A.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2rc0RI7EqYC&pg=PA84&dq=lebanese+cuisine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC3vXtxsXoAhWtShUIHR8TDZsQ6AEIrwMwMQ#v=onepage&q=lebanese%20cuisine&f=false|title=The Arab Americans|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33219-7|language=en}}</ref> A well known dessert is [[baklava]], which is made of layered filo pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] and steeped in date syrup or honey. Some desserts are specifically prepared on special occasions: the ''[[meghli]]'', for instance, is served to celebrate a newborn baby in the family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gall|first=Timothy L.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZLhZAAAAYAAJ&q=meghli+lebanon&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio5J2yr8LoAhVzQUEAHaKJC9sQ6AEITjAE|title=Worldmark Encyclopedia of Cultures and Daily Life|last2=Hobby|first2=Jeneen|date=2009|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-1-4144-4892-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT155&dq=meghli+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoury1x8XoAhUESRUIHTjRAHgQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meghli%20lebanon&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Arak (distilled beverage)|Arak]], an anise-flavored liqueur, is the Lebanese national drink and usually served with a traditional convivial Lebanese meal. Another historic and traditional drink is [[Lebanese wine]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zurayk|first=Rami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3lk-AQAAIAAJ&q=lebanese+arak&dq=lebanese+arak&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip8d7Ex8XoAhU6UhUIHYpiAioQ6AEIVzAG|title=From \u02bbAkk\u0101r to \u02bbAmel: Lebanon's slow food trail : places, products and producers from Lebanon|last2=Rahman|first2=Sami Abdul|date=2008|publisher=Slow Food Beirut|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Blair|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b5ptAAAAMAAJ&q=lebanese+wine&dq=lebanese+wine&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHlb3Vx8XoAhWCqHEKHVkMBQEQ6AEIlgEwDg|title=Lebanon: an insider's guide|date=2000|publisher=Prana Publishers|language=en}}</ref>\n== History ==\n[[File:LocationLebanon.svg|thumb|Lebanon in western [[Asia]] at the crossroads of the [[Mediterranean Basin]] and the [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabian]] hinterlands (in red)|alt=]]\nLebanese cuisine is an ancient one and part of the cuisine of the [[Levantine cuisine|Levant]]. Many dishes in Lebanese cuisine can be traced back thousands of years to eras of [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Ancient Egypt]]ian, [[Phoenicia under Babylonian rule|Babylonian]], [[Phoenicia under Assyrian rule|Assyrian]], [[Hittites|Hittite]] and [[Phoenicia]]n rule.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDnQwCJXUowC|title=Lebanon a country study|date=1989|language=en}}</ref> More recently, Lebanese cuisine was influenced by the different foreign civilizations that held power. From 1516 to 1918, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] controlled Lebanon and introduced a variety of foods that have become staples in the Lebanese diet, such as cooking with [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]. After the Ottomans were defeated in [[World War I]] (1914\u20131918), [[France]] took control of Lebanon until 1943, when the country achieved its independence. The [[France|French]] introduced foods such as [[Flan (pie)|flan]], a [[caramel custard]] dessert dating back to the 16th century AD, [[eclairs]], [[french fries]] and [[croissant]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YEcLaAEACAAJ|title=The Culinary Heritage of Lebanon|last=Choueiri|first=Ramzi N.|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Ramzi Choueiri|isbn=978-9953-0-0753-3|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Lebanese diaspora]] who live worldwide have introduced new foods, spices and culinary practices into Lebanese cuisine, keeping the cuisine innovative and renowned both beyond and within its borders.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hannam|first=Kevin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cHTDCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA136|title=Event Mobilities: Politics, place and performance|last2=Mostafanezhad|first2=Mary|last3=Rickly|first3=Jillian|date=2016-03-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-45047-4|page=136}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\n[[File:Byblos- Jbeil.jpg|alt=|thumb|A resturant in the historic quarter and souks of [[Byblos]] (also called Jbeil)]]\nMost often foods are grilled, baked or saut\u00e9ed in olive oil; butter or cream is rarely used other than in a few desserts. Vegetables are often eaten raw, pickled, or cooked. Like most Mediterranean countries, much of what the Lebanese eat is dictated by the seasons and what is available. Lebanese cuisine also varies by region. South Lebanon is famous for its Kibbe, the [[Beqaa Valley]] for its meat pastries (such as [[sfiha]]), and north Lebanon and Saida ([[Sidon]]) for its sweets. \n\nIn [[Lebanon]], very rarely are drinks served without being accompanied by food. Similar to the [[tapas]] of [[Spain]], ''mezeluri'' of [[Romania]] and aperitivo of [[Italy]], ''[[mezze]]'' is an array of small dishes placed before the guests creating an array of colors, flavors, textures and aromas.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Walker|first=Harlan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GsNyprRS7EIC&pg=PA268|title=The Meal: Proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery, 2001|date=2002|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-1-903018-24-8|page=268}}</ref><ref name=\"Cavendish\">{{Cite book|last=Cavendish|first=Marshall|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA979|title=World and Its Peoples|date=September 2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7571-2|page=979}}</ref> This style of serving food is less a part of family life than it is of entertaining and caf\u00e9s. Mezze may be as simple as raw or [[pickled vegetables]], [[hummus]], [[baba ghanouj]] and bread, or it may become an entire meal consisting of grilled marinated [[seafood]], skewered meats, a variety of cooked and raw salads and an arrangement of desserts. The assortments of dishes forming the mezze are generally consumed in small bites using a piece of Lebanese bread ([[khubz]], [[pita]]) or a fork.<ref name=\"Cavendish\" /> As a family, it is made up of three or four dishes, but in the restaurant, the mezze can range from twenty to sixty dishes, as the variant combinations and dishes involved are plenty.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jousiffe|first=Ann|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q7IUAQAAIAAJ|title=Lebanon|date=1998|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-0-86442-350-4|language=en}}</ref>  \n\nA typical ''[[mezze]]'' will consist of an elaborate variety of thirty hot and cold dishes and may include: \n\n* Salads such as [[tabbouleh]] and [[fattoush]], together with dip such as [[hummus]], [[baba ghanoush]] or ''moutabal'', and [[kebbeh]],\n* Some patties such as the [[sambusac]],\n*[[Stuffed grape leaves]] and pickles,\n* Roasted nuts, olives and vegetables,\n* Condiments like [[toum]] and [[Tarator|taratour]], ideal for spread on [[sfiha]].<ref name=\"Cavendish\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rombauer|first=Irma S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcq2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|title=Joy of Cooking: 2019 Edition Fully Revised and Updated|last2=Becker|first2=Marion Rombauer|last3=Becker|first3=Ethan|last4=Becker|first4=John|last5=Scott|first5=Megan|date=2019-11-12|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-5011-6971-7|page=46}}</ref>\n\nFamily cuisine offers also a range of dishes, such as stews (or yakhneh), which can be cooked in many forms depending on the ingredients used and are usually served with [[meat]] and rice vermicelli. Although simple fresh fruits are often served towards the end of a Lebanese meal, there is also [[dessert]], such as [[baklava]] and [[coffee]]. Although baklava is the most internationally known dessert, there is a great variety of Lebanese desserts.<ref name=\"Hamadeh\">{{Cite book|last=Hamadeh|first=Mona|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R0qWBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA211|title=A Lebanese Feast of Vegetables, Pulses, Herbs and Spices|date=2015|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84528-580-7|page=211}}</ref><br /><gallery class=\"left\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed-overlay\" caption=\"''Examples of Lebanese cuisine:''\">\nFile:Palestinianbreakfastfalafel.jpg|[[Falafel]], with hummus, [[Pita]] and various vegetables\nFile:Byblos Harbour, Millwall, London (3639283205).jpg|From left to right: [[Hummus]], [[Ful medames]] (fava bean stew), [[Batata harra]] (spicy potatoes) and [[Moussaka]]\nFile:Mixed Plate (3186676853).jpg|[[Hummus]], [[Falafel]], [[Baba Ghanoush|Baba ghanoush]], [[Tabbouleh]], [[Shawarma]], [[Kafta]] and [[Kibbeh]]\nFile:Sheikhmahshe.JPG|Sheikh Mahshi served with rice\nFile:Labanese Garlic Chicken.JPG|Farrouj Meshwi - Lebanese Garlic Chicken\nFile:Mixedlebanesefood.JPG|Clockwise from bottom right: [[Kafta]] (grilled spiced ground meat), [[Balila (dish)|Balila]] (boiled chickpeas in lemon and garlic dressing), [[Tabbouleh]] and [[Mashawi]] (barbecued spiced meat)\nFile:Tabbouleh2.JPG|Lebanese [[Tabbouleh]] served with lettuce\nFile:Sayadiyah Fish.jpg|Sayadieh Samak (baked fish with rice)\nFile:Selection of Meza From Cafe Nouf Restaurant.JPG| Selection of Lebanese food from a resturant in [[London]]\n</gallery>\n\n== List of dishes and ingredients ==\n=== Appetizers ===\n[[File:Fatethomos.JPG|thumb|Lebanese [[Fateh]] b'hummus]]\n[[File:Hummus&ful.jpg|thumb|[[Hummus]] (chickpea puree) and [[Ful medames]] (cooked fava beans)]]\n[[File:Fattoush mixed-salad.jpg|thumb|[[Fattoush]] salad made from toasted or fried pieces of [[khubz]] combined with [[Leaf vegetables|mixed greens]] and other [[Vegetable|vegetables]]]]\n[[File:Kousa Mahshi.jpg|thumb|[[Kousa Mahshi]] (stuffed [[zucchini]])]]\n[[File:Mujaddara.jpg|thumb|[[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') consists of cooked [[Lentil|lentils]] together with [[Groat (grain)|groats]], generally [[rice]], and saut\u00e9ed [[Onion|onions]]]]\n[[File:Zaatar Mankousheh.jpg|alt=|thumb|[[Za'atar]] [[Manakish|Manaeesh]] (Zaatar pizza)]]\n[[File:Sfiha2.jpg|thumb|[[Sfiha]], a pie-like dish from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]]]]\n\n*[[Ackawi cheese|Ackawi]] \u2013 white cheese salty or not depending on choice.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kehler|first=Mateo|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qRg1DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA474&dq=ackawi+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjo9-yxxs7oAhWgR0EAHTwCDSoQ6AEITzAF#v=onepage&q=ackawi%20lebanon&f=false|title=The Oxford Companion to Cheese|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-933088-1|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Halloumi cheese|Halloum]] \u2013 white cheese salty, can be grilled.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wood|first=B. J.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JyvUBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA264&dq=halloumi+lebanon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjc7O2_xs7oAhWFUcAKHSEtDM0Q6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=halloumi%20lebanon&f=false|title=Microbiology of Fermented Foods|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4613-0309-1|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Baba ghanouj]] \u2013 char-grilled ''aubergine'' ([[eggplant]]), [[tahina]], [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]] puree\u2014served as a dip.\n*[[Batata harra]] \u2013 spicy cube potatoes fried.\n*[[Balila (dish)|Balila]] \u2013 known as [[cumin]] [[chickpeas]].\n*[[Roasting|Roasted]] [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] \u2013 a mix of more than 20 kinds and flavors of [[Seed|kernels]], mostly dry roasted.\n*[[Ejjeh]] - Lebanese fresh-herb omelet\n*[[Fattoush]] \u2013 'peasant' salad of toasted pita bread, [[cucumbers]], [[tomatoes]], [[chickweed]], and [[Mentha|mint]].\n*[[Falafel]] \u2013 small deep-fried patties made of highly spiced ground [[chickpeas]].\n*[[Fried cauliflower]] \u2013 served with tarator sauce.\n*[[Fried eggplant]]\n*[[Fatteh]] \u2013 [[chickpeas]], [[yogurt]], [[Ground meat|minced meat]], spices and grilled Lebanese pita cut in triangle.\n*[[Fateh b'hummus]] \u2013 chickpeas with pita and spiced yogurt\n*[[Hummus]] \u2013 dip or spread made of blended [[chickpeas]], sesame [[tahini]], [[lemon juice]], and [[garlic]], and typically eaten with pita bread.\n*[[Hummus ras aasfour]] \u2013 Hummus with meat on top, eaten with pita bread.\n*[[Jwenih]] \u2013 chicken wings cooked with coriander, garlic and lemon, served as mezze.\n*[[Ful medames|Fuul]] (''[[vicia faba]]'') slow cooked mash of brown [[beans]] and red [[lentils]] dressed with [[lemon]], [[olive oil]] and [[cumin]].\n*[[Kibbeh]] \u2013 the national dish, mainly stuffed, can be made in different forms including fried, uncooked, and cooked with [[yogurt]].\n*[[Makdous]] \u2013 stuffed eggplant in olive oil.\n*[[Makhlouta]] - mixed bean soup.\n*[[Mutabbel]] \u2013 made from eggplant.\n*[[Labneh]]- strained yogurt, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].\n*[[Labneh we toum]] \u2013 strained yogurt mixed with garlic, spreadable and garnished with good olive oil and [[sea salt]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kalla|first=Joudie|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PTByDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=Labneh+we+toum&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6odbcx87oAhUfQkEAHe3PCY8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Labneh%20we%20toum&f=false|title=Baladi: Palestine a celebration of food from land and sea|date=2018-10-18|publisher=Jacqui Small|isbn=978-1-911127-86-4|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Shanklish]] \u2013 aged cheese balls.\n*[[Tabbouleh]] \u2013 diced parsley salad with [[burghul]], [[tomato]] and [[Mentha|mint]].\n*[[Dolma|Wara' Enab]] (''dolma'') \u2013 stuffed grape leaves.\n\n=== Main Course ===\n\n====''<u>Vegetarian</u>''====\n\n* [[Kousa Mahshi]] \u2013 stuffed [[zucchini]], many varieties are used.\n* [[Manaeesh]] \u2013 mini pizzas that are made in any number of local bakeries or Furns (Furn Assalam, Ain El Hilwe, Saida), traditionally garnished with [[cheese]], [[Za'atar]], spicy diced tomatoes, [[kashk]] in its Lebanese version, or minced meat and onions. Some bakeries allow you to bring your own toppings and build your own or buy the ones they sell there. Breakfast, lunch and dinner.\n* [[Mfaraket Koussa]] \u2013 spicy zucchini.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mouzawak|first=Kamal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2P76CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&dq=Mfaraket+Koussa&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUw-jnx87oAhUUfMAKHaGoBMwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Mfaraket%20Koussa&f=false|title=Lebanese Home Cooking: Simple, Delicious, Mostly Vegetarian Recipes from the Founder of Beirut's Souk El Tayeb Market|date=2015-09-15|publisher=Quarry Books|isbn=978-1-63159-037-5|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Manakousheh zaatar]] \u2013 thyme pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Manakousheh jebneh]] \u2013 only cheese Lebanese pizza usually served for breakfast.\n* [[Mujaddara]] (''imjaddarra'') \u2013 cooked [[lentils]] together with [[wheat]] or [[rice]], garnished with onions that have been 'sauteed' (lightly cooked in vegetable oil).\n* [[Yakhnet Sabanikh]] \u2013 Spinach stew\n\n====''<u>Meat dishes</u>''====\n\n* [[Kibbeh nayyeh]] \u2013 raw kibbeh eaten like [[steak]] tartar.\n* [[Barout del batata]] \u2013 spicy lamb served with potatoes.\n* [[Chawarma lahmeh]] \u2013  grilled meat with parsley, onion and tarator (served as a sandwich or a plat).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Helou|first=Anissa|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z6dvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT240&dq=shawarma+lahmeh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwierIjwxs7oAhXWgVwKHbNcAFEQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=shawarma%20lahmeh&f=false|title=Feast: Food of the Islamic World|date=2018-10-04|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-5266-0556-6|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Chawarma djeij]] \u2013  grilled poultry with toum (garlic) and lettuce (served as a sandwich or a plat).\n* [[Chich Taouk]] \u2013 grilled chicken marinated with garlic lemon and various oriental spices (cinnamon, cumin...)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cullen|first=David|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YqzJCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA180&dq=Chich+Taouk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiugJCdx87oAhVCi1wKHeyVA4gQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=Chich%20Taouk&f=false|title=The Lebanese Collection|date=2015-05-09|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0-9559911-8-9|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Daoud Bacha]] \u2013 meatballs with tomato sauce.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Coory|first=Kasey|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jwwvCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT123&dq=Daoud+Bacha&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi66M2sx87oAhUYGsAKHV5kDiIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Daoud%20Bacha&f=false|title=Condemn Not My Children: The Consequences of Pious Evil|date=2015-07-10|publisher=Balboa Press|isbn=978-1-4525-2957-8|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Djaj Mechwi]] \u2013 grilled chicken on bbq marinated with a garlic lemon sauce.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Stein|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uTCGiN1ZHaAC&q=Djaj+Mechwi&dq=Djaj+Mechwi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFwJi5x87oAhXUoVwKHcehB0gQ6AEIKDAA|title=The Washington, Dc., Ethnic Restaurant Guide: Your Passport to Great Ethnic Dining|date=September 1993|publisher=Open Road Publishing|isbn=978-1-883323-01-1|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Sfiha|Lahm bil aj\u0129n]] \u2013 a pastry covered with [[Ground meat|minced meat]], [[onions]], and [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]].[[File:Arabic Shawarma.jpg|thumb|[[Shawarma]] plate served with pickles, olives, french fries and toum]][[File:Toum.jpg|thumb|[[Toum]], Lebanese garlic sauce traditionally crushed together using a wooden [[mortar and pestle]]|alt=]]\n* [[Kofta]] \u2013 fingers, stars or a flat cake of [[Ground meat|minced meat]] and [[spices]] that can be baked or charcoal-grilled on skewers.\n* [[Kubideh]] \u2013 served with ''[[pivaz]]'' (a mix of minced [[parsley]], [[onions]], ground [[cumin]] and [[sumac]]).\n* [[Mulukhiyah]] \u2013 a stew with mallow leaves, [[chicken]], [[beef]], and in the Lebanese fashion, topped with raw chopped onions, and [[vinegar]] over rice. It sometimes has toasted pita chips under the rice.\n* [[Lahm bi ajain]] (also called mankhoucheh lahmeh) \u2013 minced meat with tomatoes and onion, usually served with yogurt drink<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/9789004206106_eifo_sim_1339|title=BAYT LA\u1e24M|website=Encyclop\u00e9die de l\u2019Islam|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n* [[Pastirma]] \u2013 cured, seasoned dried beef.\n* [[Qawarma]] \u2013 chopped lamb, salted and kept in the grease of the animal.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Davidson|first=Alan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RL6LAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA662&dq=Qawarma&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjius6WyM7oAhWDlFwKHZi0BQkQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=Qawarma&f=false|title=The Oxford Companion to Food|date=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967733-7|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Shish Barak]] \u2013 meat dumplings in yogurt sauce\n* [[Shish taouk]] \u2013 grilled chicken skewers that utilize only white meat, marinated in olive oil, lemon, parsley, and sumac.\n* [[Shawarma]] \u2013 marinated meat (either [[chicken]] or [[lamb and mutton|lamb]]) that is skewered on big rods and cooked slowly, then shaved and placed in a 10-inch pita roll with [[pickling|pickles]], [[tomatoes]], and other tangy condiments.\n* [[Sfiha]] \u2013 pizza-like dish topped with mutton mince, from the Lebanese town of [[Baalbek]].\n\n==== ''<u>Fish dishes</u>'' ====\n\n* [[Samkeh Harra]] \u2013 grilled [[fish]] that has been marinated with [[Chili pepper|chili]], [[citrus]], and [[cilantro]]\n* [[Siyyadiyeh]] (or Sayadiyeh) \u2013 delicately spiced fish served on a bed of rice. Fish cooked in [[saffron]] and served on rice with [[onions]], [[sumac]], and a [[tahini]] sauce (the most important part of the dish) originated in Saida.\n\n===Sweets===\n\n* [[Baklawa]] \u2013 a dessert of layered pastry filled with [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and steeped in Attar syrup ([[Orange (fruit)|orange]] or rose water and [[sugar]]), usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape that originates in Lebanon, it is a rich, sweet pastry made of layers of filo pastry filled with chopped nuts and sweetened with syrup or honey .\n* [[Halva]] \u2013 sesame paste sweet, usually made in a slab and studded with [[fruit]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s.\n* [[Kanafeh|Kunafi]] \u2013 either shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet [[white cheese]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}, [[nut (fruit)|nut]]s and [[syrup]], or more commonly the version with semolina pastry served on a [[sesame seed]] bun with sweet sugar syrup (very popular for breakfast) made with \" angel hair\" butter and pistachios or nuts. Generally these can be found in sweet shops, as well as bigger bakeries.\n* [[Ladyfinger (biscuit)|Znood Es-sett]] \u2013 filo pastry cigars with various fillings.\n* [[Ma'amoul]] \u2013  cake made from semolina with [[date (fruit)|date]], [[pistachio]] or [[walnut]] filled cookies shaped in a wooden mould called a ''tabi'' made specially for Christian (traditionally Eastern) and Muslim holidays (such as [[Ramadan]]).\n\n===Condiments===\n\n* [[Tahini]] \u2013 sesame paste.\n*[[Tarator]] \u2013 cucumber, yogurt, and lemon dip.\n* [[Toum]] \u2013 garlic sauce.\n* [[Sumac]] \u2013 a tangy spice used in many salads.\n* [[Za'atar]] \u2013 dried [[thyme]] and sumac that can differ from region to region and from family to family. Most are made in house, but can be bought at Lebanese larders.\n* Lebanese Spice Blend \u2013 a mixture of equal parts of [[allspice]], [[black pepper]], [[cinnamon]], [[cloves]], [[fenugreek]], [[nutmeg]] and [[ginger]]. It is commonly used to flavor many Lebanese dishes.\n\n== Sweets ==\n[[File:Middle eastern sweets.jpg|alt=|thumb|Selection of Lebanese sweets sold by the [[Lebanese diaspora]] in Brazil|left]][[File:Noura - Lebanese sweets.jpg|thumb|[[Halawet el Jibn]] (sweet cheese), Karabij (pistachio-filled cookie), [[Qatayef]] (sweet pastry filled with cream or nuts) |alt=]][[File:Lebanon - Baklava - Karabij - Eclair (2318962553).jpg|alt=|thumb|Mix of Lebanese desserts including [[Baklava]], [[\u00c9clair]], Karabij and others]]The modern form of Lebanese desserts have been influenced by [[Ottoman cuisine]] and share many similarties with other Levantine countries, including [[muhallebi]], a milk [[pudding]] made with rice, milk and sugar. Like many other Lebanese desserts it is sweetened with ''[[atar]]'' syrup and served with a garnish of assorted nuts.<ref name=\"sweets\">{{cite book |last1=Roufs |first1=Timothy G. |last2=Roufs |first2=Kathleen Smyth |title=Sweet Treats Around the World |pages=179\u2013183}}</ref>\n\n''[[Barazeh]]'', also found in [[Syrian cuisine]], are cookies with a light and crumbly texture; one size is decorated with sesame seeds and the other [[pistachio]]. ''[[Ma'amoul]]'' are crumbly cookies filled with pistachio, walnuts or [[Dates (fruit)|dates]]. [[Lebanese Christians]] serve ''ma'amoul'' with ''atar'' syrup for Easter, as well as a cake flavored with [[anise]] and ''[[mahlab]]''.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\nPastry shops in Tripoli offer the common ''[[baklava]]'' along with other local specialty pastries like [[Halawet el Jibn]], filled with sweetened cheese and topped with ''atar'', pistachios, [[clotted cream]] (''ashta'') and [[rose jam]]. ''Znoud al-sit'', a syrup-soaked rolled pastry filled with clotted cream and garnished in typical fashion with nuts, orange peels and [[Dates (fruit)|dates]] to the 19th century.<ref name=\"sweets\" />\n\n[[Semolina]] is used in the preparation of several Lebanese desserts like the pistachio-filled cookie ''[[karabeej|karabij]]'' (or aleppo cookies), flavored with ''[[mahlab]]'' and cinnamon, and served with ''[[natef]]'', a topping similar to [[meringue]]. ''[[Mafroukeh]]'' is a semolina dough layered with caramel and butter, soaked in ''atar'' and served with clotted cream and assorted nuts. It can also be used to make cakes like ''[[basbousa|nammoura]]''.<ref name=sweets/>\n\nDesserts include pastries such as [[Aish as-Saraya]], [[Qatayef]], [[Basbousa]], [[Harees]], [[Kanafeh]], [[baklava]], [[Ka'ak]], [[Sfouf]] and [[Maamoul]]. Lebanese [[ice cream]] is popular with its oriental flavors, including [[Qamar al-Din|Amar al-Din]] made from dried apricots (can also be eaten as a snack); fresh fruits, and pistachio. Lebanese roasted [[Nut (fruit)|nuts]] with a variety of different mixes and flavours can be eaten before, during and after meals.<ref name=\"Hamadeh\"/>\n\n== Wine ==\n{{See also|Lebanese wine|Phoenicians and wine}}Lebanon is among the oldest sites of wine production in the world.<ref>McGovern, Patrick E. 2003. Ancient wine: the search for the origins of viniculture. Princeton University Press</ref> The Phoenicians of its coastal strip were instrumental in spreading wine and viticulture throughout the Mediterranean in ancient times. Lebanons [[Beqaa Valley]] contains more than 30 vineyards, including the renowned [[Kefraya]], [[Ksara]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]] labels.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Estreicher|first=Stefan K.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hCzUiYsGNwkC&pg=PA15|title=Wine: From Neolithic Times to the 21st Century|date=2006|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-477-8|page=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyle|first=Paul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0pt5DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|title=Lebanon|date=2016|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-84162-558-4|page=102}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+\n|-\n! Wine Name\n| '''Date of Production'''\n| '''Origin'''\n| '''Founder'''\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Faqra<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vinileb.com/wineries/chateau-fakra.html|title=vinileb.com Chateau Fakra :: Online Wine cellar :: Lebanese Wine Shopping|website=vinileb.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1985\n| Fakra\n| Carlos Guillermo Adem\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau H\u00e9ritage<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateauheritage.com/|title=Lebanese Wine Chateau Heritage Lebanon Wine|website=chateauheritage.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1888\n| [[Qabb Ilyas]]\n| Touma Family (la Famille Touma)\n|-\n\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Kefraya]]\n| 1951\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Khoury<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaukhoury.com/|title=Welcome to our online shop|website=chateaukhoury.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n![[Ch\u00e2teau Marsyas]]\n| 2007\n| Beqaa Valley\n| Johnny R.Saad\u00e9 family\n|-\n! [[Ch\u00e2teau Musar]]\n| 1930\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Gaston Hochar\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Nakad in Jdita<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chateaunakad.com/|title=Chateau Nakad|website=chateaunakad.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chateauqanafar.com/|title=Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar|website=Ch\u00e2teau Qanafar|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 2010\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Naim family\n|-\n! Couvent St. Sauveur\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! [http://www.domainedestourelles.com/ Domaine des Tourelles]\n|1868\n| [[Beqaa Valley]], Chtaura\n| Fran\u00e7ois-Eug\u00e8ne Brun\n|-\n! Ch\u00e2teau St Thomas<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://closstthomas.com/|title=Ch\u00e2teau St.Thomas|website=closstthomas.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Cave du monast\u00e8re st. Jean<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beirut.com/l/26884|title=Cave Du Monastere St Jean |website=Beirut.com City Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| 1720 (Renovated 2006)\n| [[Khenchara]]\n| \n|-\n! RIACHI [http://www.riachi.me/]\n| 1839\n| [[Khenchara]]\n| Moussa Riachi \n|-\n! Cave Kouroum<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cavekouroum.com/|title=Cave Kouroum red wine white wine rose wine olive oil vinegar arak bekaa lebanon|website=www.cavekouroum.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Clos de Cana<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chateaucana.com/|title=Welcome to Ch\u00e2teau Cana|website=Welcome to Ch\u00e2teau Cana|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Domaine de Baal<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domainedebaal.com/|title=Domaine de Baal \u2013 A fine organic and natural Lebanese wine|website=Domaine de Baal \u2013 A fine organic and natural Lebanese wine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n|1995\n|Zahle \u2013 Bekaa Valley\n| Sebastien Khoury\n|-\n! Domaine Wardy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.domainewardy.com/|title=Domaine Wardy|last=Wardy|first=Domaine|website=Domaine Wardy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! [[IXSIR wine|IXSIR]]\n| 2008\n| [[Batroun]]\n| Hady Kahale, Etienne Debbane, [[Carlos Ghosn]]\n|-\n![[Ch\u00e2teau Ksara]]\n| 1857\n| [[Beqaa Valley]]\n| Zafer Chaoui\n|-\n![[Massaya]]\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Nabise Mont Liban<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pictet|first=Fran\u00e7ois Jules|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.8425|title=Description de quelques poissons fossiles du Mont Liban / par F.-J. Pictet.|date=1850|publisher=impr. de Jules-Guillaume Fick,|location=G\u00e9n\u00e8ve :}}</ref>\n| N/A\n| N/A\n| \n|-\n! Terre Joie [http://www.terrejoie.com/]\n|    2011\n|    [[West Beqaa]]\n|    [[Joe Saade]]\n|}\n\n== Beverages ==\n\n*[[Arabic coffee]]\n*[[Almaza Beer|Beer]], alcoholic beverage{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| total_width = 575\n| image_style = border:none;\n| image1 = Arak Touma, Lebanon.jpg\n| alt1 = Arak with water and ice\n| caption1 = Bottle of [[Arak (drink)|Arak]] Touma\n| image2 = Jallab.jpg\n| alt2 = Jallab\n| caption2 = [[Jallab]], made from [[carob]], [[Date palm|dates]], grape [[molasses]] and [[rose water]]\n| image3 = Coffee Syria 2.jpg\n| alt3 = Black Coffee\n| caption3 = Lebanese style black coffee\n| image4 = Ayran - Ankara.jpg\n| alt4 = Ayran \n| caption4 = Ayran (yogurt drink)\n| direction = \n}}\n*[[Arak (liqueur)|Arak]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Ayran]], yogurt\n*[[Coffee|Black coffee]]\n*[[Ceratonia siliqua|Le caroubier]], non-alcoholic beverage made from carob\n*[[Jallab]], sweet drink\n*[[Lebanese wine]], alcoholic beverage\n*[[Mate (beverage)|Mate]] in [[Shouf]] and [[Aley]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n\n== By region ==\nThese recipes are attributed to these regions in Lebanon, although you find them now as main dishes at most Lebanese homes across the country with local variations.\n\n*Ain-Zibdeh: Hareeseh (wheat and beef)\n*[[Ajaltoun]]: Maakroun bi Thineh (Pastry boiled to which is added lemon and Thineh)\n*[[Aley]]: Tabbouleh bi Dehn (cooked tabouleh with lentils with beef ghee)\n*[[Baalbek]]: Safiha Baalbakieh (meat-stuffed puff pastry)\n*Baino: Kebbe and Lahme bil-khal (meat mixed with crushed wheat and meat soaked in vinegar)\n*[[Baskinta]]: Makhlouta (meat, rice, and nuts)\n*[[Beirut]]: Samkeh Harra and Akhtabout (spicy fish and octopus), Roastuts\n*[[Beit Chabab]]: Riz bi-Djaj (chicken with rice)\n*[[Beit Mery]]: Kebbe Lakteen (pumpkin-flavoured meat)\n*[[Beiteddine]]: Kafta Bithine (spiced meat with sesame concentrate)\n*[[Broummana]]: Deleh Mehshi (stuffed rib cage of lamb)\n*[[Bsharri]]: Koussa bil-Laban (meat and rice-stuffed zucchini cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Dhour El Choueir]]: [[Shishbarak|Shish Barak]] (dough balls stuffed with ground beef and cooked in yoghurt)\n*[[Douma, Lebanon|Douma]]: Laban Immo (cooked yoghurt and lamb with rice)\n*[[Ehden]]: Kebbe Zghartweih (oven-cooked meat and crushed wheat blend)\n*[[El-Koura|El Koura]]: Abu Shoushe (taro and lentils stew)\n* Ferzol: [[Freekeh|Freikeh]] (cooked wheat with meat)\n*[[Hammana]]: Fasoulya Hammanieh (kidney bean stew)\n* Hrajel: Zaatar baladi (Thym with sesame, salt and olive oil)\n* Ihmej: Ghameh (stuffed cow intestines)\n*[[Jbeil]]: Koussa and Wark Inab bil-Kastaletah (stuffed zucchini, grape vines and steak)\n* Kifar meshki: Kebbe bil-Kishk (meat mixed with wheat and yoghurt)\n*[[Marjayoun]]: Vine leaves with squash and grilled chicken\n*[[Nabatieh]]: [[Sfiha]] (open-faced [[meat pie]]s made with ground [[mutton]]\n*[[Al-Qalamoun|Qalamoun]]: Fresh Carrot juice with ice cream inside\n*[[Ras el-Matn|Ras El Matn]]: Fatet (yoghurt, fried bread and nuts)\n* Rashana: Mjadrat Fasoulya (lentils and kidney beans)\n*[[Rashaya|Rashaya Al Wadi]]: Kebbe Heeleh (meatballs)\n* Saghbeen and [[Machghara]]: Zinkoul bil-Laban (meat filled pastry and yoghurt)\n*[[Shouf]]: Fatet Batinjan (yoghurt, fried bread and aubergine) and [[mate (beverage)|mate]]\n*[[Sidon]]: Riz bil-Foul (Rice and fava beans)\n*[[Tripoli, Lebanon]]: Mjadrah and Fattoush (crushed lentils and salad)\n*[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]: Saiyadit al-Samak (rice and fish)\n*[[Zahl\u00e9]]: Kebbe Zahleweieh (meat and crushed wheat blend)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Lebanon|Food}}\n* [[Arab cuisine]]\n* [[Levantine cuisine]]\n* [[Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{sisterlinks|Lebanon}}\n\n{{Asian topic|| cuisine}}\n{{Middle East topic |title=[[Middle Eastern cuisine]] |prefix=Cuisine of}}\n{{Mediterranean cuisine}}\n{{Cuisine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanese Cuisine}}\n[[Category:Lebanese cuisine| ]]\n[[Category:Arab cuisine]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "JJNito197", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebanese_cuisine"}
{"title_page": "Sony Pictures Studios", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Sony Pictures Studios\n| native_name. = \n| former_names = {{plainlist|\n* Inceville Studios (1912-1915)\n* Triangle Studios (1915-1919)\n* Goldwyn Studios (1919-1924)\n* Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer  Studios (1924-1986) \n* Lorimar Telepictures Studios (1986-1989)\n* Lorimar Studios (1989-1990)\n* Columbia Studios (1990-1991)\n}}\n| alternate_names = \n| image = Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg\n| caption = Overland Gate / West entrance&nbsp;\u2013 the entrance to Sony Pictures Studios\n| location = [[Culver City, California]], [[United States]]\n| address = 10202 West Washington Boulevard\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.017222|-118.401667|display=inline}}\n| start_date = \n| completion_date = \n| inauguration_date = 1912 as Inceville\n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = \n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]([[Sony]])\n| cost = \n| floor_area = \n| floor_count = \n| awards = \n| ren_awards = \n| references = \n| map_type = United States Los Angeles Western\n| map_caption = Location within Western Los Angeles\n| altitude = \n| building_type = Film and television studios\n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| ren_cost = \n| client = \n| current_tenants = [[Columbia Pictures]]<br />[[TriStar Pictures]]<br />[[Screen Gems]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Animation]]<br />[[Destination Films]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Imageworks]]<br />[[Stage 6 Films]]<br />[[Affirm Films]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Television]]<br />[[TriStar Television]]<br />[[Ghost Corps]]<br />[[Happy Madison Productions]]\n\n| renovation_date = \n| height = \n| other_dimensions = \n| architecture_firm = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer = \n| civil_engineer = \n| other_designers = \n| quantity_surveyor = \n| main_contractor = \n| ren_architect = \n| ren_firm = \n| ren_str_engineer = \n| ren_serv_engineer = \n| ren_civ_engineer = \n| ren_oth_designers = \n| ren_qty_surveyor = \n| diameter = \n}}\nThe '''Sony Pictures Studios''' is an American television and film studio complex located in [[Culver City, California]] at 10202 West Washington Boulevard and bounded by Culver Boulevard (south), Washington Boulevard (north), Overland Avenue (west) and Madison Avenue (east). Founded in 1912, the facility is currently owned by [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] and houses the division's film studios, such as [[Columbia Pictures]], [[TriStar Pictures]], and [[Screen Gems]]. The complex was the original studios of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] from 1924 to 1986 and [[Lorimar-Telepictures]] from 1986 to 1989.\n\nIn addition to films shot at the facility, several television shows have been broadcast live or taped there. The lot, which is open to the public for daily studio tours, currently houses a total of sixteen separate [[sound stage]]s.\n\n== Early history (1912-1924)==\n[[Image:Triangle studios c.1916.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Photograph of original colonnade of [[Triangle Film Corporation|Triangle Studios]]. c. 1916]]\nDirector [[Thomas H. Ince]] built his pioneering '''Inceville''' studios in [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]] in 1912. While Ince was filming at [[Ballona Creek]] in 1915, [[Harry Culver]], the founding father of Culver City, persuaded Ince to move Inceville  to Culver City. During that time, Ince co-founded [[Triangle Film Corporation]] and the Triangle Studios was opened in the form of a Greek [[colonnade]]&nbsp;\u2013 the entrance to the studios. The colonnade still stands fronting Washington Boulevard and is a Culver City historical landmark.\n\nInce added a few stages and an Administration Building before selling out to his partners [[D.W. Griffith]] and [[Mack Sennett]]. Ince relocated down the street and built the [[Culver Studios]] at that location. In 1918, Triangle Studios was sold to film producer [[Samuel Goldwyn]]. Goldwyn also added a few sound stages before selling his shares in Goldwyn Studios.\n\n== The Historic MGM Studios/Lorimar-Telepictures Studios/Lorimar Studios (1924-1990)==\n[[Image:MGM-studios-1922.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Aerial shot of Goldwyn Studios c. 1922]]\n{{main|Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer}}\nIn 1924, [[Loews Theatres]] President [[Marcus Loew]] organized the [[merger]] of three film companies&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Metro Pictures Corporation]], [[Goldwyn Pictures]] and [[Louis B. Mayer Productions]] to form [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and occupying the Goldwyn production facilities. {{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]], MGM Studios was responsible for shooting 52 films a year, from screen [[Epic film|epics]] such as ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'', and ''[[Mutiny on the Bounty (1962 film)|Mutiny on the Bounty]]'', to drawing-room dramas such as ''[[Grand Hotel (1932 film)|Grand Hotel]]'', ''[[Dinner at Eight (1933 film)|Dinner At Eight]]'', and ''[[Anna Karenina]]''. But it was the [[Technicolor]] [[musical film|musicals]], including ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain]]'' and ''[[Gigi (1958 film)|Gigi]]'' that MGM was best known for. MGM\u2019s success led to six working studio complexes, more than {{convert|180|acre|km2}} including twenty-eight soundstages&nbsp;\u2013 Stage 15 is the second largest sound stage in the world, and Stage 27 served as \"Munchkinland\" in the production of ''The Wizard of Oz''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn addition to the main production building, MGM added two large backlot facilities&nbsp;\u2013 Lot 2 located opposite the main studio across Overland Avenue. Lot 3 entered the corner of Jefferson Boulevard and Overland Avenue and was MGM\u2019s largest backlot. The administration building was inaugurated in 1938 and was named for Thalberg.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nHowever, the [[United States v. Paramount Pictures, Inc.]] antitrust case of 1948 severed MGM's connection with Loews Theaters, and it struggled through its affairs. In 1969, millionaire [[Kirk Kerkorian]] bought MGM and proceeded to dismantle the studio. MGM\u2019s film memorabilia was sold through an 18-day auction, and {{convert|38|acre|m2}} of the studio\u2019s backlots were sold. Lot 3 was razed while Lot 2 was sold to housing developments. Kerkorian used the money to construct his hotel chain, the [[MGM Resorts International|MGM Grand Hotel]]s.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn 1981, Kerkorian's [[Tracinda Corporation]] acquired [[United Artists]] and merged it with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] to become MGM/UA Entertainment Co. He then sold MUEC to [[Ted Turner]] in 1986, who after 74 days, sold MGM/UA back to Kerkorian while retaining the pre-1986 MGM film library. In 1986, the studio lot was sold to [[Lorimar-Telepictures]]. During that time, the MGM logo was removed from the studios and moved across the street to the Filmland Building (now known as Sony Pictures Plaza) before their 1992 move to Santa Monica and Century City and finally settling in Beverly Hills.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/1992/biz/news/mgm-out-sony-in-at-filmland-100429/|title=MGM out, Sony in at Filmland|last=Brennan|first=Judy|last2=Brennan|first2=Judy|date=1992-11-16|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== Columbia Studios/Sony Pictures Studios (1990-present)==\nIn early 1989, [[Warner Communications]] acquired [[Lorimar|Lorimar-Telepictures]]. Later that year, [[Sony]] hired producers [[Jon Peters]] and [[Peter Guber]] to run the company's newly acquired Columbia Pictures Entertainment unit, even though they had a contract with [[Warner Bros.]] To resolve this issue, Warner sold their Lorimar lot to Columbia, among other deals. Columbia had been sharing with Warner Bros. their studio lot in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] in a partnership called the Burbank Studios beginning in 1972. Sony sold its interest in the Burbank Studios as a result of the Guber-Peters issue.<ref>''Warner, Sony settle suit over producers'' (November 17, 1989). Los Angeles: [[Associated Press]].</ref>\n\nSony acquired the property, first renamed Columbia Studios, in poor condition and thereafter invested $100 million to renovate the studio complex. The property underwent a three-year comprehensive plan as it transitioned to the {{convert|45|acre|km2}} Sony Pictures Studios complex. The buildings, many of which still bore the names of MGM film luminaries such as Clark Gable, Judy Garland, Rita Hayworth and Burt Lancaster, were painted and upgraded. New walls were erected around the lot and the ironwork gates were restored. Nostalgic art deco and false fronts on Main Street were added, as well as hand-painted murals of Columbia film posters. The MGM logo was removed from the Filmland Building in late 1992.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe studio continues to record TV shows such as ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'', ''[[Ray Donovan]]'', and ''[[Shark Tank]]''. The long-running game shows ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' and ''[[Wheel of Fortune (U.S. game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'' and its spin-offs are also taped at Sony Pictures Studios. The revival of ''[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|American Gladiators]]'' produced by [[MGM Television]] was also taped there.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n== Taped programs ==\n=== Talk shows ===\n* ''[[Donny & Marie (1998 TV series)|Donny & Marie]]'' (1998\u20132000)\n* ''[[The Queen Latifah Show]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[Chelsea (TV series)|Chelsea]]'' (2016\u20132017)\n\n=== Game shows ===\n* ''[[Wheel of Fortune (U.S. game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n* ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' (1994\u2013present)\n* ''[[Wheel 2000]]'' (1997\u20131998)\n* ''[[Jep!]]'' (1998\u20131999)\n* ''[[Rock & Roll Jeopardy!]]'' (1998\u20132001)\n* ''[[Pyramid (game show)|Pyramid]]'' (2002\u20132004)\n* ''[[Russian Roulette (game show)|Russian Roulette]]'' (2002\u20132003)\n* ''[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|American Gladiators]]'' (2008 revival, Season 1 only)\n* ''[[Sports Jeopardy!]]'' (2015\u20132016)\n* ''[[The Joker's Wild]]'' (2017\u2013present)\n\n=== Sitcoms ===\n* ''[[Cavemen (TV series)|Cavemen]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The King of Queens]]'' (1998\u20132007)\n* ''[[Living With Fran]]'' (2005\u20132006)\n* ''[[Married... with Children]]'' (1994\u20131997)\n* ''[[That's My Bush!]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'' (2007\u20132013)\n* ''[['Til Death]]'' (2006\u20132010)\n* ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'' (2013\u2013present)\n* ''[[Dr. Ken]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[One Day at a Time (2017 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'' (2017\u2013present)\n* ''[[Live in Front of a Studio Audience: Norman Lear's All in the Family and The Jeffersons]]'' (2019 special event)\n\n=== Dramas ===\n* ''[[Close to Home (2005 TV series)|Close to Home]]'' (2005\u20132007)\n* ''[[The Guardian (TV series)|The Guardian]]'' (2001\u20132004)\n* ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]'' (2003\u20132005)\n* ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'' (2003\u20132008)\n* ''[[Party of Five]]'' (1994\u20132000)\n* ''[[Masters of Sex]]'' (2013\u20132016)\n* ''[[Ray Donovan (TV series)|Ray Donovan]]'' (2013\u20132020)\n* ''[[Insecure (TV series)|Insecure]]'' (2016\u2013present)\n\n=== Reality ===\n* ''[[Shark Tank]]'' (2014\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Gong Show]]'' (2017\u20132018)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|Los Angeles}}\n* [http://www.sonypicturesstudios.com/ Sony Pictures Studios]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150205172234/http://www.sonypicturesmuseum.com/studio/lothistory Studio Lot History]\n* [http://www.sonypicturespost.com/ SPE Post Production]\n\n{{Sony Corp}}\n{{coord|34|1|2|N|118|24|6|W|region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Sony Pictures Entertainment|Studios]]\n[[Category:American film studios]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Television studios in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = Sony Pictures Studios\n| native_name. = \n| former_names = {{plainlist|\n* Inceville Studios (1912-1915)\n* Triangle Studios (1915-1919)\n* Goldwyn Studios (1919-1924)\n* Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer  Studios (1924-1986) \n* Lorimar Telepictures Studios (1986-1989)\n* Lorimar Studios (1989-1990)\n* Columbia Studios (1990-1991)\n}}\n| alternate_names = \n| image = Sony Pictures Entertainment entrance 1.jpg\n| caption = Overland Gate / West entrance&nbsp;\u2013 the entrance to Sony Pictures Studios\n| location = [[Culver City, California]], [[United States]]\n| address = 10202 West Washington Boulevard\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.017222|-118.401667|display=inline}}\n| start_date = \n| completion_date = \n| inauguration_date = 1912 as Inceville\n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = \n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]([[Sony]])\n| cost = \n| floor_area = \n| floor_count = \n| awards = \n| ren_awards = \n| references = \n| map_type = United States Los Angeles Western\n| map_caption = Location within Western Los Angeles\n| altitude = \n| building_type = Film and television studios\n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| ren_cost = \n| client = \n| current_tenants = [[Columbia Pictures]]<br />[[TriStar Pictures]]<br />[[Screen Gems]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Animation]]<br />[[Destination Films]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Imageworks]]<br />[[Stage 6 Films]]<br />[[Affirm Films]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Worldwide Acquisitions]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]]<br />[[Sony Pictures Television]]<br />[[TriStar Television]]<br />[[Ghost Corps]]<br />[[Happy Madison Productions]]\n\n| renovation_date = \n| height = \n| other_dimensions = \n| architecture_firm = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer = \n| civil_engineer = \n| other_designers = \n| quantity_surveyor = \n| main_contractor = \n| ren_architect = \n| ren_firm = \n| ren_str_engineer = \n| ren_serv_engineer = \n| ren_civ_engineer = \n| ren_oth_designers = \n| ren_qty_surveyor = \n| diameter = \n}}\nThe '''Sony Pictures Studios''' is an American television and film studio complex located in [[Culver City, California]] at 10202 West Washington Boulevard and bounded by Culver Boulevard (south), Washington Boulevard (north), Overland Avenue (west) and Madison Avenue (east). Founded in 1912, the facility is currently owned by [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] and houses the division's film studios, such as [[Columbia Pictures]], [[TriStar Pictures]], and [[Screen Gems]]. The complex was the original studios of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] from 1924 to 1986 and [[Lorimar-Telepictures]] from 1986 to 1989.\n\nIn addition to films shot at the facility, several television shows have been broadcast live or taped there. The lot, which is open to the public for daily studio tours, currently houses a total of sixteen separate [[sound stage]]s.\n\n== Early history (1912-1924)==\n[[Image:Triangle studios c.1916.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Photograph of original colonnade of [[Triangle Film Corporation|Triangle Studios]]. c. 1916]]\nDirector [[Thomas H. Ince]] built his pioneering '''Inceville''' studios in [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]] in 1912. While Ince was filming at [[Ballona Creek]] in 1915, [[Harry Culver]], the founding father of Culver City, persuaded Ince to move Inceville  to Culver City. During that time, Ince co-founded [[Triangle Film Corporation]] and the Triangle Studios was opened in the form of a Greek [[colonnade]]&nbsp;\u2013 the entrance to the studios. The colonnade still stands fronting Washington Boulevard and is a Culver City historical landmark.\n\nInce added a few stages and an Administration Building before selling out to his partners [[D.W. Griffith]] and [[Mack Sennett]]. Ince relocated down the street and built the [[Culver Studios]] at that location. In 1918, Triangle Studios was sold to film producer [[Samuel Goldwyn]]. Goldwyn also added a few sound stages before selling his shares in Goldwyn Studios.\n\n== The Historic MGM Studios/Lorimar-Telepictures Studios/Lorimar Studios (1924-1990)==\n[[Image:MGM-studios-1922.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Aerial shot of Goldwyn Studios c. 1922]]\n{{main|Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer}}\nIn 1924, [[Loews Theatres]] President [[Marcus Loew]] organized the [[merger]] of three film companies&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Metro Pictures Corporation]], Goldwyn Studios and Louis B. Mayer Productions to form [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and occupying the Goldwyn production facilities. {{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]], MGM Studios was responsible for shooting 52 films a year, from screen [[Epic film|epics]] such as ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'', and ''[[Mutiny on the Bounty (1962 film)|Mutiny on the Bounty]]'', to drawing-room dramas such as ''[[Grand Hotel (1932 film)|Grand Hotel]]'', ''[[Dinner at Eight (1933 film)|Dinner At Eight]]'', and ''[[Anna Karenina]]''. But it was the [[Technicolor]] [[musical film|musicals]], including ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain]]'' and ''[[Gigi (1958 film)|Gigi]]'' that MGM was best known for. MGM\u2019s success led to six working studio complexes, more than {{convert|180|acre|km2}} including twenty-eight soundstages&nbsp;\u2013 Stage 15 is the second largest sound stage in the world, and Stage 27 served as \"Munchkinland\" in the production of ''The Wizard of Oz''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn addition to the main production building, MGM added two large backlot facilities&nbsp;\u2013 Lot 2 located opposite the main studio across Overland Avenue. Lot 3 entered the corner of Jefferson Boulevard and Overland Avenue and was MGM\u2019s largest backlot. The administration building was inaugurated in 1938 and was named for Thalberg.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nHowever, the [[United States v. Paramount Pictures, Inc.]] antitrust case of 1948 severed MGM's connection with Loews Theaters, and it struggled through its affairs. In 1969, millionaire [[Kirk Kerkorian]] bought MGM and proceeded to dismantle the studio. MGM\u2019s film memorabilia was sold through an 18-day auction, and {{convert|38|acre|m2}} of the studio\u2019s backlots were sold. Lot 3 was razed while Lot 2 was sold to housing developments. Kerkorian used the money to construct his hotel chain, the [[MGM Resorts International|MGM Grand Hotel]]s.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nIn 1981, Kerkorian's [[Tracinda Corporation]] acquired [[United Artists]] and merged it with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] to become MGM/UA Entertainment Co. He then sold MUEC to [[Ted Turner]] in 1986, who after 74 days, sold MGM/UA back to Kerkorian while retaining the pre-1986 MGM film library. In 1986, the studio lot was sold to [[Lorimar-Telepictures]]. During that time, the MGM logo was removed from the studios and moved across the street to the Filmland Building (now known as Sony Pictures Plaza) before their 1992 move to Santa Monica and Century City and finally settling in Beverly Hills.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/1992/biz/news/mgm-out-sony-in-at-filmland-100429/|title=MGM out, Sony in at Filmland|last=Brennan|first=Judy|last2=Brennan|first2=Judy|date=1992-11-16|work=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== Columbia Studios/Sony Pictures Studios (1990-present)==\nIn early 1989, [[Warner Communications]] acquired [[Lorimar|Lorimar-Telepictures]]. Later that year, [[Sony]] hired producers [[Jon Peters]] and [[Peter Guber]] to run the company's newly acquired Columbia Pictures Entertainment unit, even though they had a contract with [[Warner Bros.]] To resolve this issue, Warner sold their Lorimar lot to Columbia, among other deals. Columbia had been sharing with Warner Bros. their studio lot in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] in a partnership called the Burbank Studios beginning in 1972. Sony sold its interest in the Burbank Studios as a result of the Guber-Peters issue.<ref>''Warner, Sony settle suit over producers'' (November 17, 1989). Los Angeles: [[Associated Press]].</ref>\n\nSony acquired the property, first renamed Columbia Studios, in poor condition and thereafter invested $100 million to renovate the studio complex. The property underwent a three-year comprehensive plan as it transitioned to the {{convert|45|acre|km2}} Sony Pictures Studios complex. The buildings, many of which still bore the names of MGM film luminaries such as Clark Gable, Judy Garland, Rita Hayworth and Burt Lancaster, were painted and upgraded. New walls were erected around the lot and the ironwork gates were restored. Nostalgic art deco and false fronts on Main Street were added, as well as hand-painted murals of Columbia film posters. The MGM logo was removed from the Filmland Building in late 1992.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nThe studio continues to record TV shows such as ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'', ''[[Ray Donovan]]'', and ''[[Shark Tank]]''. The long-running game shows ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' and ''[[Wheel of Fortune (U.S. game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'' and its spin-offs are also taped at Sony Pictures Studios. The revival of ''[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|American Gladiators]]'' produced by [[MGM Television]] was also taped there.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n== Taped programs ==\n=== Talk shows ===\n* ''[[Donny & Marie (1998 TV series)|Donny & Marie]]'' (1998\u20132000)\n* ''[[The Queen Latifah Show]]'' (2013\u20132015)\n* ''[[Chelsea (TV series)|Chelsea]]'' (2016\u20132017)\n\n=== Game shows ===\n* ''[[Wheel of Fortune (U.S. game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'' (1995\u2013present)\n* ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' (1994\u2013present)\n* ''[[Wheel 2000]]'' (1997\u20131998)\n* ''[[Jep!]]'' (1998\u20131999)\n* ''[[Rock & Roll Jeopardy!]]'' (1998\u20132001)\n* ''[[Pyramid (game show)|Pyramid]]'' (2002\u20132004)\n* ''[[Russian Roulette (game show)|Russian Roulette]]'' (2002\u20132003)\n* ''[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|American Gladiators]]'' (2008 revival, Season 1 only)\n* ''[[Sports Jeopardy!]]'' (2015\u20132016)\n* ''[[The Joker's Wild]]'' (2017\u2013present)\n\n=== Sitcoms ===\n* ''[[Cavemen (TV series)|Cavemen]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The King of Queens]]'' (1998\u20132007)\n* ''[[Living With Fran]]'' (2005\u20132006)\n* ''[[Married... with Children]]'' (1994\u20131997)\n* ''[[That's My Bush!]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'' (2007\u20132013)\n* ''[['Til Death]]'' (2006\u20132010)\n* ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'' (2013\u2013present)\n* ''[[Dr. Ken]]'' (2015\u20132017)\n* ''[[One Day at a Time (2017 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'' (2017\u2013present)\n* ''[[Live in Front of a Studio Audience: Norman Lear's All in the Family and The Jeffersons]]'' (2019 special event)\n\n=== Dramas ===\n* ''[[Close to Home (2005 TV series)|Close to Home]]'' (2005\u20132007)\n* ''[[The Guardian (TV series)|The Guardian]]'' (2001\u20132004)\n* ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]'' (2003\u20132005)\n* ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'' (2003\u20132008)\n* ''[[Party of Five]]'' (1994\u20132000)\n* ''[[Masters of Sex]]'' (2013\u20132016)\n* ''[[Ray Donovan (TV series)|Ray Donovan]]'' (2013\u20132020)\n* ''[[Insecure (TV series)|Insecure]]'' (2016\u2013present)\n\n=== Reality ===\n* ''[[Shark Tank]]'' (2014\u2013present)\n* ''[[The Gong Show]]'' (2017\u20132018)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|Los Angeles}}\n* [http://www.sonypicturesstudios.com/ Sony Pictures Studios]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150205172234/http://www.sonypicturesmuseum.com/studio/lothistory Studio Lot History]\n* [http://www.sonypicturespost.com/ SPE Post Production]\n\n{{Sony Corp}}\n{{coord|34|1|2|N|118|24|6|W|region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Sony Pictures Entertainment|Studios]]\n[[Category:American film studios]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1912]]\n[[Category:Television studios in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Lord Cornwallis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sony_Pictures_Studios"}
{"title_page": "Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2019}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n\n[[File:Angl-NZ-Waikato-Arms.svg|thumb|upright|Arms of the Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki]]\n\nThe '''Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki''' is one of the thirteen [[diocese]]s and ''hui amorangi'' (Maori Dioceses) of the [[Anglican Church in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia]].<ref>[http://www.anglican.org.nz/About About] from Anglican Church in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia, 8 September 2011</ref> The diocese covers the area from the [[Waikato]] to the area surrounding [[Mount Taranaki]] on the [[north island]] of [[New Zealand]].\n\nThe diocese was established in 1926 as the '''Diocese of Waikato''', with [[Cecil Arthur Cherrington]] being the first bishop. In 2010, the name of the diocese was changed to the Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki. This reflects the structure of the diocese (since 2008), with two bishoprics and two co-ordinary (presiding) bishops.<ref>[http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/ Welcome] from Anglican Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki, retrieved 8 September 2011</ref>\n\nThe seat of the Bishop of Waikato is at [[St. Peter's Cathedral, Hamilton, New Zealand|St Peter's Cathedral]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]. The current Bishop of Waikato is [[Helen-Ann Hartley]].\n\nThe seat of the [[Bishop of Taranaki]] is at the Taranaki Cathedral Church of St Mary. The incumbent Bishop of Taranaki is [[Philip Richardson (bishop)|Philip Richardson]] (who has been the archbishop of the New Zealand dioceses since 1 May 2013).<ref>[http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/content/3/ About] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113104252/http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/content/3/ |date=2015-01-13 }} from WaikatoTaranakiAnglican.org.nz, retrieved 19 December 2014</ref> Richardson had previously been the only suffragan Bishop in Taranaki in the Waikato diocese from 1999 until the co-diocesan arrangement started in 2008.<ref>[http://www.bishopsactionfoundation.org.nz/page/the-beginning-of-the-story/4/16/ The Bishop's Action Foundation \u2014 The beginning of the story...] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122130415/http://www.bishopsactionfoundation.org.nz/page/the-beginning-of-the-story/4/16/ |date=2016-01-22 }} (Accessed 27 July 2016)</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Waikato==\n* [[Cecil Cherrington]] (1926\u20131951)\n* [[John Holland (bishop)|John Holland]] (1951\u20131968)\n* [[Allen Johnston]] (1968\u20131980)\n* [[Brian Davis (bishop)|Brian Davis]] (1980\u20131986)\n* [[Roger Herft]] (1986\u20131993)\n* [[David Moxon]] (1993\u20132013; co-equal diocesan after 2008)\n* [[Helen-Ann Hartley]] (2014\u20132017; co-equal diocesan)<ref>{{cite news |last=Furrow |first=Gary |date=8 December 2017 |title=Bishop of Waikato says concluding her role 'a happy-sad time' |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/life-style/99387601/bishop-of-waikato-says-concluding-her-role-a-happysad-time?rm=m |access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n* ''vacant'' (2017\u2013present; Bishop of Taranaki acting)<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Libby |date=9 February 2018 |title=No new Anglican Bishop for the Waikato - Taranaki takes on the job |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/101056505/no-new-anglican-bishop-for-the-waikato--taranaki-takes-on-the-job |access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Taranaki==\n* [[Philip Richardson (bishop)|Philip Richardson]] (co-equal diocesan 2008\u2013present; previously suffragan Bishop in Taranaki, 1999\u20132008)\n\n==Parishes==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Piako===\n*[[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]]\n*[[Katikati]]\n*[[Mangakino]]\n*[[Matamata]]\n*[[Morrinsville]]\n*[[Paeroa]]\n*[[Putaruru]]\n*[[Tamahere]]\n*[[Te Aroha]]\n*[[Tirau]]\n*[[Tokoroa]]\n*[[Waihi]]\n*[[Waihi Beach]]\n*[[Whangamata]]\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Taranaki===\n*[[Bell Block, Taranaki, New Zealand|Bell Block]]\n*Brooklands\n*Eltham-Kaponga\n*Fitzroy\n*H\u0101wera\n*Inglewood\n*Manaia\n*[[Okato]]\n*[[Opunake]]\n*Patea\n*[[New Plymouth]]\n*[[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford]]\n*[[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]\n*Waverley-Waitotara\n*West [[New Plymouth]]\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Waikato===\n*Bryant Park\n*[[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] - St Peters Cathedral\n*Chartwell\n*Claudelands\n*Forest Lake - Holy Trinity Church\n*West Hamilton\n*Hamilton East\n*Hillcrest\n*Huntly\n*Melville\n*Nawton\n*[[Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia]]\n*[[Raglan, New Zealand|Raglan]]\n*Te Kauwhata\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Waitomo===\n*Kawhia\n*Orakau\n*Otorohanga\n*Piopio-Aria-Mokau\n*Taumarunui\n*[[Te Awamutu]]\n*Te Kuiti\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/ Diocese of Waikato & Taranaki website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216045001/http://www.stpeterscathedral.nzl.org/ St Peter's Cathedral website]\n\n{{Province of New Zealand}}\n\n{{coord|-37.791901|175.286484|region:NZ-WKO_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Anglican dioceses in New Zealand|Waikato]]\n[[Category:Waikato]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2019}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n\n[[File:Angl-NZ-Waikato-Arms.svg|thumb|upright|Arms of the Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki]]\n\nThe '''Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki''' is one of the thirteen [[diocese]]s and ''hui amorangi'' (Maori Dioceses) of the [[Anglican Church in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia]].<ref>[http://www.anglican.org.nz/About About] from Anglican Church in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia, 8 September 2011</ref> The diocese covers the area from the [[Waikato]] to the area surrounding [[Mount Taranaki]] on the [[north island]] of [[New Zealand]].\n\nThe diocese was established in 1926 as the '''Diocese of Waikato''', with [[Cecil Arthur Cherrington]] being the first bishop. In 2010, the name of the diocese was changed to the Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki. This reflects the structure of the diocese (since 2008), with two bishoprics and two co-ordinary (presiding) bishops.<ref>[http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/ Welcome] from Anglican Diocese of Waikato and Taranaki, retrieved 8 September 2011</ref>\n\nThe seat of the Bishop of Waikato is at [[St. Peter's Cathedral, Hamilton, New Zealand|St Peter's Cathedral]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]. The current Bishop of Waikato is [[Helen-Ann Hartley]].\n\nThe seat of the [[Bishop of Taranaki]] is at the Taranaki Cathedral Church of St Mary. The incumbent Bishop of Taranaki is [[Philip Richardson (bishop)|Philip Richardson]] (who has been the archbishop of the New Zealand dioceses since 1 May 2013).<ref>[http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/content/3/ About] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113104252/http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/content/3/ |date=2015-01-13 }} from WaikatoTaranakiAnglican.org.nz, retrieved 19 December 2014</ref> Richardson had previously been the only suffragan Bishop in Taranaki in the Waikato diocese from 1999 until the co-diocesan arrangement started in 2008.<ref>[http://www.bishopsactionfoundation.org.nz/page/the-beginning-of-the-story/4/16/ The Bishop's Action Foundation \u2014 The beginning of the story...] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122130415/http://www.bishopsactionfoundation.org.nz/page/the-beginning-of-the-story/4/16/ |date=2016-01-22 }} (Accessed 27 July 2016)</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Waikato==\n* [[Cecil Cherrington]] (1926\u20131951)\n* [[John Holland (bishop)|John Holland]] (1951\u20131968)\n* [[Allen Johnston]] (1968\u20131980)\n* [[Brian Davis (bishop)|Brian Davis]] (1980\u20131986)\n* [[Roger Herft]] (1986\u20131993)\n* [[David Moxon]] (1993\u20132013; co-equal diocesan after 2008)\n* [[Helen-Ann Hartley]] (2014\u20132017; co-equal diocesan)<ref>{{cite news |last=Furrow |first=Gary |date=8 December 2017 |title=Bishop of Waikato says concluding her role 'a happy-sad time' |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/life-style/99387601/bishop-of-waikato-says-concluding-her-role-a-happysad-time?rm=m |access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n* ''vacant'' (2017\u2013present; Bishop of Taranaki acting)<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Libby |date=9 February 2018 |title=No new Anglican Bishop for the Waikato - Taranaki takes on the job |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/101056505/no-new-anglican-bishop-for-the-waikato--taranaki-takes-on-the-job |access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Bishops of Taranaki==\n* [[Philip Richardson (bishop)|Philip Richardson]] (co-equal diocesan 2008\u2013present; previously suffragan Bishop in Taranaki, 1999\u20132008)\n\n==Parishes==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Piako===\n*[[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]]\n*[[Katikati]]\n*[[Mangakino]]\n*[[Matamata]]\n*[[Morrinsville]]\n*[[Paeroa]]\n*[[Putaruru]]\n*[[Tamahere]]\n*[[Te Aroha]]\n*[[Tirau]]\n*[[Tokoroa]]\n*[[Waihi]]\n*[[Waihi Beach]]\n*[[Whangamata]]\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Taranaki===\n*[[Bell Block, Taranaki, New Zealand|Bell Block]]\n*Brooklands\n*Eltham-Kaponga\n*Fitzroy\n*Hawera\n*Inglewood\n*Manaia\n*[[Okato]]\n*[[Opunake]]\n*Patea\n*[[New Plymouth]]\n*[[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford]]\n*[[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]]\n*Waverley-Waitotara\n*West [[New Plymouth]]\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Waikato===\n*Bryant Park\n*[[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] - St Peters Cathedral\n*Chartwell\n*Claudelands\n*Forest Lake - Holy Trinity Church\n*West Hamilton\n*Hamilton East\n*Hillcrest\n*Huntly\n*Melville\n*Nawton\n*[[Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia]]\n*[[Raglan, New Zealand|Raglan]]\n*Te Kauwhata\n{{col-4}}\n\n===Waitomo===\n*Kawhia\n*Orakau\n*Otorohanga\n*Piopio-Aria-Mokau\n*Taumarunui\n*[[Te Awamutu]]\n*Te Kuiti\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.waikatotaranakianglican.org.nz/ Diocese of Waikato & Taranaki website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216045001/http://www.stpeterscathedral.nzl.org/ St Peter's Cathedral website]\n\n{{Province of New Zealand}}\n\n{{coord|-37.791901|175.286484|region:NZ-WKO_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Anglican dioceses in New Zealand|Waikato]]\n[[Category:Waikato]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaranaki:clean up, replaced: Hawera \u2192 H\u0101wera as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diocese_of_Waikato_and_Taranaki"}
{"title_page": "Sherwin B. Nuland", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Sherwin B. Nuland\n|image             = Sherwin_B._Nuland.jpg\n|image_size        =\n|caption           =\n|birth_name=Shepsel Ber Nudelman \n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1930|12|08}}\n|birth_place       = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|2014|3|03|1930|12|08}}\n| death_place      = [[Hamden, Connecticut]], U.S.\n|fields            = [[Surgeon]], writer, educator\n|workplaces        = [[Yale School of Medicine]] \n|alma_mater        = [[Bronx High School of Science]]<br/> [[New York University]]<br/>Yale School of Medicine\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|academic_advisors =\n|doctoral_students =\n|notable_students  =\n|known_for         = ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter''\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|awards            = 1994 National Book Award\n|religion          =\n|children=4, including [[Victoria Nuland|Victoria]]\n|footnotes         =\n|spouse= Rhona L. Goulston (divorced)<br>{{marriage|Sarah Peterson|1977}}\n}}\n\n'''Sherwin Bernard Nuland'''<ref>[http://medicine.yale.edu/sherwin_nuland-2.profile?source=news Yale School of Medicine biography page] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140304222502/http://medicine.yale.edu/sherwin_nuland-2.profile?source=news |date=2014-03-04 }}</ref> (born '''Shepsel Ber Nudelman'''), December 8, 1930 \u2013 March 3, 2014, was an American [[surgeon]] and writer who taught [[bioethics]], [[history of medicine]], and [[medicine]] at the [[Yale School of Medicine]], and occasionally [[bioethics]] and [[history of medicine]] at Yale College. His 1994 book ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter'' was a \n[[New York Times Best Seller]] and won the [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]],<ref name=nba1994>\n[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1994 \"National Book Awards \u2013 1994\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2012-03-24.</ref> as well as being a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize]].\n\nIn 2011 Nuland was awarded the Jonathan Rhoads Gold Medal of the [[American Philosophical Society]], for \u201cDistinguished Service to Medicine.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://branford.yalecollege.yale.edu/sherwin-nuland |title=Sherwin Nuland &#124; Branford College |publisher=Branford.yalecollege.yale.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-12-17}}</ref>\n\nNuland wrote non-academic articles for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' and the ''[[New York Review of Books]]''.  He was a fellow of the [[Hastings Center]], an independent bioethics research institution.<ref>[http://www.thehastingscenter.org/About/Default.aspx?id=902 The Hastings Center] Hastings Center Fellows. Retrieved 2010-11-06.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nNuland was born Shepsel Ber Nudelman in [[The Bronx]], New York City, on December 8, 1930, to immigrant [[Ukrainian Jewish]] parents, Meyer (a garment repairman)<ref name=\"wos\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.webofstories.com/play/sherwin.nuland/8 |title=Sherwin Nuland&nbsp;\u2013 Physician&nbsp;\u2013 Why I Had to Change My Name |publisher=Web of Stories}}</ref> and Vitsche Nudelman.<ref name=obit>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/05/us/sherwin-b-nuland-author-who-challenged-concept-of-dignified-death-dies-at-83.html?hpw&rref=obituaries Sherwin B. Nuland, \u2018How We Die\u2019 Author, Dies at 83]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved 2014-03-04.</ref>\n\nAlthough raised in a traditional [[Orthodox Jew]]ish home, he came to consider himself [[agnostic]], but continued to attend [[synagogue]].<ref>Edward Hendrie, ''Solving the Mystery of Babylon the Great'' (Great Mountain, 2011), 148.</ref> As a Lithuanian Jew, he witnessed anti-Semitic discrimination against his cousin and changed his name when he applied to college to ensure admittance.<ref name=\"wos\" />\n\nNuland was a graduate of [[The Bronx High School of Science]], [[New York University]] and [[Yale School of Medicine]], where he obtained his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] degree and also completed a [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[surgery]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nAt the time of his death, he was living in [[Connecticut]] with his second wife, Sarah Nuland (n\u00e9e Peterson). He had four children, two from each marriage. His daughter [[Victoria Nuland]], a career [[foreign service officer]] and the former U.S. [[ambassador]] to [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]] and former spokesperson for the [[Department of State]], was appointed Assistant Secretary, Bureau of European and Eurasian Affairs in September, 2013.<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nDr. Nuland avowed a \u201cunique relationship\u201d with death. The 1994 National Book Award for nonfiction was granted to his ''How We Die: Reflections on Life\u2019s Final Chapter''.<ref>Emily Langer, \u201cSherwin B. Nuland, surgeon and writer who demystified death, dies at 83\u201d (''The Washington Post'', March 5, 2014).</ref>\n\nIn a 2001 [[TED (conference)|TED]] talk, which was released in October 2007, Nuland spoke of his severe [[Clinical depression|depression]] and obsessive thoughts in the early 1970s, probably caused by his difficult childhood and the dissolution of his first marriage. As drug therapy remained ineffective, a [[lobotomy]] was suggested, but his treating resident suggested [[Electroconvulsive therapy|electroshock therapy]] instead, which led to his recovery.<ref>[https://www.ted.com/talks/sherwin_nuland_on_electroshock_therapy \"Sherwin Nuland on Electroshock Therapy\"]. Filmed 2001, posted 2007. ''Talks''. TED: Ideas Worth Sharing. Retrieved 2012-03-24.</ref>  Twelve years after the talk, TED\u2019s Curator, Chris Anderson, recalled that Nuland's talk \u201cremains one of the most powerful moments in the conference\u2019s history.\u201d<ref>Emily McManus, \u201cRemembering Sherwin Nuland\u201d (TED Blog, March 6, 2014) at  http://blog.ted.com/2014/03/06/remembering-sherwin-nuland/.</ref>\n\nNuland was also one of the featured lecturers at [[One Day University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onedayu.com/events/detail/62 |title=One Day University |publisher=Onedayu.com |date=2013-04-21 |accessdate=2015-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Nuland produced a series of lectures for the Teaching Company\u2019s [[The Great Courses]] on the history of [[Western medicine]] titled ''Doctors: The History of Scientific Medicine Revealed Through Biography''.<ref>[http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/Courses/course_detail.aspx?cid=8128 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017051457/http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/Courses/course_detail.aspx?cid=8128 |date=October 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nNuland died on March 3, 2014, at his home in [[Hamden, Connecticut]], of [[prostate cancer]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* ''Doctors: The Biography of Medicine'' (New York: Knopf, 1988) {{ISBN|0-679-76009-1}}\n* ''Medicine: The Art of Healing'' (New York: Hugh Lauter Levin Associates, Inc.  Distributed by Macmillan, 1992) {{ISBN|0-88363-292-6}}\n* ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter'' (New York: Knopf: Distributed by Random House, 1994) {{ISBN|0-679-41461-4}}\n* ''The Wisdom of the Body'' (New York: Knopf, 1997) {{ISBN|0-679-44407-6}}\n* ''How We Live'' (New York: Vintage Books, 1998) [originally published as ''The Wisdom of the Body'' in 1997] {{ISBN|0-09-976761-9}}\n* ''Leonardo Da Vinci (Penguin Lives)'' (New York: Viking, 2000) {{ISBN|0-670-89391-9}}\n* ''The Mysteries Within: A Surgeon Explores Myth, Medicine, and the Human Body'' (New York: Simon & Schuster, 2000) {{ISBN|0-684-85486-4}}\n* ''The Doctors' Plague: Germs, Childbed Fever and the Strange Story of Ignac Semmelweis'' (New York: W.W. Norton, 2003) {{ISBN|0-393-05299-0}}\n* ''Lost in America: A Journey with My Father'' (New York: Knopf: Distributed by Random House, 2003) {{ISBN|0-375-41294-8}}\n* ''Maimonides (Jewish Encounters)'' (New York: Nextbook: Schocken, 2005) {{ISBN|0-8052-4200-7}}\n* ''The Art of Aging: A Doctor's Prescription for Well-Being'' (New York: Random House, 2007) {{ISBN|1-4000-6477-5}}\n* ''The Uncertain Art: Thoughts on a Life in Medicine'' (New York: Random House, 2008) {{ISBN|1-4000-6478-3}}\n* ''[[The Soul of Medicine: Tales from the Bedside]]'' (New York: Kaplan Publishing, 2009) {{ISBN|1-60714-055-1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|1207345}}\n* [http://www.webofstories.com/people/sherwin.nuland Sherwin B. Nuland tells his life story] (video)\n* [https://www.ted.com/talks/sherwin_nuland_on_electroshock_therapy Sherwin Nuland's 2001 TEDTalk], on the history of electroshock therapy and his personal experience with severe depression\n* [http://www.vimeo.com/5513031 Sherwin Nuland vs. Aubrey de Grey in a clip from the documentary, HOW TO LIVE FOREVER]\n* {{C-SPAN|Sherwin Nuland}}\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Nul ''In Depth'' interview with Nuland, October 2, 2005]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuland, Sherwin}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American medical historians]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:American skeptics]]\n[[Category:American surgeons]]\n[[Category:Deaths from prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Hastings Center Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jewish American scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish agnostics]]\n[[Category:National Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Medicine faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Sherwin B. Nuland\n|image             = Sherwin_B._Nuland.jpg\n|image_size        =\n|caption           =\n|birth_name=Shepsel Ber Nudelman \n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1930|12|08}}\n|birth_place       = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|2014|3|03|1930|12|08}}\n| death_place      = [[Hamden, Connecticut]], U.S.\n|fields            = [[Surgeon]], writer, educator\n|workplaces        = [[Yale School of Medicine]] \n|alma_mater        = [[Bronx High School of Science]]<br/> [[New York University]]<br/>Yale School of Medicine\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|academic_advisors =\n|doctoral_students =\n|notable_students  =\n|known_for         = ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter''\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|awards            = 1994 National Book Award\n|religion          =\n|children=4, including [[Victoria Nuland|Victoria]]\n|footnotes         =\n|spouse= Rhona L. Goulston (divorced)<br>{{marriage|Sarah Peterson|1977}}\n}}\n\n'''Sherwin Bernard Nuland'''<ref>[http://medicine.yale.edu/sherwin_nuland-2.profile?source=news Yale School of Medicine biography page] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140304222502/http://medicine.yale.edu/sherwin_nuland-2.profile?source=news |date=2014-03-04 }}</ref> (born '''Shepsel Ber Nudelman'''), December 8, 1930 \u2013 March 3, 2014, was an American [[surgeon]] and writer who taught [[bioethics]], [[history of medicine]], and [[medicine]] at the [[Yale School of Medicine]], and occasionally [[bioethics]] and [[history of medicine]] at Yale College. His 1994 book ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter'' was a \n[[New York Times Best Seller]] and won the [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]],<ref name=nba1994>\n[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1994 \"National Book Awards \u2013 1994\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2012-03-24.</ref> as well as being a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize]].\n\nIn 2011 Nuland was awarded the Jonathan Rhoads Gold Medal of the [[American Philosophical Society]], for \u201cDistinguished Service to Medicine.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://branford.yalecollege.yale.edu/sherwin-nuland |title=Sherwin Nuland &#124; Branford College |publisher=Branford.yalecollege.yale.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-12-17}}</ref>\n\nNuland wrote non-academic articles for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' and the ''[[New York Review of Books]]''.  He was a fellow of the [[Hastings Center]], an independent bioethics research institution.<ref>[http://www.thehastingscenter.org/About/Default.aspx?id=902 The Hastings Center] Hastings Center Fellows. Retrieved 2010-11-06.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nNuland was born Shepsel Ber Nudelman in [[The Bronx]], New York City, on December 8, 1930, to immigrant [[Ukrainian Jewish]] parents, Meyer (a garment repairman)<ref name=\"wos\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.webofstories.com/play/sherwin.nuland/8 |title=Sherwin Nuland&nbsp;\u2013 Physician&nbsp;\u2013 Why I Had to Change My Name |publisher=Web of Stories}}</ref> and Vitsche Nudelman.<ref name=obit>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/05/us/sherwin-b-nuland-author-who-challenged-concept-of-dignified-death-dies-at-83.html?hpw&rref=obituaries Sherwin B. Nuland, \u2018How We Die\u2019 Author, Dies at 83]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved 2014-03-04.</ref>\n\nAlthough raised in a traditional [[Orthodox Jew]]ish home, he came to consider himself [[agnostic]], but continued to attend [[synagogue]].<ref>Edward Hendrie, ''Solving the Mystery of Babylon the Great'' (Great Mountain, 2011), 148.</ref> As a Lithuanian Jew, he witnessed anti-Semitic discrimination against his cousin and changed his name when he applied to college to ensure admittance.<ref name=\"wos\" />\n\nNuland was a graduate of [[The Bronx High School of Science]], [[New York University]] and [[Yale School of Medicine]], where he obtained his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] degree and also completed a [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[surgery]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nAt the time of his death, he was living in [[Connecticut]] with his second wife, Sarah Nuland (n\u00e9e Peterson). He had four children, two from each marriage. His daughter [[Victoria Nuland]], a career [[foreign service officer]] and the former U.S. [[ambassador]] to [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]] and former spokesperson for the [[Department of State]], was appointed Assistant Secretary, Bureau of European and Eurasian Affairs in September, 2013.<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nDr. Nuland avowed a \u201cunique relationship\u201d with death. The 1994 National Book Award for nonfiction was granted to his ''How We Die: Reflections on Life\u2019s Final Chapter''.<ref>Emily Langer, \u201cSherwin B. Nuland, surgeon and writer who demystified death, dies at 83\u201d (''The Washington Post'', March 5, 2014).</ref>\n\nIn a 2001 [[TED (conference)|TED]] talk, which was released in October 2007, Nuland spoke of his severe [[Clinical depression|depression]] and obsessive thoughts in the early 1970s, probably caused by his difficult childhood and the dissolution of his first marriage. As drug therapy remained ineffective, a [[lobotomy]] was suggested, but his treating resident suggested [[Electroconvulsive therapy|electroshock therapy]] instead, which led to his recovery.<ref>[https://www.ted.com/talks/sherwin_nuland_on_electroshock_therapy \"Sherwin Nuland on Electroshock Therapy\"]. Filmed 2001, posted 2007. ''Talks''. TED: Ideas Worth Sharing. Retrieved 2012-03-24.</ref>  Twelve years after the talk, TED\u2019s Curator, Chris Anderson, recalled that Nuland's talk \u201cremains one of the most powerful moments in the conference\u2019s history.\u201d<ref>Emily McManus, \u201cRemembering Sherwin Nuland\u201d (TED Blog, March 6, 2014) at  http://blog.ted.com/2014/03/06/remembering-sherwin-nuland/.</ref>\n\nNuland was also one of the featured lecturers at [[One Day University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onedayu.com/events/detail/62 |title=One Day University |publisher=Onedayu.com |date=2013-04-21 |accessdate=2015-12-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Nuland produced a series of lectures for the Teaching Company\u2019s [[The Great Courses]] on the history of [[Western medicine]] titled ''Doctors: The History of Scientific Medicine Revealed Through Biography''.<ref>[http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/Courses/course_detail.aspx?cid=8128 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017051457/http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/Courses/course_detail.aspx?cid=8128 |date=October 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nNuland died on March 3, 2014, at his home in [[Hamden, Connecticut]], of [[prostate cancer]].<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* ''Doctors: The Biography of Medicine'' (New York: Knopf, 1988) {{ISBN|0-679-76009-1}}\n* ''Medicine: The Art of Healing'' (New York: Hugh Lauter Levin Associates, Inc.  Distributed by Macmillan, 1992) {{ISBN|0-88363-292-6}}\n* ''How We Die: Reflections on Life's Final Chapter'' (New York: Knopf: Distributed by Random House, 1994) {{ISBN|0-679-41461-4}}\n* ''The Wisdom of the Body'' (New York: Knopf, 1997) {{ISBN|0-679-44407-6}}\n* ''How We Live'' (New York: Vintage Books, 1998) [originally published as ''The Wisdom of the Body'' in 1997] {{ISBN|0-09-976761-9}}\n* ''Leonardo Da Vinci (Penguin Lives)'' (New York: Viking, 2000) {{ISBN|0-670-89391-9}}\n* ''The Mysteries Within: A Surgeon Explores Myth, Medicine, and the Human Body'' (New York: Simon & Schuster, 2000) {{ISBN|0-684-85486-4}}\n* ''The Doctors' Plague: Germs, Childbed Fever and the Strange Story of Ignac Semmelweis'' (New York: W.W. Norton, 2003) {{ISBN|0-393-05299-0}}\n* ''Lost in America: A Journey with My Father'' (New York: Knopf: Distributed by Random House, 2003) {{ISBN|0-375-41294-8}}\n* ''Maimonides (Jewish Encounters)'' (New York: Nextbook: Schocken, 2005) {{ISBN|0-8052-4200-7}}\n* ''The Art of Aging: A Doctor's Prescription for Well-Being'' (New York: Random House, 2007) {{ISBN|1-4000-6477-5}}\n* ''The Uncertain Art: Thoughts on a Life in Medicine'' (New York: Random House, 2008) {{ISBN|1-4000-6478-3}}\n* ''The Soul of Medicine'' (New York: Kaplan Publishing, 2009) {{ISBN|1-60714-055-1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|1207345}}\n* [http://www.webofstories.com/people/sherwin.nuland Sherwin B. Nuland tells his life story] (video)\n* [https://www.ted.com/talks/sherwin_nuland_on_electroshock_therapy Sherwin Nuland's 2001 TEDTalk], on the history of electroshock therapy and his personal experience with severe depression\n* [http://www.vimeo.com/5513031 Sherwin Nuland vs. Aubrey de Grey in a clip from the documentary, HOW TO LIVE FOREVER]\n* {{C-SPAN|Sherwin Nuland}}\n** [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/Nul ''In Depth'' interview with Nuland, October 2, 2005]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuland, Sherwin}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American medical historians]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:American skeptics]]\n[[Category:American surgeons]]\n[[Category:Deaths from prostate cancer]]\n[[Category:Hastings Center Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jewish American scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish agnostics]]\n[[Category:National Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Medicine faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Atlantic306", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherwin_B._Nuland"}
